cvs.texi(,10444) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,10445) @node log
cvs.texi(,10446) @appendixsec log---Print out log information for files
cvs.texi(,10447) @cindex log (subcommand)
cvs.texi(,10448) 
cvs.texi(,10449) @itemize @bullet
cvs.texi(,10450) @item
cvs.texi(,10451) Synopsis: log [options] [files@dots{}]
cvs.texi(,10452) @item
cvs.texi(,10453) Requires: repository, working directory.
cvs.texi(,10454) @item
cvs.texi(,10455) Changes: nothing.
cvs.texi(,10456) @end itemize
cvs.texi(,10457) 
cvs.texi(,10458) Display log information for files.  @code{log} used to
cvs.texi(,10459) call the @sc{rcs} utility @code{rlog}.  Although this
cvs.texi(,10460) is no longer true in the current sources, this history
cvs.texi(,10461) determines the format of the output and the options,
cvs.texi(,10462) which are not quite in the style of the other @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,10463) commands.
cvs.texi(,10464) 
cvs.texi(,10465) @cindex Timezone, in output
cvs.texi(,10466) @cindex Zone, time, in output
cvs.texi(,10467) @c Kind of a funny place to document the timezone used
cvs.texi(,10468) @c in output from commands other than @code{log}.
cvs.texi(,10469) @c There is also more we need to say about this,
cvs.texi(,10470) @c including what happens in a client/server environment.
cvs.texi(,10471) The output includes the location of the @sc{rcs} file,
cvs.texi(,10472) the @dfn{head} revision (the latest revision on the
cvs.texi(,10473) trunk), all symbolic names (tags) and some other
cvs.texi(,10474) things.  For each revision, the revision number, the
cvs.texi(,10475) author, the number of lines added/deleted and the log
cvs.texi(,10476) message are printed.  All times are displayed in
cvs.texi(,10477) Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).  (Other parts of
cvs.texi(,10478) @sc{cvs} print times in the local timezone).
cvs.texi(,10479) @c FIXCVS: need a better way to control the timezone
cvs.texi(,10480) @c used in output.  Previous/current versions of CVS did/do
cvs.texi(,10481) @c sometimes support -z in RCSINIT, and/or an
cvs.texi(,10482) @c undocumented (except by reference to 'rlog') -z option
cvs.texi(,10483) @c to cvs log, but this has not been a consistent,
cvs.texi(,10484) @c documented feature.  Perhaps a new global option,
cvs.texi(,10485) @c where LT means the client's timezone, which the
cvs.texi(,10486) @c client then communicates to the server, is the
cvs.texi(,10487) @c right solution.
cvs.texi(,10488) 
cvs.texi(,10489) @strong{Note: @code{log} uses @samp{-R} in a way that conflicts
cvs.texi(,10490) with the normal use inside @sc{cvs} (@pxref{Common options}).}
cvs.texi(,10491) 
cvs.texi(,10492) @menu
cvs.texi(,10493) * log options::                 log options
cvs.texi(,10494) * log examples::                log examples
cvs.texi(,10495) @end menu
cvs.texi(,10496) 
cvs.texi(,10497) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,10498) @node log options
cvs.texi(,10499) @appendixsubsec log options
cvs.texi(,10500) 
cvs.texi(,10501) By default, @code{log} prints all information that is
cvs.texi(,10502) available.  All other options restrict the output.
cvs.texi(,10503) 
cvs.texi(,10504) @table @code
cvs.texi(,10505) @item -b
cvs.texi(,10506) Print information about the revisions on the default
cvs.texi(,10507) branch, normally the highest branch on the trunk.
cvs.texi(,10508) 
cvs.texi(,10509) @item -d @var{dates}
cvs.texi(,10510) Print information about revisions with a checkin
cvs.texi(,10511) date/time in the range given by the
cvs.texi(,10512) semicolon-separated list of dates.  The date formats
cvs.texi(,10513) accepted are those accepted by the @samp{-D} option to
cvs.texi(,10514) many other @sc{cvs} commands (@pxref{Common options}).
cvs.texi(,10515) Dates can be combined into ranges as follows:
cvs.texi(,10516) 
cvs.texi(,10517) @c Should we be thinking about accepting ISO8601
cvs.texi(,10518) @c ranges?  For example "1972-09-10/1972-09-12".
cvs.texi(,10519) @table @code
cvs.texi(,10520) @item @var{d1}<@var{d2}
cvs.texi(,10521) @itemx @var{d2}>@var{d1}
cvs.texi(,10522) Select the revisions that were deposited between
cvs.texi(,10523) @var{d1} and @var{d2}.
cvs.texi(,10524) 
cvs.texi(,10525) @item <@var{d}
cvs.texi(,10526) @itemx @var{d}>
cvs.texi(,10527) Select all revisions dated @var{d} or earlier.
cvs.texi(,10528) 
cvs.texi(,10529) @item @var{d}<
cvs.texi(,10530) @itemx >@var{d}
cvs.texi(,10531) Select all revisions dated @var{d} or later.
cvs.texi(,10532) 
cvs.texi(,10533) @item @var{d}
cvs.texi(,10534) Select the single, latest revision dated @var{d} or
cvs.texi(,10535) earlier.
cvs.texi(,10536) @end table
cvs.texi(,10537) 
cvs.texi(,10538) The @samp{>} or @samp{<} characters may be followed by
cvs.texi(,10539) @samp{=} to indicate an inclusive range rather than an
cvs.texi(,10540) exclusive one.
cvs.texi(,10541) 
cvs.texi(,10542) Note that the separator is a semicolon (;).
cvs.texi(,10543) 
cvs.texi(,10544) @item -h
cvs.texi(,10545) Print only the name of the @sc{rcs} file, name
cvs.texi(,10546) of the file in the working directory, head,
cvs.texi(,10547) default branch, access list, locks, symbolic names, and
cvs.texi(,10548) suffix.
cvs.texi(,10549) 
cvs.texi(,10550) @item -l
cvs.texi(,10551) Local; run only in current working directory.  (Default
cvs.texi(,10552) is to run recursively).
cvs.texi(,10553) 
cvs.texi(,10554) @item -N
cvs.texi(,10555) Do not print the list of tags for this file.  This
cvs.texi(,10556) option can be very useful when your site uses a lot of
cvs.texi(,10557) tags, so rather than "more"'ing over 3 pages of tag
cvs.texi(,10558) information, the log information is presented without
cvs.texi(,10559) tags at all.
cvs.texi(,10560) 
cvs.texi(,10561) @item -R
cvs.texi(,10562) Print only the name of the @sc{rcs} file.
cvs.texi(,10563) 
cvs.texi(,10564) @c Note that using a bare revision (in addition to not
cvs.texi(,10565) @c being explicitly documented here) is potentially
cvs.texi(,10566) @c confusing; it shows the log message to get from the
cvs.texi(,10567) @c previous revision to that revision.  "-r1.3 -r1.6"
cvs.texi(,10568) @c (equivalent to "-r1.3,1.6") is even worse; it
cvs.texi(,10569) @c prints the messages to get from 1.2 to 1.3 and 1.5
cvs.texi(,10570) @c to 1.6.  By analogy with "cvs diff", users might
cvs.texi(,10571) @c expect that it is more like specifying a range.
cvs.texi(,10572) @c It is not 100% clear to me how much of this should
cvs.texi(,10573) @c be documented (for example, multiple -r options
cvs.texi(,10574) @c perhaps could/should be deprecated given the false
cvs.texi(,10575) @c analogy with "cvs diff").
cvs.texi(,10576) @c In general, this section should be rewritten to talk
cvs.texi(,10577) @c about messages to get from revision rev1 to rev2,
cvs.texi(,10578) @c rather than messages for revision rev2 (that is, the
cvs.texi(,10579) @c messages are associated with a change not a static
cvs.texi(,10580) @c revision and failing to make this distinction causes
cvs.texi(,10581) @c much confusion).
cvs.texi(,10582) @item -r@var{revisions}
cvs.texi(,10583) Print information about revisions given in the
cvs.texi(,10584) comma-separated list @var{revisions} of revisions and
cvs.texi(,10585) ranges.  The following table explains the available
cvs.texi(,10586) range formats:
cvs.texi(,10587) 
cvs.texi(,10588) @table @code
cvs.texi(,10589) @item @var{rev1}:@var{rev2}
cvs.texi(,10590) Revisions @var{rev1} to @var{rev2} (which must be on
cvs.texi(,10591) the same branch).
cvs.texi(,10592) 
cvs.texi(,10593) @item @var{rev1}::@var{rev2}
cvs.texi(,10594) The same, but excluding @var{rev1}.
cvs.texi(,10595) 
cvs.texi(,10596) @item :@var{rev}
cvs.texi(,10597) @itemx ::@var{rev}
cvs.texi(,10598) Revisions from the beginning of the branch up to
cvs.texi(,10599) and including @var{rev}.
cvs.texi(,10600) 
cvs.texi(,10601) @item @var{rev}:
cvs.texi(,10602) Revisions starting with @var{rev} to the end of the
cvs.texi(,10603) branch containing @var{rev}.
cvs.texi(,10604) 
cvs.texi(,10605) @item @var{rev}::
cvs.texi(,10606) Revisions starting just after @var{rev} to the end of the
cvs.texi(,10607) branch containing @var{rev}.
cvs.texi(,10608) 
cvs.texi(,10609) @item @var{branch}
cvs.texi(,10610) An argument that is a branch means all revisions on
cvs.texi(,10611) that branch.
cvs.texi(,10612) 
cvs.texi(,10613) @item @var{branch1}:@var{branch2}
cvs.texi(,10614) @itemx @var{branch1}::@var{branch2}
cvs.texi(,10615) A range of branches means all revisions
cvs.texi(,10616) on the branches in that range.
cvs.texi(,10617) 
cvs.texi(,10618) @item @var{branch}.
cvs.texi(,10619) The latest revision in @var{branch}.
cvs.texi(,10620) @end table
cvs.texi(,10621) 
cvs.texi(,10622) A bare @samp{-r} with no revisions means the latest
cvs.texi(,10623) revision on the default branch, normally the trunk.
cvs.texi(,10624) There can be no space between the @samp{-r} option and
cvs.texi(,10625) its argument.
cvs.texi(,10626) 
cvs.texi(,10627) @item -S
cvs.texi(,10628) Suppress the header if no revisions are selected.
cvs.texi(,10629) 
cvs.texi(,10630) @item -s @var{states}
cvs.texi(,10631) Print information about revisions whose state
cvs.texi(,10632) attributes match one of the states given in the
cvs.texi(,10633) comma-separated list @var{states}.
cvs.texi(,10634) 
cvs.texi(,10635) @item -t
cvs.texi(,10636) Print the same as @samp{-h}, plus the descriptive text.
cvs.texi(,10637) 
cvs.texi(,10638) @item -w@var{logins}
cvs.texi(,10639) Print information about revisions checked in by users
cvs.texi(,10640) with login names appearing in the comma-separated list
cvs.texi(,10641) @var{logins}.  If @var{logins} is omitted, the user's
cvs.texi(,10642) login is assumed.  There can be no space between the
cvs.texi(,10643) @samp{-w} option and its argument.
cvs.texi(,10644) @end table
cvs.texi(,10645) 
cvs.texi(,10646) @code{log} prints the intersection of the revisions
cvs.texi(,10647) selected with the options @samp{-d}, @samp{-s}, and
cvs.texi(,10648) @samp{-w}, intersected with the union of the revisions
cvs.texi(,10649) selected by @samp{-b} and @samp{-r}.
cvs.texi(,10650) 
cvs.texi(,10651) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,10652) @node log examples
cvs.texi(,10653) @appendixsubsec log examples
cvs.texi(,10654) 
cvs.texi(,10655) Contributed examples are gratefully accepted.
cvs.texi(,10656) 
cvs.texi(,10657) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,10658) @node rdiff
cvs.texi(,10659) @appendixsec rdiff---'patch' format diffs between releases
cvs.texi(,10660) @cindex rdiff (subcommand)
cvs.texi(,10661) 
cvs.texi(,10662) @itemize @bullet
cvs.texi(,10663) @item
cvs.texi(,10664) rdiff [-flags] [-V vn] [-r t|-D d [-r t2|-D d2]] modules@dots{}
cvs.texi(,10665) @item
cvs.texi(,10666) Requires: repository.
cvs.texi(,10667) @item
cvs.texi(,10668) Changes: nothing.
cvs.texi(,10669) @item
cvs.texi(,10670) Synonym: patch
cvs.texi(,10671) @end itemize
cvs.texi(,10672) 
cvs.texi(,10673) Builds a Larry Wall format patch(1) file between two
cvs.texi(,10674) releases, that can be fed directly into the @code{patch}
cvs.texi(,10675) program to bring an old release up-to-date with the new
cvs.texi(,10676) release.  (This is one of the few @sc{cvs} commands that
cvs.texi(,10677) operates directly from the repository, and doesn't
cvs.texi(,10678) require a prior checkout.) The diff output is sent to
cvs.texi(,10679) the standard output device.
cvs.texi(,10680) 
cvs.texi(,10681) You can specify (using the standard @samp{-r} and
cvs.texi(,10682) @samp{-D} options) any combination of one or two
cvs.texi(,10683) revisions or dates.  If only one revision or date is
cvs.texi(,10684) specified, the patch file reflects differences between
cvs.texi(,10685) that revision or date and the current head revisions in
cvs.texi(,10686) the @sc{rcs} file.
cvs.texi(,10687) 
cvs.texi(,10688) Note that if the software release affected is contained
cvs.texi(,10689) in more than one directory, then it may be necessary to
cvs.texi(,10690) specify the @samp{-p} option to the @code{patch} command when
cvs.texi(,10691) patching the old sources, so that @code{patch} is able to find
cvs.texi(,10692) the files that are located in other directories.
cvs.texi(,10693) 
cvs.texi(,10694) @menu
cvs.texi(,10695) * rdiff options::               rdiff options
cvs.texi(,10696) * rdiff examples::              rdiff examples
cvs.texi(,10697) @end menu
cvs.texi(,10698) 
cvs.texi(,10699) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,10700) @node rdiff options
cvs.texi(,10701) @appendixsubsec rdiff options
cvs.texi(,10702) 
cvs.texi(,10703) These standard options are supported by @code{rdiff}
cvs.texi(,10704) (@pxref{Common options}, for a complete description of
cvs.texi(,10705) them):
cvs.texi(,10706) 
cvs.texi(,10707) @table @code
cvs.texi(,10708) @item -D @var{date}
cvs.texi(,10709) Use the most recent revision no later than @var{date}.
cvs.texi(,10710) 
cvs.texi(,10711) @item -f
cvs.texi(,10712) If no matching revision is found, retrieve the most
cvs.texi(,10713) recent revision (instead of ignoring the file).
cvs.texi(,10714) 
cvs.texi(,10715) @item -l
cvs.texi(,10716) Local; don't descend subdirectories.
cvs.texi(,10717) 
cvs.texi(,10718) @item -R
cvs.texi(,10719) Examine directories recursively.  This option is on by default.
cvs.texi(,10720) 
cvs.texi(,10721) @item -r @var{tag}
cvs.texi(,10722) Use revision @var{tag}.
cvs.texi(,10723) @end table
cvs.texi(,10724) 
cvs.texi(,10725) In addition to the above, these options are available:
cvs.texi(,10726) 
cvs.texi(,10727) @table @code
cvs.texi(,10728) @item -c
cvs.texi(,10729) Use the context diff format.  This is the default format.
cvs.texi(,10730) 
cvs.texi(,10731) @item -s
cvs.texi(,10732) Create a summary change report instead of a patch.  The
cvs.texi(,10733) summary includes information about files that were
cvs.texi(,10734) changed or added between the releases.  It is sent to
cvs.texi(,10735) the standard output device.  This is useful for finding
cvs.texi(,10736) out, for example, which files have changed between two
cvs.texi(,10737) dates or revisions.
cvs.texi(,10738) 
cvs.texi(,10739) @item -t
cvs.texi(,10740) A diff of the top two revisions is sent to the standard
cvs.texi(,10741) output device.  This is most useful for seeing what the
cvs.texi(,10742) last change to a file was.
cvs.texi(,10743) 
cvs.texi(,10744) @item -u
cvs.texi(,10745) Use the unidiff format for the context diffs.
cvs.texi(,10746) Remember that old versions
cvs.texi(,10747) of the @code{patch} program can't handle the unidiff
cvs.texi(,10748) format, so if you plan to post this patch to the net
cvs.texi(,10749) you should probably not use @samp{-u}.
cvs.texi(,10750) 
cvs.texi(,10751) @item -V @var{vn}
cvs.texi(,10752) Expand keywords according to the rules current in
cvs.texi(,10753) @sc{rcs} version @var{vn} (the expansion format changed with
cvs.texi(,10754) @sc{rcs} version 5).  Note that this option is no
cvs.texi(,10755) longer accepted.  @sc{cvs} will always expand keywords the
cvs.texi(,10756) way that @sc{rcs} version 5 does.
cvs.texi(,10757) @end table
cvs.texi(,10758) 
cvs.texi(,10759) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,10760) @node rdiff examples
cvs.texi(,10761) @appendixsubsec rdiff examples
cvs.texi(,10762) 
cvs.texi(,10763) Suppose you receive mail from @t{foo@@example.net} asking for an
cvs.texi(,10764) update from release 1.2 to 1.4 of the tc compiler.  You
cvs.texi(,10765) have no such patches on hand, but with @sc{cvs} that can
cvs.texi(,10766) easily be fixed with a command such as this:
cvs.texi(,10767) 
cvs.texi(,10768) @example
cvs.texi(,10769) $ cvs rdiff -c -r FOO1_2 -r FOO1_4 tc | \
cvs.texi(,10770) $$ Mail -s 'The patches you asked for' foo@@example.net
cvs.texi(,10771) @end example
cvs.texi(,10772) 
cvs.texi(,10773) Suppose you have made release 1.3, and forked a branch
cvs.texi(,10774) called @samp{R_1_3fix} for bugfixes.  @samp{R_1_3_1}
cvs.texi(,10775) corresponds to release 1.3.1, which was made some time
cvs.texi(,10776) ago.  Now, you want to see how much development has been
cvs.texi(,10777) done on the branch.  This command can be used:
cvs.texi(,10778) 
cvs.texi(,10779) @example
cvs.texi(,10780) $ cvs patch -s -r R_1_3_1 -r R_1_3fix module-name
cvs.texi(,10781) cvs rdiff: Diffing module-name
cvs.texi(,10782) File ChangeLog,v changed from revision 1.52.2.5 to 1.52.2.6
cvs.texi(,10783) File foo.c,v changed from revision 1.52.2.3 to 1.52.2.4
cvs.texi(,10784) File bar.h,v changed from revision 1.29.2.1 to 1.2
cvs.texi(,10785) @end example
cvs.texi(,10786) 
cvs.texi(,10787) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,10788) @node release
cvs.texi(,10789) @appendixsec release---Indicate that a Module is no longer in use
cvs.texi(,10790) @cindex release (subcommand)
cvs.texi(,10791) 
cvs.texi(,10792) @itemize @bullet
cvs.texi(,10793) @item
cvs.texi(,10794) release [-d] directories@dots{}
cvs.texi(,10795) @item
cvs.texi(,10796) Requires: Working directory.
cvs.texi(,10797) @item
cvs.texi(,10798) Changes: Working directory, history log.
cvs.texi(,10799) @end itemize
cvs.texi(,10800) 
cvs.texi(,10801) This command is meant to safely cancel the effect of
cvs.texi(,10802) @samp{cvs checkout}.  Since @sc{cvs} doesn't lock files, it
cvs.texi(,10803) isn't strictly necessary to use this command.  You can
cvs.texi(,10804) always simply delete your working directory, if you
cvs.texi(,10805) like; but you risk losing changes you may have
cvs.texi(,10806) forgotten, and you leave no trace in the @sc{cvs} history
cvs.texi(,10807) file (@pxref{history file}) that you've abandoned your
cvs.texi(,10808) checkout.
cvs.texi(,10809) 
cvs.texi(,10810) Use @samp{cvs release} to avoid these problems.  This
cvs.texi(,10811) command checks that no uncommitted changes are
cvs.texi(,10812) present; that you are executing it from immediately
cvs.texi(,10813) above a @sc{cvs} working directory; and that the repository
cvs.texi(,10814) recorded for your files is the same as the repository
cvs.texi(,10815) defined in the module database.
cvs.texi(,10816) 
cvs.texi(,10817) If all these conditions are true, @samp{cvs release}
cvs.texi(,10818) leaves a record of its execution (attesting to your
cvs.texi(,10819) intentionally abandoning your checkout) in the @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,10820) history log.
cvs.texi(,10821) 
cvs.texi(,10822) @menu
cvs.texi(,10823) * release options::             release options
cvs.texi(,10824) * release output::              release output
cvs.texi(,10825) * release examples::            release examples
cvs.texi(,10826) @end menu
cvs.texi(,10827) 
cvs.texi(,10828) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,10829) @node release options
cvs.texi(,10830) @appendixsubsec release options
cvs.texi(,10831) 
cvs.texi(,10832) The @code{release} command supports one command option:
cvs.texi(,10833) 
cvs.texi(,10834) @table @code
cvs.texi(,10835) @item -d
cvs.texi(,10836) Delete your working copy of the file if the release
cvs.texi(,10837) succeeds.  If this flag is not given your files will
cvs.texi(,10838) remain in your working directory.
cvs.texi(,10839) 
cvs.texi(,10840) @strong{WARNING:  The @code{release} command deletes
cvs.texi(,10841) all directories and files recursively.  This
cvs.texi(,10842) has the very serious side-effect that any directory
cvs.texi(,10843) that you have created inside your checked-out sources,
cvs.texi(,10844) and not added to the repository (using the @code{add}
cvs.texi(,10845) command; @pxref{Adding files}) will be silently deleted---even
cvs.texi(,10846) if it is non-empty!}
cvs.texi(,10847) @end table
cvs.texi(,10848) 
cvs.texi(,10849) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,10850) @node release output
cvs.texi(,10851) @appendixsubsec release output
cvs.texi(,10852) 
cvs.texi(,10853) Before @code{release} releases your sources it will
cvs.texi(,10854) print a one-line message for any file that is not
cvs.texi(,10855) up-to-date.
cvs.texi(,10856) 
cvs.texi(,10857) @table @code
cvs.texi(,10858) @item U @var{file}
cvs.texi(,10859) @itemx P @var{file}
cvs.texi(,10860) There exists a newer revision of this file in the
cvs.texi(,10861) repository, and you have not modified your local copy
cvs.texi(,10862) of the file (@samp{U} and @samp{P} mean the same thing).
cvs.texi(,10863) 
cvs.texi(,10864) @item A @var{file}
cvs.texi(,10865) The file has been added to your private copy of the
cvs.texi(,10866) sources, but has not yet been committed to the
cvs.texi(,10867) repository.  If you delete your copy of the sources
cvs.texi(,10868) this file will be lost.
cvs.texi(,10869) 
cvs.texi(,10870) @item R @var{file}
cvs.texi(,10871) The file has been removed from your private copy of the
cvs.texi(,10872) sources, but has not yet been removed from the
cvs.texi(,10873) repository, since you have not yet committed the
cvs.texi(,10874) removal.  @xref{commit}.
cvs.texi(,10875) 
cvs.texi(,10876) @item M @var{file}
cvs.texi(,10877) The file is modified in your working directory.  There
cvs.texi(,10878) might also be a newer revision inside the repository.
cvs.texi(,10879) 
cvs.texi(,10880) @item ? @var{file}
cvs.texi(,10881) @var{file} is in your working directory, but does not
cvs.texi(,10882) correspond to anything in the source repository, and is
cvs.texi(,10883) not in the list of files for @sc{cvs} to ignore (see the
cvs.texi(,10884) description of the @samp{-I} option, and
cvs.texi(,10885) @pxref{cvsignore}).  If you remove your working
cvs.texi(,10886) sources, this file will be lost.
cvs.texi(,10887) @end table
cvs.texi(,10888) 
cvs.texi(,10889) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,10890) @node release examples
cvs.texi(,10891) @appendixsubsec release examples
cvs.texi(,10892) 
cvs.texi(,10893) Release the @file{tc} directory, and delete your local working copy
cvs.texi(,10894) of the files.
cvs.texi(,10895) 
cvs.texi(,10896) @example
cvs.texi(,10897) $ cd ..         # @r{You must stand immediately above the}
cvs.texi(,10898)                 # @r{sources when you issue @samp{cvs release}.}
cvs.texi(,10899) $ cvs release -d tc
cvs.texi(,10900) You have [0] altered files in this repository.
cvs.texi(,10901) Are you sure you want to release (and delete) directory `tc': y
cvs.texi(,10902) $
cvs.texi(,10903) @end example
cvs.texi(,10904) 
cvs.texi(,10905) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,10906) @node update
cvs.texi(,10907) @appendixsec update---Bring work tree in sync with repository
cvs.texi(,10908) @cindex update (subcommand)
cvs.texi(,10909) 
cvs.texi(,10910) @itemize @bullet
cvs.texi(,10911) @item
cvs.texi(,10912) update [-ACdflPpR] [-I name] [-j rev [-j rev]] [-k kflag] [-r tag|-D date] [-W spec] files@dots{}
cvs.texi(,10913) @item
cvs.texi(,10914) Requires: repository, working directory.
cvs.texi(,10915) @item
cvs.texi(,10916) Changes: working directory.
cvs.texi(,10917) @end itemize
cvs.texi(,10918) 
cvs.texi(,10919) After you've run checkout to create your private copy
cvs.texi(,10920) of source from the common repository, other developers
cvs.texi(,10921) will continue changing the central source.  From time
cvs.texi(,10922) to time, when it is convenient in your development
cvs.texi(,10923) process, you can use the @code{update} command from
cvs.texi(,10924) within your working directory to reconcile your work
cvs.texi(,10925) with any revisions applied to the source repository
cvs.texi(,10926) since your last checkout or update.  Without the @code{-C}
cvs.texi(,10927) option, @code{update} will also merge any differences
cvs.texi(,10928) between the local copy of files and their base revisions
cvs.texi(,10929) into any destination revisions specified with @code{-r},
cvs.texi(,10930) @code{-D}, or @code{-A}.
cvs.texi(,10931) 
cvs.texi(,10932) @menu
cvs.texi(,10933) * update options::              update options
cvs.texi(,10934) * update output::               update output
cvs.texi(,10935) @end menu
cvs.texi(,10936) 
cvs.texi(,10937) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,10938) @node update options
cvs.texi(,10939) @appendixsubsec update options
cvs.texi(,10940) 
cvs.texi(,10941) These standard options are available with @code{update}
cvs.texi(,10942) (@pxref{Common options}, for a complete description of
cvs.texi(,10943) them):
cvs.texi(,10944) 
cvs.texi(,10945) @table @code
cvs.texi(,10946) @item -D date
cvs.texi(,10947) Use the most recent revision no later than @var{date}.
cvs.texi(,10948) This option is sticky, and implies @samp{-P}.
cvs.texi(,10949) See @ref{Sticky tags}, for more information on sticky tags/dates.
cvs.texi(,10950) 
cvs.texi(,10951) @item -f
cvs.texi(,10952) Only useful with the @samp{-D @var{date}} or @samp{-r
cvs.texi(,10953) @var{tag}} flags.  If no matching revision is found,
cvs.texi(,10954) retrieve the most recent revision (instead of ignoring
cvs.texi(,10955) the file).
cvs.texi(,10956) 
cvs.texi(,10957) @item -k @var{kflag}
cvs.texi(,10958) Process keywords according to @var{kflag}.  See
cvs.texi(,10959) @ref{Keyword substitution}.
cvs.texi(,10960) This option is sticky; future updates of
cvs.texi(,10961) this file in this working directory will use the same
cvs.texi(,10962) @var{kflag}.  The @code{status} command can be viewed
cvs.texi(,10963) to see the sticky options.  See @ref{Invoking CVS}, for
cvs.texi(,10964) more information on the @code{status} command.
cvs.texi(,10965) 
cvs.texi(,10966) @item -l
cvs.texi(,10967) Local; run only in current working directory.  @xref{Recursive behavior}.
cvs.texi(,10968) 
cvs.texi(,10969) @item -P
cvs.texi(,10970) Prune empty directories.  See @ref{Moving directories}.
cvs.texi(,10971) 
cvs.texi(,10972) @item -p
cvs.texi(,10973) Pipe files to the standard output.
cvs.texi(,10974) 
cvs.texi(,10975) @item -R
cvs.texi(,10976) Update directories recursively (default).  @xref{Recursive
cvs.texi(,10977) behavior}.
cvs.texi(,10978) 
cvs.texi(,10979) @item -r rev
cvs.texi(,10980) Retrieve revision/tag @var{rev}.  This option is sticky,
cvs.texi(,10981) and implies @samp{-P}.
cvs.texi(,10982) See @ref{Sticky tags}, for more information on sticky tags/dates.
cvs.texi(,10983) @end table
cvs.texi(,10984) 
cvs.texi(,10985) @need 800
cvs.texi(,10986) These special options are also available with
cvs.texi(,10987) @code{update}.
cvs.texi(,10988) 
cvs.texi(,10989) @table @code
cvs.texi(,10990) @item -A
cvs.texi(,10991) Reset any sticky tags, dates, or @samp{-k} options.
cvs.texi(,10992) See @ref{Sticky tags}, for more information on sticky tags/dates.
cvs.texi(,10993) 
cvs.texi(,10994) @item -C
cvs.texi(,10995) Overwrite locally modified files with clean copies from
cvs.texi(,10996) the repository (the modified file is saved in
cvs.texi(,10997) @file{.#@var{file}.@var{revision}}, however).
cvs.texi(,10998) 
cvs.texi(,10999) @item -d
cvs.texi(,11000) Create any directories that exist in the repository if
cvs.texi(,11001) they're missing from the working directory.  Normally,
cvs.texi(,11002) @code{update} acts only on directories and files that
cvs.texi(,11003) were already enrolled in your working directory.
cvs.texi(,11004) 
cvs.texi(,11005) This is useful for updating directories that were
cvs.texi(,11006) created in the repository since the initial checkout;
cvs.texi(,11007) but it has an unfortunate side effect.  If you
cvs.texi(,11008) deliberately avoided certain directories in the
cvs.texi(,11009) repository when you created your working directory
cvs.texi(,11010) (either through use of a module name or by listing
cvs.texi(,11011) explicitly the files and directories you wanted on the
cvs.texi(,11012) command line), then updating with @samp{-d} will create
cvs.texi(,11013) those directories, which may not be what you want.
cvs.texi(,11014) 
cvs.texi(,11015) @item -I @var{name}
cvs.texi(,11016) Ignore files whose names match @var{name} (in your
cvs.texi(,11017) working directory) during the update.  You can specify
cvs.texi(,11018) @samp{-I} more than once on the command line to specify
cvs.texi(,11019) several files to ignore.  Use @samp{-I !} to avoid
cvs.texi(,11020) ignoring any files at all.  @xref{cvsignore}, for other
cvs.texi(,11021) ways to make @sc{cvs} ignore some files.
cvs.texi(,11022) 
cvs.texi(,11023) @item -W@var{spec}
cvs.texi(,11024) Specify file names that should be filtered during
cvs.texi(,11025) update.  You can use this option repeatedly.
cvs.texi(,11026) 
cvs.texi(,11027) @var{spec} can be a file name pattern of the same type
cvs.texi(,11028) that you can specify in the @file{.cvswrappers}
cvs.texi(,11029) file. @xref{Wrappers}.
cvs.texi(,11030) 
cvs.texi(,11031) @item -j@var{revision}
cvs.texi(,11032) With two @samp{-j} options, merge changes from the
cvs.texi(,11033) revision specified with the first @samp{-j} option to
cvs.texi(,11034) the revision specified with the second @samp{j} option,
cvs.texi(,11035) into the working directory.
cvs.texi(,11036) 
cvs.texi(,11037) With one @samp{-j} option, merge changes from the
cvs.texi(,11038) ancestor revision to the revision specified with the
cvs.texi(,11039) @samp{-j} option, into the working directory.  The
cvs.texi(,11040) ancestor revision is the common ancestor of the
cvs.texi(,11041) revision which the working directory is based on, and
cvs.texi(,11042) the revision specified in the @samp{-j} option.
cvs.texi(,11043) 
cvs.texi(,11044) Note that using a single @samp{-j @var{tagname}} option rather than
cvs.texi(,11045) @samp{-j @var{branchname}} to merge changes from a branch will
cvs.texi(,11046) often not remove files which were removed on the branch.
cvs.texi(,11047) @xref{Merging adds and removals}, for more.
cvs.texi(,11048) 
cvs.texi(,11049) In addition, each @samp{-j} option can contain an optional
cvs.texi(,11050) date specification which, when used with branches, can
cvs.texi(,11051) limit the chosen revision to one within a specific
cvs.texi(,11052) date.  An optional date is specified by adding a colon
cvs.texi(,11053) (:) to the tag:
cvs.texi(,11054) @samp{-j@var{Symbolic_Tag}:@var{Date_Specifier}}.
cvs.texi(,11055) 
cvs.texi(,11056) @xref{Branching and merging}.
cvs.texi(,11057) 
cvs.texi(,11058) @end table
cvs.texi(,11059) 
cvs.texi(,11060) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,11061) @node update output
cvs.texi(,11062) @appendixsubsec update output
cvs.texi(,11063) 
cvs.texi(,11064) @code{update} and @code{checkout} keep you informed of
cvs.texi(,11065) their progress by printing a line for each file, preceded
cvs.texi(,11066) by one character indicating the status of the file:
cvs.texi(,11067) 
cvs.texi(,11068) @table @code
cvs.texi(,11069) @item U @var{file}
cvs.texi(,11070) The file was brought up to date with respect to the
cvs.texi(,11071) repository.  This is done for any file that exists in
cvs.texi(,11072) the repository but not in your source, and for files
cvs.texi(,11073) that you haven't changed but are not the most recent
cvs.texi(,11074) versions available in the repository.
cvs.texi(,11075) 
cvs.texi(,11076) @item P @var{file}
cvs.texi(,11077) Like @samp{U}, but the @sc{cvs} server sends a patch instead of an entire
cvs.texi(,11078) file.  This accomplishes the same thing as @samp{U} using less bandwidth.
cvs.texi(,11079) 
cvs.texi(,11080) @item A @var{file}
cvs.texi(,11081) The file has been added to your private copy of the
cvs.texi(,11082) sources, and will be added to the source repository
cvs.texi(,11083) when you run @code{commit} on the file.  This is a
cvs.texi(,11084) reminder to you that the file needs to be committed.
cvs.texi(,11085) 
cvs.texi(,11086) @item R @var{file}
cvs.texi(,11087) The file has been removed from your private copy of the
cvs.texi(,11088) sources, and will be removed from the source repository
cvs.texi(,11089) when you run @code{commit} on the file.  This is a
cvs.texi(,11090) reminder to you that the file needs to be committed.
cvs.texi(,11091) 
cvs.texi(,11092) @item M @var{file}
cvs.texi(,11093) The file is modified in  your  working  directory.
cvs.texi(,11094) 
cvs.texi(,11095) @samp{M} can indicate one of two states for a file
cvs.texi(,11096) you're working on: either there were no modifications
cvs.texi(,11097) to the same file in the repository, so that your file
cvs.texi(,11098) remains as you last saw it; or there were modifications
cvs.texi(,11099) in the repository as well as in your copy, but they
cvs.texi(,11100) were merged successfully, without conflict, in your
cvs.texi(,11101) working directory.
cvs.texi(,11102) 
cvs.texi(,11103) @sc{cvs} will print some messages if it merges your work,
cvs.texi(,11104) and a backup copy of your working file (as it looked
cvs.texi(,11105) before you ran @code{update}) will be made.  The exact
cvs.texi(,11106) name of that file is printed while @code{update} runs.
cvs.texi(,11107) 
cvs.texi(,11108) @item C @var{file}
cvs.texi(,11109) @cindex .# files
cvs.texi(,11110) @cindex __ files (VMS)
cvs.texi(,11111) A conflict was detected while trying to merge your
cvs.texi(,11112) changes to @var{file} with changes from the source
cvs.texi(,11113) repository.  @var{file} (the copy in your working
cvs.texi(,11114) directory) is now the result of attempting to merge
cvs.texi(,11115) the two revisions; an unmodified copy of your file
cvs.texi(,11116) is also in your working directory, with the name
cvs.texi(,11117) @file{.#@var{file}.@var{revision}} where @var{revision}
cvs.texi(,11118) is the revision that your modified file started
cvs.texi(,11119) from.  Resolve the conflict as described in
cvs.texi(,11120) @ref{Conflicts example}.
cvs.texi(,11121) @c "some systems" as in out-of-the-box OSes?  Not as
cvs.texi(,11122) @c far as I know.  We need to advise sysadmins as well
cvs.texi(,11123) @c as users how to set up this kind of purge, if that is
cvs.texi(,11124) @c what they want.
cvs.texi(,11125) @c We also might want to think about cleaner solutions,
cvs.texi(,11126) @c like having CVS remove the .# file once the conflict
cvs.texi(,11127) @c has been resolved or something like that.
cvs.texi(,11128) (Note that some systems automatically purge
cvs.texi(,11129) files that begin with @file{.#} if they have not been
cvs.texi(,11130) accessed for a few days.  If you intend to keep a copy
cvs.texi(,11131) of your original file, it is a very good idea to rename
cvs.texi(,11132) it.)  Under @sc{vms}, the file name starts with
cvs.texi(,11133) @file{__} rather than @file{.#}.
cvs.texi(,11134) 
cvs.texi(,11135) @item ? @var{file}
cvs.texi(,11136) @var{file} is in your working directory, but does not
cvs.texi(,11137) correspond to anything in the source repository, and is
cvs.texi(,11138) not in the list of files for @sc{cvs} to ignore (see the
cvs.texi(,11139) description of the @samp{-I} option, and
cvs.texi(,11140) @pxref{cvsignore}).
cvs.texi(,11141) @end table
cvs.texi(,11142) 
cvs.texi(,11143) @node Invoking CVS
cvs.texi(,11144) @appendix Quick reference to CVS commands
cvs.texi(,11145) @cindex Command reference
cvs.texi(,11146) @cindex Reference, commands
cvs.texi(,11147) @cindex Invoking CVS
cvs.texi(,11148) 
cvs.texi(,11149) This appendix describes how to invoke @sc{cvs}, with
cvs.texi(,11150) references to where each command or feature is
cvs.texi(,11151) described in detail.  For other references run the
cvs.texi(,11152) @code{cvs --help} command, or see @ref{Index}.
cvs.texi(,11153) 
cvs.texi(,11154) A @sc{cvs} command looks like:
cvs.texi(,11155) 
cvs.texi(,11156) @example
cvs.texi(,11157) cvs [ @var{global_options} ] @var{command} [ @var{command_options} ] [ @var{command_args} ]
cvs.texi(,11158) @end example
cvs.texi(,11159) 
cvs.texi(,11160) Global options:
cvs.texi(,11161) 
cvs.texi(,11162) @table @code
cvs.texi(,11163) @item --allow-root=@var{rootdir}
cvs.texi(,11164) Specify legal @sc{cvsroot} directory (server only) (not
cvs.texi(,11165) in @sc{cvs} 1.9 and older).  See @ref{Password
cvs.texi(,11166) authentication server}.
cvs.texi(,11167) 
cvs.texi(,11168) @item -a
cvs.texi(,11169) Authenticate all communication (client only) (not in @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,11170) 1.9 and older).  See @ref{Global options}.
cvs.texi(,11171) 
cvs.texi(,11172) @item -b
cvs.texi(,11173) Specify RCS location (@sc{cvs} 1.9 and older).  See
cvs.texi(,11174) @ref{Global options}.
cvs.texi(,11175) 
cvs.texi(,11176) @item -d @var{root}
cvs.texi(,11177) Specify the @sc{cvsroot}.  See @ref{Repository}.
cvs.texi(,11178) 
cvs.texi(,11179) @item -e @var{editor}
cvs.texi(,11180) Edit messages with @var{editor}.  See @ref{Committing
cvs.texi(,11181) your changes}.
cvs.texi(,11182) 
cvs.texi(,11183) @item -f
cvs.texi(,11184) Do not read the @file{~/.cvsrc} file.  See @ref{Global
cvs.texi(,11185) options}.
cvs.texi(,11186) 
cvs.texi(,11187) @item -H
cvs.texi(,11188) @itemx --help
cvs.texi(,11189) Print a help message.  See @ref{Global options}.
cvs.texi(,11190) 
cvs.texi(,11191) @item -l
cvs.texi(,11192) Do not log in @file{$CVSROOT/CVSROOT/history} file.  See @ref{Global
cvs.texi(,11193) options}.
cvs.texi(,11194) 
cvs.texi(,11195) @item -n
cvs.texi(,11196) Do not change any files.  See @ref{Global options}.
cvs.texi(,11197) 
cvs.texi(,11198) @item -Q
cvs.texi(,11199) Be really quiet.  See @ref{Global options}.
cvs.texi(,11200) 
cvs.texi(,11201) @item -q
cvs.texi(,11202) Be somewhat quiet.  See @ref{Global options}.
cvs.texi(,11203) 
cvs.texi(,11204) @item -r
cvs.texi(,11205) Make new working files read-only.  See @ref{Global options}.
cvs.texi(,11206) 
cvs.texi(,11207) @item -s @var{variable}=@var{value}
cvs.texi(,11208) Set a user variable.  See @ref{Variables}.
cvs.texi(,11209) 
cvs.texi(,11210) @item -T @var{tempdir}
cvs.texi(,11211) Put temporary files in @var{tempdir}.  See @ref{Global
cvs.texi(,11212) options}.
cvs.texi(,11213) 
cvs.texi(,11214) @item -t
cvs.texi(,11215) Trace @sc{cvs} execution.  See @ref{Global options}.
cvs.texi(,11216) 
cvs.texi(,11217) @item -v
cvs.texi(,11218) @item --version
cvs.texi(,11219) Display version and copyright information for @sc{cvs}.
cvs.texi(,11220) 
cvs.texi(,11221) @item -w
cvs.texi(,11222) Make new working files read-write.  See @ref{Global
cvs.texi(,11223) options}.
cvs.texi(,11224) 
cvs.texi(,11225) @item -x
cvs.texi(,11226) Encrypt all communication (client only).
cvs.texi(,11227) See @ref{Global options}.
cvs.texi(,11228) 
cvs.texi(,11229) @item -z @var{gzip-level}
cvs.texi(,11230) @cindex Compression
cvs.texi(,11231) @cindex Gzip
cvs.texi(,11232) Set the compression level (client only).
cvs.texi(,11233) See @ref{Global options}.
cvs.texi(,11234) @end table
cvs.texi(,11235) 
cvs.texi(,11236) Keyword expansion modes (@pxref{Substitution modes}):
cvs.texi(,11237) 
cvs.texi(,11238) @example
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11239) -kkv  $ Id: file1,v 1.1 1993/12/09 03:21:13 joe Exp $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11240) -kkvl $ Id: file1,v 1.1 1993/12/09 03:21:13 joe Exp harry $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11241) -kk   $ Id$
cvs.texi(,11242) -kv   file1,v 1.1 1993/12/09 03:21:13 joe Exp
cvs.texi(,11243) -ko   @i{no expansion}
cvs.texi(,11244) -kb   @i{no expansion, file is binary}
cvs.texi(,11245) @end example
cvs.texi(,11246) 
cvs.texi(,11247) Keywords (@pxref{Keyword list}):
cvs.texi(,11248) 
cvs.texi(,11249) @example
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11250) $ Author: joe $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11251) $ Date: 1993/12/09 03:21:13 $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11252) $ CVSHeader: files/file1,v 1.1 1993/12/09 03:21:13 joe Exp harry $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11253) $ Header: /home/files/file1,v 1.1 1993/12/09 03:21:13 joe Exp harry $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11254) $ Id: file1,v 1.1 1993/12/09 03:21:13 joe Exp harry $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11255) $ Locker: harry $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11256) $ Name: snapshot_1_14 $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11257) $ RCSfile: file1,v $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11258) $ Revision: 1.1 $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11259) $ Source: /home/files/file1,v $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11260) $ State: Exp $
cvs.texi(splitrcskeyword,11261) $ Log: file1,v $
cvs.texi(,11262) Revision 1.1  1993/12/09 03:30:17  joe
cvs.texi(,11263) Initial revision
cvs.texi(,11264) 
cvs.texi(,11265) @end example
cvs.texi(,11266) 
cvs.texi(,11267) @c The idea behind this table is that we want each item
cvs.texi(,11268) @c to be a sentence or two at most.  Preferably a
cvs.texi(,11269) @c single line.
cvs.texi(,11270) @c
cvs.texi(,11271) @c In some cases refs to "foo options" are just to get
cvs.texi(,11272) @c this thing written quickly, not because the "foo
cvs.texi(,11273) @c options" node is really the best place to point.
cvs.texi(,11274) Commands, command options, and command arguments:
cvs.texi(,11275) 
cvs.texi(,11276) @table @code
cvs.texi(,11277) @c ------------------------------------------------------------
cvs.texi(,11278) @item add [@var{options}] [@var{files}@dots{}]
cvs.texi(,11279) Add a new file/directory.  See @ref{Adding files}.
cvs.texi(,11280) 
cvs.texi(,11281) @table @code
cvs.texi(,11282) @item -k @var{kflag}
cvs.texi(,11283) Set keyword expansion.
cvs.texi(,11284) 
cvs.texi(,11285) @item -m @var{msg}
cvs.texi(,11286) Set file description.
cvs.texi(,11287) @end table
cvs.texi(,11288) 
cvs.texi(,11289) @c ------------------------------------------------------------
cvs.texi(,11290) @item admin [@var{options}] [@var{files}@dots{}]
cvs.texi(,11291) Administration of history files in the repository.  See
cvs.texi(,11292) @ref{admin}.
cvs.texi(,11293) @c This list omits those options which are not
cvs.texi(,11294) @c documented as being useful with CVS.  That might be
cvs.texi(,11295) @c a mistake...
cvs.texi(,11296) 
cvs.texi(,11297) @table @code
cvs.texi(,11298) @item -b[@var{rev}]
cvs.texi(,11299) Set default branch.  See @ref{Reverting local changes}.
cvs.texi(,11300) 
cvs.texi(,11301) @item -c@var{string}
cvs.texi(,11302) Set comment leader.
cvs.texi(,11303) 
cvs.texi(,11304) @item -k@var{subst}
cvs.texi(,11305) Set keyword substitution.  See @ref{Keyword
cvs.texi(,11306) substitution}.
cvs.texi(,11307) 
cvs.texi(,11308) @item -l[@var{rev}]
cvs.texi(,11309) Lock revision @var{rev}, or latest revision.
cvs.texi(,11310) 
cvs.texi(,11311) @item -m@var{rev}:@var{msg}
cvs.texi(,11312) Replace the log message of revision @var{rev} with
cvs.texi(,11313) @var{msg}.
cvs.texi(,11314) 
cvs.texi(,11315) @item -o@var{range}
cvs.texi(,11316) Delete revisions from the repository.  See
cvs.texi(,11317) @ref{admin options}.
cvs.texi(,11318) 
cvs.texi(,11319) @item -q
cvs.texi(,11320) Run quietly; do not print diagnostics.
cvs.texi(,11321) 
cvs.texi(,11322) @item -s@var{state}[:@var{rev}]
cvs.texi(,11323) Set the state.
cvs.texi(,11324) 
cvs.texi(,11325) @c Does not work for client/server CVS
cvs.texi(,11326) @item -t
cvs.texi(,11327) Set file description from standard input.
cvs.texi(,11328) 
cvs.texi(,11329) @item -t@var{file}
cvs.texi(,11330) Set file description from @var{file}.
cvs.texi(,11331) 
cvs.texi(,11332) @item -t-@var{string}
cvs.texi(,11333) Set file description to @var{string}.
cvs.texi(,11334) 
cvs.texi(,11335) @item -u[@var{rev}]
cvs.texi(,11336) Unlock revision @var{rev}, or latest revision.
cvs.texi(,11337) @end table
cvs.texi(,11338) 
cvs.texi(,11339) @c ------------------------------------------------------------
cvs.texi(,11340) @item annotate [@var{options}] [@var{files}@dots{}]
cvs.texi(,11341) Show last revision where each line was modified.  See
cvs.texi(,11342) @ref{annotate}.
cvs.texi(,11343) 
cvs.texi(,11344) @table @code
cvs.texi(,11345) @item -D @var{date}
cvs.texi(,11346) Annotate the most recent revision no later than
cvs.texi(,11347) @var{date}.  See @ref{Common options}.
cvs.texi(,11348) 
cvs.texi(,11349) @item -F
cvs.texi(,11350) Force annotation of binary files.  (Without this option,
cvs.texi(,11351) binary files are skipped with a message.)
cvs.texi(,11352) 
cvs.texi(,11353) @item -f
cvs.texi(,11354) Use head revision if tag/date not found.  See
cvs.texi(,11355) @ref{Common options}.
cvs.texi(,11356) 
cvs.texi(,11357) @item -l
cvs.texi(,11358) Local; run only in current working directory.  @xref{Recursive behavior}.
cvs.texi(,11359) 
cvs.texi(,11360) @item -R
cvs.texi(,11361) Operate recursively (default).  @xref{Recursive
cvs.texi(,11362) behavior}.
cvs.texi(,11363) 
cvs.texi(,11364) @item -r @var{tag}
cvs.texi(,11365) Annotate revision @var{tag}.  See @ref{Common options}.
cvs.texi(,11366) @end table
cvs.texi(,11367) 
cvs.texi(,11368) @c ------------------------------------------------------------
cvs.texi(,11369) @item checkout [@var{options}] @var{modules}@dots{}
cvs.texi(,11370) Get a copy of the sources.  See @ref{checkout}.
cvs.texi(,11371) 
cvs.texi(,11372) @table @code
cvs.texi(,11373) @item -A
cvs.texi(,11374) Reset any sticky tags/date/options.  See @ref{Sticky
cvs.texi(,11375) tags} and @ref{Keyword substitution}.
cvs.texi(,11376) 
cvs.texi(,11377) @item -c
cvs.texi(,11378) Output the module database.  See @ref{checkout options}.
cvs.texi(,11379) 
cvs.texi(,11380) @item -D @var{date}
cvs.texi(,11381) Check out revisions as of @var{date} (is sticky).  See
cvs.texi(,11382) @ref{Common options}.
cvs.texi(,11383) 
cvs.texi(,11384) @item -d @var{dir}
cvs.texi(,11385) Check out into @var{dir}.  See @ref{checkout options}.
cvs.texi(,11386) 
cvs.texi(,11387) @item -f
cvs.texi(,11388) Use head revision if tag/date not found.  See
cvs.texi(,11389) @ref{Common options}.
cvs.texi(,11390) 
cvs.texi(,11391) @c Probably want to use rev1/rev2 style like for diff
cvs.texi(,11392) @c -r.  Here and in on-line help.
cvs.texi(,11393) @item -j @var{rev}
cvs.texi(,11394) Merge in changes.  See @ref{checkout options}.
cvs.texi(,11395) 
cvs.texi(,11396) @item -k @var{kflag}
cvs.texi(,11397) Use @var{kflag} keyword expansion.  See
cvs.texi(,11398) @ref{Substitution modes}.
cvs.texi(,11399) 
cvs.texi(,11400) @item -l
cvs.texi(,11401) Local; run only in current working directory.  @xref{Recursive behavior}.
cvs.texi(,11402) 
cvs.texi(,11403) @item -N
cvs.texi(,11404) Don't ``shorten'' module paths if -d specified.  See
cvs.texi(,11405) @ref{checkout options}.
cvs.texi(,11406) 
cvs.texi(,11407) @item -n
cvs.texi(,11408) Do not run module program (if any).  See @ref{checkout options}.
cvs.texi(,11409) 
cvs.texi(,11410) @item -P
cvs.texi(,11411) Prune empty directories.  See @ref{Moving directories}.
cvs.texi(,11412) 
cvs.texi(,11413) @item -p
cvs.texi(,11414) Check out files to standard output (avoids
cvs.texi(,11415) stickiness).  See @ref{checkout options}.
cvs.texi(,11416) 
cvs.texi(,11417) @item -R
cvs.texi(,11418) Operate recursively (default).  @xref{Recursive
cvs.texi(,11419) behavior}.
cvs.texi(,11420) 
cvs.texi(,11421) @item -r @var{tag}
cvs.texi(,11422) Checkout revision @var{tag} (is sticky).  See @ref{Common options}.
cvs.texi(,11423) 
cvs.texi(,11424) @item -s
cvs.texi(,11425) Like -c, but include module status.  See @ref{checkout options}.
cvs.texi(,11426) @end table
cvs.texi(,11427) 
cvs.texi(,11428) @c ------------------------------------------------------------
cvs.texi(,11429) @item commit [@var{options}] [@var{files}@dots{}]
cvs.texi(,11430) Check changes into the repository.  See @ref{commit}.
cvs.texi(,11431) 
cvs.texi(,11432) @table @code
cvs.texi(,11433) @item -F @var{file}
cvs.texi(,11434) Read log message from @var{file}.  See @ref{commit options}.
cvs.texi(,11435) 
cvs.texi(,11436) @item -f
cvs.texi(,11437) @c What is this "disables recursion"?  It is from the
cvs.texi(,11438) @c on-line help; is it documented in this manual?
cvs.texi(,11439) Force the file to be committed; disables recursion.
cvs.texi(,11440) See @ref{commit options}.
cvs.texi(,11441) 
cvs.texi(,11442) @item -l
cvs.texi(,11443) Local; run only in current working directory.  See @ref{Recursive behavior}.
cvs.texi(,11444) 
cvs.texi(,11445) @item -m @var{msg}
cvs.texi(,11446) Use @var{msg} as log message.  See @ref{commit options}.
cvs.texi(,11447) 
cvs.texi(,11448) @item -n
cvs.texi(,11449) Do not run module program (if any).  See @ref{commit options}.
cvs.texi(,11450) 
cvs.texi(,11451) @item -R
cvs.texi(,11452) Operate recursively (default).  @xref{Recursive
cvs.texi(,11453) behavior}.
cvs.texi(,11454) 
cvs.texi(,11455) @item -r @var{rev}
cvs.texi(,11456) Commit to @var{rev}.  See @ref{commit options}.
cvs.texi(,11457) @c FIXME: should be dragging over text from
cvs.texi(,11458) @c commit options, especially if it can be cleaned up
cvs.texi(,11459) @c and made concise enough.
