cvs.texi(,12074) @node Administrative files
cvs.texi(,12075) @appendix Reference manual for Administrative files
cvs.texi(,12076) @cindex Administrative files (reference)
cvs.texi(,12077) @cindex Files, reference manual
cvs.texi(,12078) @cindex Reference manual (files)
cvs.texi(,12079) @cindex CVSROOT (file)
cvs.texi(,12080) 
cvs.texi(,12081) @c FIXME?  Somewhere there needs to be a more "how-to"
cvs.texi(,12082) @c guide to writing these.  I think the triggers
cvs.texi(,12083) @c (commitinfo, loginfo, taginfo, &c) are perhaps a
cvs.texi(,12084) @c different case than files like modules.  One
cvs.texi(,12085) @c particular issue that people sometimes are
cvs.texi(,12086) @c (unnecessarily?) worried about is performance, and
cvs.texi(,12087) @c the impact of writing in perl or sh or ____.
cvs.texi(,12088) Inside the repository, in the directory
cvs.texi(,12089) @file{$CVSROOT/CVSROOT}, there are a number of
cvs.texi(,12090) supportive files for @sc{cvs}.  You can use @sc{cvs} in a limited
cvs.texi(,12091) fashion without any of them, but if they are set up
cvs.texi(,12092) properly they can help make life easier.  For a
cvs.texi(,12093) discussion of how to edit them, see @ref{Intro
cvs.texi(,12094) administrative files}.
cvs.texi(,12095) 
cvs.texi(,12096) The most important of these files is the @file{modules}
cvs.texi(,12097) file, which defines the modules inside the repository.
cvs.texi(,12098) 
cvs.texi(,12099) @menu
cvs.texi(,12100) * modules::                     Defining modules
cvs.texi(,12101) * Wrappers::                    Specify binary-ness based on file name
cvs.texi(,12102) * commit files::                The commit support files (commitinfo,
cvs.texi(,12103)                                 verifymsg, editinfo, loginfo)
cvs.texi(,12104) * rcsinfo::                     Templates for the log messages
cvs.texi(,12105) * cvsignore::                   Ignoring files via cvsignore
cvs.texi(,12106) * checkoutlist::                Adding your own administrative files
cvs.texi(,12107) * history file::                History information
cvs.texi(,12108) * Variables::                   Various variables are expanded
cvs.texi(,12109) * config::                      Miscellaneous CVS configuration
cvs.texi(,12110) @end menu
cvs.texi(,12111) 
cvs.texi(,12112) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,12113) @node modules
cvs.texi(,12114) @appendixsec The modules file
cvs.texi(,12115) @cindex Modules (admin file)
cvs.texi(,12116) @cindex Defining modules (reference manual)
cvs.texi(,12117) 
cvs.texi(,12118) The @file{modules} file records your definitions of
cvs.texi(,12119) names for collections of source code.  @sc{cvs} will
cvs.texi(,12120) use these definitions if you use @sc{cvs} to update the
cvs.texi(,12121) modules file (use normal commands like @code{add},
cvs.texi(,12122) @code{commit}, etc).
cvs.texi(,12123) 
cvs.texi(,12124) The @file{modules} file may contain blank lines and
cvs.texi(,12125) comments (lines beginning with @samp{#}) as well as
cvs.texi(,12126) module definitions.  Long lines can be continued on the
cvs.texi(,12127) next line by specifying a backslash (@samp{\}) as the
cvs.texi(,12128) last character on the line.
cvs.texi(,12129) 
cvs.texi(,12130) There are three basic types of modules: alias modules,
cvs.texi(,12131) regular modules, and ampersand modules.  The difference
cvs.texi(,12132) between them is the way that they map files in the
cvs.texi(,12133) repository to files in the working directory.  In all
cvs.texi(,12134) of the following examples, the top-level repository
cvs.texi(,12135) contains a directory called @file{first-dir}, which
cvs.texi(,12136) contains two files, @file{file1} and @file{file2}, and a
cvs.texi(,12137) directory @file{sdir}.  @file{first-dir/sdir} contains
cvs.texi(,12138) a file @file{sfile}.
cvs.texi(,12139) 
cvs.texi(,12140) @c FIXME: should test all the examples in this section.
cvs.texi(,12141) 
cvs.texi(,12142) @menu
cvs.texi(,12143) * Alias modules::             The simplest kind of module
cvs.texi(,12144) * Regular modules::
cvs.texi(,12145) * Ampersand modules::
cvs.texi(,12146) * Excluding directories::     Excluding directories from a module
cvs.texi(,12147) * Module options::            Regular and ampersand modules can take options
cvs.texi(,12148) * Module program options::    How the modules ``program options'' programs
cvs.texi(,12149)                               are run. 
cvs.texi(,12150) @end menu
cvs.texi(,12151) 
cvs.texi(,12152) @node Alias modules
cvs.texi(,12153) @appendixsubsec Alias modules
cvs.texi(,12154) @cindex Alias modules
cvs.texi(,12155) @cindex -a, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12156) 
cvs.texi(,12157) Alias modules are the simplest kind of module:
cvs.texi(,12158) 
cvs.texi(,12159) @table @code
cvs.texi(,12160) @item @var{mname} -a @var{aliases}@dots{}
cvs.texi(,12161) This represents the simplest way of defining a module
cvs.texi(,12162) @var{mname}.  The @samp{-a} flags the definition as a
cvs.texi(,12163) simple alias: @sc{cvs} will treat any use of @var{mname} (as
cvs.texi(,12164) a command argument) as if the list of names
cvs.texi(,12165) @var{aliases} had been specified instead.
cvs.texi(,12166) @var{aliases} may contain either other module names or
cvs.texi(,12167) paths.  When you use paths in aliases, @code{checkout}
cvs.texi(,12168) creates all intermediate directories in the working
cvs.texi(,12169) directory, just as if the path had been specified
cvs.texi(,12170) explicitly in the @sc{cvs} arguments.
cvs.texi(,12171) @end table
cvs.texi(,12172) 
cvs.texi(,12173) For example, if the modules file contains:
cvs.texi(,12174) 
cvs.texi(,12175) @example
cvs.texi(,12176) amodule -a first-dir
cvs.texi(,12177) @end example
cvs.texi(,12178) 
cvs.texi(,12179) @noindent
cvs.texi(,12180) then the following two commands are equivalent:
cvs.texi(,12181) 
cvs.texi(,12182) @example
cvs.texi(,12183) $ cvs co amodule
cvs.texi(,12184) $ cvs co first-dir
cvs.texi(,12185) @end example
cvs.texi(,12186) 
cvs.texi(,12187) @noindent
cvs.texi(,12188) and they each would provide output such as:
cvs.texi(,12189) 
cvs.texi(,12190) @example
cvs.texi(,12191) cvs checkout: Updating first-dir
cvs.texi(,12192) U first-dir/file1
cvs.texi(,12193) U first-dir/file2
cvs.texi(,12194) cvs checkout: Updating first-dir/sdir
cvs.texi(,12195) U first-dir/sdir/sfile
cvs.texi(,12196) @end example
cvs.texi(,12197) 
cvs.texi(,12198) @node Regular modules
cvs.texi(,12199) @appendixsubsec Regular modules
cvs.texi(,12200) @cindex Regular modules
cvs.texi(,12201) 
cvs.texi(,12202) @table @code
cvs.texi(,12203) @item @var{mname} [ options ] @var{dir} [ @var{files}@dots{} ]
cvs.texi(,12204) In the simplest case, this form of module definition
cvs.texi(,12205) reduces to @samp{@var{mname} @var{dir}}.  This defines
cvs.texi(,12206) all the files in directory @var{dir} as module mname.
cvs.texi(,12207) @var{dir} is a relative path (from @code{$CVSROOT}) to a
cvs.texi(,12208) directory of source in the source repository.  In this
cvs.texi(,12209) case, on checkout, a single directory called
cvs.texi(,12210) @var{mname} is created as a working directory; no
cvs.texi(,12211) intermediate directory levels are used by default, even
cvs.texi(,12212) if @var{dir} was a path involving several directory
cvs.texi(,12213) levels.
cvs.texi(,12214) @end table
cvs.texi(,12215) 
cvs.texi(,12216) For example, if a module is defined by:
cvs.texi(,12217) 
cvs.texi(,12218) @example
cvs.texi(,12219) regmodule first-dir
cvs.texi(,12220) @end example
cvs.texi(,12221) 
cvs.texi(,12222) @noindent
cvs.texi(,12223) then regmodule will contain the files from first-dir:
cvs.texi(,12224) 
cvs.texi(,12225) @example
cvs.texi(,12226) $ cvs co regmodule
cvs.texi(,12227) cvs checkout: Updating regmodule
cvs.texi(,12228) U regmodule/file1
cvs.texi(,12229) U regmodule/file2
cvs.texi(,12230) cvs checkout: Updating regmodule/sdir
cvs.texi(,12231) U regmodule/sdir/sfile
cvs.texi(,12232) $
cvs.texi(,12233) @end example
cvs.texi(,12234) 
cvs.texi(,12235) By explicitly specifying files in the module definition
cvs.texi(,12236) after @var{dir}, you can select particular files from
cvs.texi(,12237) directory @var{dir}.  Here is
cvs.texi(,12238) an example:
cvs.texi(,12239) 
cvs.texi(,12240) @example
cvs.texi(,12241) regfiles first-dir/sdir sfile
cvs.texi(,12242) @end example
cvs.texi(,12243) 
cvs.texi(,12244) @noindent
cvs.texi(,12245) With this definition, getting the regfiles module
cvs.texi(,12246) will create a single working directory
cvs.texi(,12247) @file{regfiles} containing the file listed, which
cvs.texi(,12248) comes from a directory deeper
cvs.texi(,12249) in the @sc{cvs} source repository:
cvs.texi(,12250) 
cvs.texi(,12251) @example
cvs.texi(,12252) $ cvs co regfiles
cvs.texi(,12253) U regfiles/sfile
cvs.texi(,12254) $
cvs.texi(,12255) @end example
cvs.texi(,12256) 
cvs.texi(,12257) @node Ampersand modules
cvs.texi(,12258) @appendixsubsec Ampersand modules
cvs.texi(,12259) @cindex Ampersand modules
cvs.texi(,12260) @cindex &, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12261) 
cvs.texi(,12262) A module definition can refer to other modules by
cvs.texi(,12263) including @samp{&@var{module}} in its definition.
cvs.texi(,12264) @example
cvs.texi(,12265) @var{mname} [ options ] @var{&module}@dots{}
cvs.texi(,12266) @end example
cvs.texi(,12267) 
cvs.texi(,12268) Then getting the module creates a subdirectory for each such
cvs.texi(,12269) module, in the directory containing the module.  For
cvs.texi(,12270) example, if modules contains
cvs.texi(,12271) 
cvs.texi(,12272) @example
cvs.texi(,12273) ampermod &first-dir
cvs.texi(,12274) @end example
cvs.texi(,12275) 
cvs.texi(,12276) @noindent
cvs.texi(,12277) then a checkout will create an @code{ampermod} directory
cvs.texi(,12278) which contains a directory called @code{first-dir},
cvs.texi(,12279) which in turns contains all the directories and files
cvs.texi(,12280) which live there.  For example, the command
cvs.texi(,12281) 
cvs.texi(,12282) @example
cvs.texi(,12283) $ cvs co ampermod
cvs.texi(,12284) @end example
cvs.texi(,12285) 
cvs.texi(,12286) @noindent
cvs.texi(,12287) will create the following files:
cvs.texi(,12288) 
cvs.texi(,12289) @example
cvs.texi(,12290) ampermod/first-dir/file1
cvs.texi(,12291) ampermod/first-dir/file2
cvs.texi(,12292) ampermod/first-dir/sdir/sfile
cvs.texi(,12293) @end example
cvs.texi(,12294) 
cvs.texi(,12295) There is one quirk/bug: the messages that @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,12296) prints omit the @file{ampermod}, and thus do not
cvs.texi(,12297) correctly display the location to which it is checking
cvs.texi(,12298) out the files:
cvs.texi(,12299) 
cvs.texi(,12300) @example
cvs.texi(,12301) $ cvs co ampermod
cvs.texi(,12302) cvs checkout: Updating first-dir
cvs.texi(,12303) U first-dir/file1
cvs.texi(,12304) U first-dir/file2
cvs.texi(,12305) cvs checkout: Updating first-dir/sdir
cvs.texi(,12306) U first-dir/sdir/sfile
cvs.texi(,12307) $
cvs.texi(,12308) @end example
cvs.texi(,12309) 
cvs.texi(,12310) Do not rely on this buggy behavior; it may get fixed in
cvs.texi(,12311) a future release of @sc{cvs}.
cvs.texi(,12312) 
cvs.texi(,12313) @c FIXCVS: What happens if regular and & modules are
cvs.texi(,12314) @c combined, as in "ampermodule first-dir &second-dir"?
cvs.texi(,12315) @c When I tried it, it seemed to just ignore the
cvs.texi(,12316) @c "first-dir".  I think perhaps it should be an error
cvs.texi(,12317) @c (but this needs further investigation).
cvs.texi(,12318) @c In addition to discussing what each one does, we
