cvs.texi(,12321) 
cvs.texi(,12322) @node Excluding directories
cvs.texi(,12323) @appendixsubsec Excluding directories
cvs.texi(,12324) @cindex Excluding directories, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12325) @cindex !, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12326) 
cvs.texi(,12327) An alias module may exclude particular directories from
cvs.texi(,12328) other modules by using an exclamation mark (@samp{!})
cvs.texi(,12329) before the name of each directory to be excluded.
cvs.texi(,12330) 
cvs.texi(,12331) For example, if the modules file contains:
cvs.texi(,12332) 
cvs.texi(,12333) @example
cvs.texi(,12334) exmodule -a !first-dir/sdir first-dir
cvs.texi(,12335) @end example
cvs.texi(,12336) 
cvs.texi(,12337) @noindent
cvs.texi(,12338) then checking out the module @samp{exmodule} will check
cvs.texi(,12339) out everything in @samp{first-dir} except any files in
cvs.texi(,12340) the subdirectory @samp{first-dir/sdir}.
cvs.texi(,12341) @c Note that the "!first-dir/sdir" sometimes must be listed
cvs.texi(,12342) @c before "first-dir".  That seems like a probable bug, in which
cvs.texi(,12343) @c case perhaps it should be fixed (to allow either
cvs.texi(,12344) @c order) rather than documented.  See modules4 in testsuite.
cvs.texi(,12345) 
cvs.texi(,12346) @node Module options
cvs.texi(,12347) @appendixsubsec Module options
cvs.texi(,12348) @cindex Options, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12349) 
cvs.texi(,12350) Either regular modules or ampersand modules can contain
cvs.texi(,12351) options, which supply additional information concerning
cvs.texi(,12352) the module.
cvs.texi(,12353) 
cvs.texi(,12354) @table @code
cvs.texi(,12355) @cindex -d, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12356) @item -d @var{name}
cvs.texi(,12357) Name the working directory something other than the
cvs.texi(,12358) module name.
cvs.texi(,12359) @c FIXME: Needs a bunch of examples, analogous to the
cvs.texi(,12360) @c examples for alias, regular, and ampersand modules
cvs.texi(,12361) @c which show where the files go without -d.
cvs.texi(,12362) 
cvs.texi(,12363) @cindex Export program
cvs.texi(,12364) @cindex -e, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12365) @item -e @var{prog}
cvs.texi(,12366) Specify a program @var{prog} to run whenever files in a
cvs.texi(,12367) module are exported.  @var{prog} runs with a single
cvs.texi(,12368) argument, the module name.
cvs.texi(,12369) @c FIXME: Is it run on server? client?
cvs.texi(,12370) 
cvs.texi(,12371) @cindex Checkout program
cvs.texi(,12372) @cindex -o, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12373) @item -o @var{prog}
cvs.texi(,12374) Specify a program @var{prog} to run whenever files in a
cvs.texi(,12375) module are checked out.  @var{prog} runs with a single
cvs.texi(,12376) argument, the module name.  See @ref{Module program options} for
cvs.texi(,12377) information on how @var{prog} is called.
cvs.texi(,12378) @c FIXME: Is it run on server? client?
cvs.texi(,12379) 
cvs.texi(,12380) @cindex Status of a module
cvs.texi(,12381) @cindex Module status
cvs.texi(,12382) @cindex -s, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12383) @item -s @var{status}
cvs.texi(,12384) Assign a status to the module.  When the module file is
cvs.texi(,12385) printed with @samp{cvs checkout -s} the modules are
cvs.texi(,12386) sorted according to primarily module status, and
cvs.texi(,12387) secondarily according to the module name.  This option
cvs.texi(,12388) has no other meaning.  You can use this option for
cvs.texi(,12389) several things besides status: for instance, list the
cvs.texi(,12390) person that is responsible for this module.
cvs.texi(,12391) 
cvs.texi(,12392) @cindex Tag program
cvs.texi(,12393) @cindex -t, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12394) @item -t @var{prog}
cvs.texi(,12395) Specify a program @var{prog} to run whenever files in a
cvs.texi(,12396) module are tagged with @code{rtag}.  @var{prog} runs
cvs.texi(,12397) with two arguments: the module name and the symbolic
cvs.texi(,12398) tag specified to @code{rtag}.  It is not run
cvs.texi(,12399) when @code{tag} is executed.  Generally you will find
cvs.texi(,12400) that taginfo is a better solution (@pxref{user-defined logging}).
cvs.texi(,12401) @c FIXME: Is it run on server? client?
cvs.texi(,12402) @c Problems with -t include:
cvs.texi(,12403) @c * It is run after the tag not before
cvs.texi(,12404) @c * It doesn't get passed all the information that
cvs.texi(,12405) @c   taginfo does ("mov", &c).
cvs.texi(,12406) @c * It only is run for rtag, not tag.
cvs.texi(,12407) @end table
cvs.texi(,12408) 
cvs.texi(,12409) You should also see @pxref{Module program options} about how the
cvs.texi(,12410) ``program options'' programs are run.
cvs.texi(,12411) 
cvs.texi(,12412) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,12413) 
cvs.texi(,12414) @node Module program options
cvs.texi(,12415) @appendixsubsec How the modules file ``program options'' programs are run
cvs.texi(,12416) @cindex Modules file program options
cvs.texi(,12417) @cindex -t, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12418) @cindex -o, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12419) @cindex -e, in modules file
cvs.texi(,12420) 
cvs.texi(,12421) @noindent
cvs.texi(,12422) For checkout, rtag, and export, the program is server-based, and as such the
cvs.texi(,12423) following applies:-
cvs.texi(,12424) 
cvs.texi(,12425) If using remote access methods (pserver, ext, etc.),
cvs.texi(,12426) @sc{cvs} will execute this program on the server from a temporary
cvs.texi(,12427) directory. The path is searched for this program.
cvs.texi(,12428) 
cvs.texi(,12429) If using ``local access'' (on a local or remote NFS file system, i.e.
cvs.texi(,12430) repository set just to a path),
cvs.texi(,12431) the program will be executed from the newly checked-out tree, if
cvs.texi(,12432) found there, or alternatively searched for in the path if not.
cvs.texi(,12433) 
cvs.texi(,12434) The programs are all run after the operation has effectively
cvs.texi(,12435) completed.
cvs.texi(,12436) 
cvs.texi(,12437) 
cvs.texi(,12438) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,12439) @node Wrappers
cvs.texi(,12440) @appendixsec The cvswrappers file
cvs.texi(,12441) @cindex cvswrappers (admin file)
cvs.texi(,12442) @cindex CVSWRAPPERS, environment variable
cvs.texi(,12443) @cindex Wrappers
cvs.texi(,12444) 
cvs.texi(,12445) @c FIXME: need some better way of separating this out
cvs.texi(,12446) @c by functionality.  -m is
cvs.texi(,12447) @c one feature, and -k is a another.  And this discussion
cvs.texi(,12448) @c should be better motivated (e.g. start with the
cvs.texi(,12449) @c problems, then explain how the feature solves it).
cvs.texi(,12450) 
cvs.texi(,12451) Wrappers refers to a @sc{cvs} feature which lets you
cvs.texi(,12452) control certain settings based on the name of the file
cvs.texi(,12453) which is being operated on.  The settings are @samp{-k}
cvs.texi(,12454) for binary files, and @samp{-m} for nonmergeable text
cvs.texi(,12455) files.
cvs.texi(,12456) 
cvs.texi(,12457) The @samp{-m} option
cvs.texi(,12458) specifies the merge methodology that should be used when
cvs.texi(,12459) a non-binary file is updated.  @code{MERGE} means the usual
cvs.texi(,12460) @sc{cvs} behavior: try to merge the files.  @code{COPY}
cvs.texi(,12461) means that @code{cvs update} will refuse to merge
cvs.texi(,12462) files, as it also does for files specified as binary
cvs.texi(,12463) with @samp{-kb} (but if the file is specified as
cvs.texi(,12464) binary, there is no need to specify @samp{-m 'COPY'}).
cvs.texi(,12465) @sc{cvs} will provide the user with the
cvs.texi(,12466) two versions of the files, and require the user using
cvs.texi(,12467) mechanisms outside @sc{cvs}, to insert any necessary
cvs.texi(,12468) changes.
cvs.texi(,12469) 
cvs.texi(,12470) @strong{WARNING: do not use @code{COPY} with
cvs.texi(,12471) @sc{cvs} 1.9 or earlier - such versions of @sc{cvs} will
cvs.texi(,12472) copy one version of your file over the other, wiping
cvs.texi(,12473) out the previous contents.}
cvs.texi(,12474) @c Ordinarily we don't document the behavior of old
cvs.texi(,12475) @c versions.  But this one is so dangerous, I think we
cvs.texi(,12476) @c must.  I almost renamed it to -m 'NOMERGE' so we
cvs.texi(,12477) @c could say "never use -m 'COPY'".
cvs.texi(,12478) The @samp{-m} wrapper option only affects behavior when
cvs.texi(,12479) merging is done on update; it does not affect how files
cvs.texi(,12480) are stored.  See @ref{Binary files}, for more on
cvs.texi(,12481) binary files.
cvs.texi(,12482) 
cvs.texi(,12483) The basic format of the file @file{cvswrappers} is:
cvs.texi(,12484) 
cvs.texi(,12485) @c FIXME: @example is all wrong for this.  Use @deffn or
cvs.texi(,12486) @c something more sensible.
cvs.texi(,12487) @example
cvs.texi(,12488) wildcard     [option value][option value]...
cvs.texi(,12489) 
cvs.texi(,12490) where option is one of
cvs.texi(,12491) -m           update methodology      value: MERGE or COPY
cvs.texi(,12492) -k           keyword expansion       value: expansion mode
cvs.texi(,12493) 
cvs.texi(,12494) and value is a single-quote delimited value.
cvs.texi(,12495) @end example
cvs.texi(,12496) 
cvs.texi(,12558) 
cvs.texi(,12559) @c FIXME: We don't document -W or point to where it is
cvs.texi(,12560) @c documented.  Or .cvswrappers.
cvs.texi(,12561) For example, the following command imports a
cvs.texi(,12562) directory, treating files whose name ends in
cvs.texi(,12563) @samp{.exe} as binary:
cvs.texi(,12564) 
cvs.texi(,12565) @example
cvs.texi(,12566) cvs import -I ! -W "*.exe -k 'b'" first-dir vendortag reltag
cvs.texi(,12567) @end example
cvs.texi(,12568) 
cvs.texi(,12569) @c Another good example, would be storing files
cvs.texi(,12570) @c (e.g. binary files) compressed in the repository.
cvs.texi(,12571) @c 	::::::::::::::::::
cvs.texi(,12572) @c 	cvswrappers
cvs.texi(,12573) @c 	::::::::::::::::::
cvs.texi(,12574) @c 	*.t12 -m 'COPY'
cvs.texi(,12575) @c 	*.t[0-9][0-9] -f 'gunzipcp %s' -t 'gzipcp %s %s' -m 'COPY'
cvs.texi(,12576) @c
cvs.texi(,12577) @c	::::::::::::::::::
cvs.texi(,12578) @c	gunzipcp
cvs.texi(,12579) @c	::::::::::::::::::
cvs.texi(,12580) @c	:
cvs.texi(,12581) @c	[ -f $1 ] || exit 1
cvs.texi(,12582) @c	zcat $1 > /tmp/.#$1.$$
cvs.texi(,12583) @c	mv /tmp/.#$1.$$ $1
cvs.texi(,12584) @c
cvs.texi(,12585) @c	::::::::::::::::::
cvs.texi(,12586) @c	gzipcp
cvs.texi(,12587) @c	::::::::::::::::::
cvs.texi(,12588) @c	:
cvs.texi(,12589) @c	DIRNAME=`echo $1 | sed -e "s|/.*/||g"`
cvs.texi(,12590) @c	if [ ! -d $DIRNAME ] ; then
cvs.texi(,12591) @c	      DIRNAME=`echo $1 | sed -e "s|.*/||g"`
cvs.texi(,12592) @c	fi
cvs.texi(,12593) @c	gzip -c  $DIRNAME  > $2
cvs.texi(,12594) @c One catch--"cvs diff" will not invoke the wrappers
cvs.texi(,12595) @c (probably a CVS bug, although I haven't thought it out).
cvs.texi(,12596) 
cvs.texi(,12597) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,12598) @node commit files
cvs.texi(,12599) @appendixsec The commit support files
cvs.texi(,12600) @cindex Committing, administrative support files
cvs.texi(,12601) 
cvs.texi(,12602) The @samp{-i} flag in the @file{modules} file can be
cvs.texi(,12603) used to run a certain program whenever files are
cvs.texi(,12604) committed (@pxref{modules}).  The files described in
cvs.texi(,12605) this section provide other, more flexible, ways to run
cvs.texi(,12606) programs whenever something is committed.
cvs.texi(,12607) 
cvs.texi(,12608) There are three kind of programs that can be run on
cvs.texi(,12609) commit.  They are specified in files in the repository,
cvs.texi(,12610) as described below.  The following table summarizes the
cvs.texi(,12611) file names and the purpose of the corresponding
cvs.texi(,12612) programs.
cvs.texi(,12613) 
cvs.texi(,12614) @table @file
cvs.texi(,12615) @item commitinfo
cvs.texi(,12616) The program is responsible for checking that the commit
cvs.texi(,12617) is allowed.  If it exits with a non-zero exit status
cvs.texi(,12618) the commit will be aborted.
cvs.texi(,12619) 
cvs.texi(,12620) @item verifymsg
cvs.texi(,12621) The specified program is used to evaluate the log message,
cvs.texi(,12622) and possibly verify that it contains all required
cvs.texi(,12623) fields.  This is most useful in combination with the
cvs.texi(,12624) @file{rcsinfo} file, which can hold a log message
cvs.texi(,12625) template (@pxref{rcsinfo}).
cvs.texi(,12626) 
cvs.texi(,12627) @item editinfo
cvs.texi(,12628) The specified program is used to edit the log message,
cvs.texi(,12629) and possibly verify that it contains all required
cvs.texi(,12630) fields.  This is most useful in combination with the
cvs.texi(,12631) @file{rcsinfo} file, which can hold a log message
cvs.texi(,12632) template (@pxref{rcsinfo}).  (obsolete)
cvs.texi(,12633) 
cvs.texi(,12634) @item loginfo
cvs.texi(,12635) The specified program is called when the commit is
cvs.texi(,12636) complete.  It receives the log message and some
cvs.texi(,12637) additional information and can store the log message in
cvs.texi(,12638) a file, or mail it to appropriate persons, or maybe
cvs.texi(,12639) post it to a local newsgroup, or@dots{}  Your
cvs.texi(,12640) imagination is the limit!
cvs.texi(,12641) @end table
cvs.texi(,12642) 
cvs.texi(,12643) @menu
cvs.texi(,12644) * syntax::                      The common syntax
cvs.texi(,12645) * commitinfo::                  Pre-commit checking
cvs.texi(,12646) * verifymsg::                   How are log messages evaluated?
cvs.texi(,12647) * editinfo::                    Specifying how log messages are created
cvs.texi(,12648)                                 (obsolete)
cvs.texi(,12649) * loginfo::                     Where should log messages be sent?
cvs.texi(,12650) @end menu
cvs.texi(,12651) 
cvs.texi(,12652) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,12653) @node syntax
cvs.texi(,12654) @appendixsubsec The common syntax
cvs.texi(,12655) @cindex Info files (syntax)
cvs.texi(,12656) @cindex Syntax of info files
cvs.texi(,12657) @cindex Common syntax of info files
cvs.texi(,12658) 
cvs.texi(,12659) @c FIXME: having this so totally separate from the
cvs.texi(,12660) @c Variables node is rather bogus.
cvs.texi(,12661) 
cvs.texi(,12662) The administrative files such as @file{commitinfo},
cvs.texi(,12663) @file{loginfo}, @file{rcsinfo}, @file{verifymsg}, etc.,
cvs.texi(,12664) all have a common format.  The purpose of the files are
cvs.texi(,12665) described later on.  The common syntax is described
cvs.texi(,12666) here.
cvs.texi(,12667) 
cvs.texi(,12668) @cindex Regular expression syntax
cvs.texi(,12669) Each line contains the following:
cvs.texi(,12670) @itemize @bullet
cvs.texi(,12671) @item
cvs.texi(,12672) @c Say anything about DEFAULT and ALL?  Right now we
cvs.texi(,12673) @c leave that to the description of each file (and in fact
cvs.texi(,12674) @c the practice is inconsistent which is really annoying).
cvs.texi(,12675) A regular expression.  This is a basic regular
cvs.texi(,12676) expression in the syntax used by GNU emacs.
cvs.texi(,12677) @c FIXME: What we probably should be saying is "POSIX Basic
cvs.texi(,12678) @c Regular Expression with the following extensions (`\('
cvs.texi(,12679) @c `\|' '+' etc)"
cvs.texi(,12680) @c rather than define it with reference to emacs.
cvs.texi(,12681) @c The reference to emacs is not strictly speaking
cvs.texi(,12682) @c true, as we don't support \=, \s, or \S.  Also it isn't
cvs.texi(,12683) @c clear we should document and/or promise to continue to
cvs.texi(,12684) @c support all the obscure emacs extensions like \<.
cvs.texi(,12685) @c Also need to better cite (or include) full
cvs.texi(,12686) @c documentation for the syntax.
cvs.texi(,12687) @c Also see comment in configure.in about what happens to the
cvs.texi(,12688) @c syntax if we pick up a system-supplied regexp matcher.
cvs.texi(,12689) 
cvs.texi(,12690) @item
cvs.texi(,12691) A whitespace separator---one or more spaces and/or tabs.
cvs.texi(,12692) 
cvs.texi(,12693) @item
cvs.texi(,12694) A file name or command-line template.
cvs.texi(,12695) @end itemize
cvs.texi(,12696) 
cvs.texi(,12697) @noindent
cvs.texi(,12698) Blank lines are ignored.  Lines that start with the
cvs.texi(,12699) character @samp{#} are treated as comments.  Long lines
cvs.texi(,12700) unfortunately can @emph{not} be broken in two parts in
cvs.texi(,12701) any way.
cvs.texi(,12702) 
cvs.texi(,12703) The first regular expression that matches the current
cvs.texi(,12704) directory name in the repository is used.  The rest of the line
cvs.texi(,12705) is used as a file name or command-line as appropriate.
cvs.texi(,12706) 
cvs.texi(,12707) @c FIXME: need an example.  In particular, show what
cvs.texi(,12708) @c the regular expression is matched against (one
cvs.texi(,12709) @c ordinarily clueful person got confused about whether it
cvs.texi(,12710) @c includes the filename--"directory name" above should be
cvs.texi(,12711) @c unambiguous but there is nothing like an example to
cvs.texi(,12712) @c confirm people's understanding of this sort of thing).
cvs.texi(,12713) 
cvs.texi(,12714) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,12715) @node commitinfo
cvs.texi(,12716) @appendixsubsec Commitinfo
cvs.texi(,12717) @cindex @file{commitinfo}
cvs.texi(,12718) @cindex Commits, precommit verification of
cvs.texi(,12719) @cindex Precommit checking
cvs.texi(,12720) 
cvs.texi(,12721) The @file{commitinfo} file defines programs to execute
cvs.texi(,12722) whenever @samp{cvs commit} is about to execute.  These
cvs.texi(,12723) programs are used for pre-commit checking to verify
cvs.texi(,12724) that the modified, added and removed files are really
cvs.texi(,12725) ready to be committed.  This could be used, for
cvs.texi(,12726) instance, to verify that the changed files conform to
cvs.texi(,12727) to your site's standards for coding practice.
cvs.texi(,12728) 
cvs.texi(,12729) As mentioned earlier, each line in the
cvs.texi(,12730) @file{commitinfo} file consists of a regular expression
cvs.texi(,12731) and a command-line template.  The template can include
cvs.texi(,12732) a program name and any number of arguments you wish to
cvs.texi(,12733) supply to it.  The full path to the current source
cvs.texi(,12734) repository is appended to the template, followed by the
cvs.texi(,12735) file names of any files involved in the commit (added,
cvs.texi(,12736) removed, and modified files).
cvs.texi(,12737) 
cvs.texi(,12738) @cindex Exit status, of commitinfo
cvs.texi(,12739) The first line with a regular expression matching the
cvs.texi(,12740) directory within the repository will be used.  If the
cvs.texi(,12741) command returns a non-zero exit status the commit will
cvs.texi(,12742) be aborted.
cvs.texi(,12743) @c FIXME: need example(s) of what "directory within the
cvs.texi(,12744) @c repository" means.
cvs.texi(,12745) 
cvs.texi(,12746) @cindex DEFAULT in commitinfo
cvs.texi(,12747) If the repository name does not match any of the
cvs.texi(,12748) regular expressions in this file, the @samp{DEFAULT}
cvs.texi(,12749) line is used, if it is specified.
cvs.texi(,12750) 
cvs.texi(,12751) @cindex ALL in commitinfo
cvs.texi(,12752) All occurrences of the name @samp{ALL} appearing as a
cvs.texi(,12753) regular expression are used in addition to the first
cvs.texi(,12754) matching regular expression or the name @samp{DEFAULT}.
cvs.texi(,12755) 
cvs.texi(,12756) @cindex @file{commitinfo}, working directory
cvs.texi(,12757) @cindex @file{commitinfo}, command environment
cvs.texi(,12758) The command will be run in the root of the workspace
cvs.texi(,12759) containing the new versions of any files the user would like
cvs.texi(,12760) to modify (commit), @emph{or in a copy of the workspace on
cvs.texi(,12761) the server (@pxref{Remote repositories})}.  If a file is
cvs.texi(,12762) being removed, there will be no copy of the file under the
cvs.texi(,12763) current directory.  If a file is being added, there will be
cvs.texi(,12764) no corresponding archive file in the repository unless the
cvs.texi(,12765) file is being resurrected.
cvs.texi(,12766) 
cvs.texi(,12767) Note that both the repository directory and the corresponding
cvs.texi(,12768) Attic (@pxref{Attic}) directory may need to be checked to
cvs.texi(,12769) locate the archive file corresponding to any given file being
cvs.texi(,12770) committed.  Much of the information about the specific commit
cvs.texi(,12771) request being made, including the destination branch, commit
cvs.texi(,12772) message, and command line options specified, is not available
cvs.texi(,12773) to the command.
cvs.texi(,12774) 
cvs.texi(,12775) @c FIXME: should discuss using commitinfo to control
cvs.texi(,12776) @c who has checkin access to what (e.g. Joe can check into
cvs.texi(,12777) @c directories a, b, and c, and Mary can check into
cvs.texi(,12778) @c directories b, c, and d--note this case cannot be
cvs.texi(,12779) @c conveniently handled with unix groups).  Of course,
cvs.texi(,12780) @c adding a new set of features to CVS might be a more
cvs.texi(,12781) @c natural way to fix this problem than telling people to
cvs.texi(,12782) @c use commitinfo.
cvs.texi(,12783) @c FIXME: Should make some reference, especially in
cvs.texi(,12784) @c the context of controlling who has access, to the fact
cvs.texi(,12785) @c that commitinfo can be circumvented.  Perhaps
cvs.texi(,12786) @c mention SETXID (but has it been carefully examined
cvs.texi(,12787) @c for holes?).  This fits in with the discussion of
cvs.texi(,12788) @c general CVS security in "Password authentication
cvs.texi(,12789) @c security" (the bit which is not pserver-specific).
cvs.texi(,12790) 
cvs.texi(,12791) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,12792) @node verifymsg
cvs.texi(,12793) @appendixsubsec Verifying log messages
cvs.texi(,12794) @cindex @file{verifymsg} (admin file)
cvs.texi(,12795) @cindex Log message, verifying
cvs.texi(,12796) 
cvs.texi(,12797) Once you have entered a log message, you can evaluate
cvs.texi(,12798) that message to check for specific content, such as
cvs.texi(,12799) a bug ID.  Use the @file{verifymsg} file to
cvs.texi(,12800) specify a program that is used to verify the log message.
cvs.texi(,12801) This program could be a simple script that checks
cvs.texi(,12802) that the entered message contains the required fields.
cvs.texi(,12803) 
cvs.texi(,12804) The @file{verifymsg} file is often most useful together
cvs.texi(,12805) with the @file{rcsinfo} file, which can be used to
cvs.texi(,12806) specify a log message template.
cvs.texi(,12807) 
cvs.texi(,12808) Each line in the @file{verifymsg} file consists of a
cvs.texi(,12809) regular expression and a command-line template.  The
cvs.texi(,12810) template must include a program name, and can include
cvs.texi(,12811) any number of arguments.  The full path to the current
cvs.texi(,12812) log message template file is appended to the template.
cvs.texi(,12813) 
cvs.texi(,12814) One thing that should be noted is that the @samp{ALL}
cvs.texi(,12815) keyword is not supported.  If more than one matching
cvs.texi(,12816) line is found, the first one is used.  This can be
cvs.texi(,12817) useful for specifying a default verification script in a
cvs.texi(,12818) directory, and then overriding it in a subdirectory.
cvs.texi(,12819) 
cvs.texi(,12820) @cindex DEFAULT in @file{verifymsg}
cvs.texi(,12821) If the repository name does not match any of the
cvs.texi(,12822) regular expressions in this file, the @samp{DEFAULT}
cvs.texi(,12823) line is used, if it is specified.
cvs.texi(,12824) 
cvs.texi(,12825) @cindex Exit status, of @file{verifymsg}
cvs.texi(,12826) If the verification script exits with a non-zero exit status,
cvs.texi(,12827) the commit is aborted.
cvs.texi(,12828) 
cvs.texi(,12829) @cindex @file{verifymsg}, changing the log message
cvs.texi(,12830) In the default configuration, CVS allows the
cvs.texi(,12831) verification script to change the log message. This is
cvs.texi(,12832) controlled via the RereadLogAfterVerify CVSROOT/config
cvs.texi(,12833) option.
cvs.texi(,12834) 
cvs.texi(,12835) When @samp{RereadLogAfterVerify=always} or
cvs.texi(,12836) @samp{RereadLogAfterVerify=stat}, the log message will
cvs.texi(,12837) either always be reread after the verification script
cvs.texi(,12838) is run or reread only if the log message file status
cvs.texi(,12839) has changed.
cvs.texi(,12840) 
cvs.texi(,12841) @xref{config}, for more on CVSROOT/config options.
cvs.texi(,12842) 
cvs.texi(,12843) It is NOT a good idea for a @file{verifymsg} script to
cvs.texi(,12844) interact directly with the user in the various
cvs.texi(,12845) client/server methods. For the @code{pserver} method,
cvs.texi(,12846) there is no protocol support for communicating between
cvs.texi(,12847) @file{verifymsg} and the client on the remote end. For the
cvs.texi(,12848) @code{ext} and @code{server} methods, it is possible
cvs.texi(,12849) for CVS to become confused by the characters going
cvs.texi(,12850) along the same channel as the CVS protocol
cvs.texi(,12851) messages. See @ref{Remote repositories}, for more
cvs.texi(,12852) information on client/server setups.  In addition, at the time
cvs.texi(,12853) the @file{verifymsg} script runs, the CVS
cvs.texi(,12854) server has locks in place in the repository.  If control is
cvs.texi(,12855) returned to the user here then other users may be stuck waiting
cvs.texi(,12856) for access to the repository.
cvs.texi(,12857) 
cvs.texi(,12858) This option can be useful if you find yourself using an
cvs.texi(,12859) rcstemplate that needs to be modified to remove empty
cvs.texi(,12860) elements or to fill in default values.  It can also be
cvs.texi(,12861) useful if the rcstemplate has changed in the repository
cvs.texi(,12862) and the CVS/Template was not updated, but is able to be
cvs.texi(,12863) adapted to the new format by the verification script
cvs.texi(,12864) that is run by @file{verifymsg}.
cvs.texi(,12865) 
cvs.texi(,12866) An example of an update might be to change all
cvs.texi(,12867) occurrences of 'BugId:' to be 'DefectId:' (which can be
cvs.texi(,12868) useful if the rcstemplate has recently been changed and
cvs.texi(,12869) there are still checked-out user trees with cached
cvs.texi(,12870) copies in the CVS/Template file of the older version).
cvs.texi(,12871) 
cvs.texi(,12872) Another example of an update might be to delete a line
cvs.texi(,12873) that contains 'BugID: none' from the log message after
cvs.texi(,12874) validation of that value as being allowed is made.
cvs.texi(,12875) 
cvs.texi(,12876) The following is a little silly example of a
cvs.texi(,12877) @file{verifymsg} file, together with the corresponding
cvs.texi(,12878) @file{rcsinfo} file, the log message template and an
cvs.texi(,12879) verification  script.  We begin with the log message template.
cvs.texi(,12880) We want to always record a bug-id number on the first
cvs.texi(,12881) line of the log message.  The rest of log message is
cvs.texi(,12882) free text.  The following template is found in the file
cvs.texi(,12883) @file{/usr/cvssupport/tc.template}.
cvs.texi(,12884) 
cvs.texi(,12885) @example
cvs.texi(,12886) BugId:
cvs.texi(,12887) @end example
cvs.texi(,12888) 
cvs.texi(,12889) The script @file{/usr/cvssupport/bugid.verify} is used to
cvs.texi(,12890) evaluate the log message.
cvs.texi(,12891) 
cvs.texi(,12892) @example
cvs.texi(,12893) #!/bin/sh
cvs.texi(,12894) #
cvs.texi(,12895) #       bugid.verify filename
cvs.texi(,12896) #
cvs.texi(,12897) #  Verify that the log message contains a valid bugid
cvs.texi(,12898) #  on the first line.
cvs.texi(,12899) #
cvs.texi(,12900) if head -1 < $1 | grep '^BugId:[ ]*[0-9][0-9]*$' > /dev/null; then
cvs.texi(,12901)     exit 0
cvs.texi(,12902) elif head -1 < $1 | grep '^BugId:[ ]*none$' > /dev/null; then
cvs.texi(,12903)     # It is okay to allow commits with 'BugId: none',
cvs.texi(,12904)     # but do not put that text into the real log message.
cvs.texi(,12905)     grep -v '^BugId:[ ]*none$' > $1.rewrite
cvs.texi(,12906)     mv $1.rewrite $1
cvs.texi(,12907)     exit 0
cvs.texi(,12908) else
cvs.texi(,12909)     echo "No BugId found."
cvs.texi(,12910)     exit 1
cvs.texi(,12911) fi
cvs.texi(,12912) @end example
cvs.texi(,12913) 
cvs.texi(,12914) The @file{verifymsg} file contains this line:
cvs.texi(,12915) 
cvs.texi(,12916) @example
cvs.texi(,12917) ^tc     /usr/cvssupport/bugid.verify
cvs.texi(,12918) @end example
cvs.texi(,12919) 
cvs.texi(,12920) The @file{rcsinfo} file contains this line:
cvs.texi(,12921) 
cvs.texi(,12922) @example
cvs.texi(,12923) ^tc     /usr/cvssupport/tc.template
cvs.texi(,12924) @end example
cvs.texi(,12925) 
cvs.texi(,12926) The @file{config} file contains this line:
cvs.texi(,12927) 
cvs.texi(,12928) @example
cvs.texi(,12929) RereadLogAfterVerify=always
cvs.texi(,12930) @end example
cvs.texi(,12931) 
cvs.texi(,12932) 
cvs.texi(,12933) 
cvs.texi(,12934) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,12935) @node editinfo
cvs.texi(,12936) @appendixsubsec Editinfo
cvs.texi(,12937) @cindex editinfo (admin file)
cvs.texi(,12938) @cindex Editor, specifying per module
cvs.texi(,12939) @cindex Per-module editor
cvs.texi(,12940) @cindex Log messages, editing
cvs.texi(,12941) 
cvs.texi(,12942) @strong{Note: The @file{editinfo} feature has been
cvs.texi(,12943) rendered obsolete.  To set a default editor for log
cvs.texi(,12944) messages use the @code{CVSEDITOR}, @code{EDITOR} environment variables
cvs.texi(,12945) (@pxref{Environment variables}) or the @samp{-e} global
cvs.texi(,12946) option (@pxref{Global options}).  See @ref{verifymsg},
cvs.texi(,12947) for information on the use of the @file{verifymsg}
cvs.texi(,12948) feature for evaluating log messages.}
cvs.texi(,12949) 
cvs.texi(,12950) If you want to make sure that all log messages look the
cvs.texi(,12951) same way, you can use the @file{editinfo} file to
cvs.texi(,12952) specify a program that is used to edit the log message.
cvs.texi(,12953) This program could be a custom-made editor that always
cvs.texi(,12954) enforces a certain style of the log message, or maybe a
cvs.texi(,12955) simple shell script that calls an editor, and checks
cvs.texi(,12956) that the entered message contains the required fields.
cvs.texi(,12957) 
cvs.texi(,12958) If no matching line is found in the @file{editinfo}
cvs.texi(,12959) file, the editor specified in the environment variable
cvs.texi(,12960) @code{$CVSEDITOR} is used instead.  If that variable is
cvs.texi(,12961) not set, then the environment variable @code{$EDITOR}
cvs.texi(,12962) is used instead.  If that variable is not
cvs.texi(,12963) set a default will be used.  See @ref{Committing your changes}.
cvs.texi(,12964) 
cvs.texi(,12965) The @file{editinfo} file is often most useful together
cvs.texi(,12966) with the @file{rcsinfo} file, which can be used to
cvs.texi(,12967) specify a log message template.
cvs.texi(,12968) 
cvs.texi(,12969) Each line in the @file{editinfo} file consists of a
cvs.texi(,12970) regular expression and a command-line template.  The
cvs.texi(,12971) template must include a program name, and can include
cvs.texi(,12972) any number of arguments.  The full path to the current
cvs.texi(,12973) log message template file is appended to the template.
cvs.texi(,12974) 
cvs.texi(,12975) One thing that should be noted is that the @samp{ALL}
cvs.texi(,12976) keyword is not supported.  If more than one matching
cvs.texi(,12977) line is found, the first one is used.  This can be
cvs.texi(,12978) useful for specifying a default edit script in a
cvs.texi(,12979) module, and then overriding it in a subdirectory.
cvs.texi(,12980) 
cvs.texi(,12981) @cindex DEFAULT in editinfo
cvs.texi(,12982) If the repository name does not match any of the
cvs.texi(,12983) regular expressions in this file, the @samp{DEFAULT}
cvs.texi(,12984) line is used, if it is specified.
cvs.texi(,12985) 
cvs.texi(,12986) If the edit script exits with a non-zero exit status,
cvs.texi(,12987) the commit is aborted.
cvs.texi(,12988) 
cvs.texi(,12989) Note: when @sc{cvs} is accessing a remote repository,
cvs.texi(,12990) or when the @samp{-m} or @samp{-F} options to @code{cvs
cvs.texi(,12991) commit} are used, @file{editinfo} will not be consulted.
cvs.texi(,12992) There is no good workaround for this; use
cvs.texi(,12993) @file{verifymsg} instead.
cvs.texi(,12994) 
cvs.texi(,12995) @menu
cvs.texi(,12996) * editinfo example::            Editinfo example
cvs.texi(,12997) @end menu
cvs.texi(,12998) 
cvs.texi(,12999) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,13000) @node editinfo example
cvs.texi(,13001) @appendixsubsubsec Editinfo example
cvs.texi(,13002) 
cvs.texi(,13003) The following is a little silly example of a
cvs.texi(,13004) @file{editinfo} file, together with the corresponding
cvs.texi(,13005) @file{rcsinfo} file, the log message template and an
cvs.texi(,13006) editor script.  We begin with the log message template.
cvs.texi(,13007) We want to always record a bug-id number on the first
cvs.texi(,13008) line of the log message.  The rest of log message is
cvs.texi(,13009) free text.  The following template is found in the file
cvs.texi(,13010) @file{/usr/cvssupport/tc.template}.
cvs.texi(,13011) 
cvs.texi(,13012) @example
cvs.texi(,13013) BugId:
cvs.texi(,13014) @end example
cvs.texi(,13015) 
cvs.texi(,13016) The script @file{/usr/cvssupport/bugid.edit} is used to
cvs.texi(,13017) edit the log message.
cvs.texi(,13018) 
cvs.texi(,13019) @example
cvs.texi(,13020) #!/bin/sh
cvs.texi(,13021) #
cvs.texi(,13022) #       bugid.edit filename
cvs.texi(,13023) #
cvs.texi(,13024) #  Call $EDITOR on FILENAME, and verify that the
cvs.texi(,13025) #  resulting file contains a valid bugid on the first
cvs.texi(,13026) #  line.
cvs.texi(,13027) if [ "x$EDITOR" = "x" ]; then EDITOR=vi; fi
cvs.texi(,13028) if [ "x$CVSEDITOR" = "x" ]; then CVSEDITOR=$EDITOR; fi
cvs.texi(,13029) $CVSEDITOR $1
cvs.texi(,13030) until head -1|grep '^BugId:[ ]*[0-9][0-9]*$' < $1
cvs.texi(,13031) do  echo -n  "No BugId found.  Edit again? ([y]/n)"
cvs.texi(,13032)     read ans
cvs.texi(,13033)     case $@{ans@} in
cvs.texi(,13034)         n*) exit 1;;
cvs.texi(,13035)     esac
cvs.texi(,13036)     $CVSEDITOR $1
cvs.texi(,13037) done
cvs.texi(,13038) @end example
cvs.texi(,13039) 
cvs.texi(,13040) The @file{editinfo} file contains this line:
cvs.texi(,13041) 
cvs.texi(,13042) @example
cvs.texi(,13043) ^tc     /usr/cvssupport/bugid.edit
cvs.texi(,13044) @end example
cvs.texi(,13045) 
cvs.texi(,13046) The @file{rcsinfo} file contains this line:
cvs.texi(,13047) 
cvs.texi(,13048) @example
cvs.texi(,13049) ^tc     /usr/cvssupport/tc.template
cvs.texi(,13050) @end example
cvs.texi(,13051) 
cvs.texi(,13052) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,13053) @node loginfo
cvs.texi(,13054) @appendixsubsec Loginfo
cvs.texi(,13055) @cindex loginfo (admin file)
cvs.texi(,13056) @cindex Storing log messages
cvs.texi(,13057) @cindex Mailing log messages
cvs.texi(,13058) @cindex Distributing log messages
cvs.texi(,13059) @cindex Log messages
cvs.texi(,13060) 
cvs.texi(,13061) @c "cvs commit" is not quite right.  What we
cvs.texi(,13062) @c mean is "when the repository gets changed" which
cvs.texi(,13063) @c also includes "cvs import" and "cvs add" on a directory.
cvs.texi(,13064) The @file{loginfo} file is used to control where
cvs.texi(,13065) @samp{cvs commit} log information is sent.  The first
cvs.texi(,13066) entry on a line is a regular expression which is tested
cvs.texi(,13067) against the directory that the change is being made to,
cvs.texi(,13068) relative to the @code{$CVSROOT}.  If a match is found, then
cvs.texi(,13069) the remainder of the line is a filter program that
cvs.texi(,13070) should expect log information on its standard input.
cvs.texi(,13071) 
cvs.texi(,13072) If the repository name does not match any of the
cvs.texi(,13073) regular expressions in this file, the @samp{DEFAULT}
cvs.texi(,13074) line is used, if it is specified.
cvs.texi(,13075) 
cvs.texi(,13076) All occurrences of the name @samp{ALL} appearing as a
cvs.texi(,13077) regular expression are used in addition to the first
cvs.texi(,13078) matching regular expression or @samp{DEFAULT}.
cvs.texi(,13079) 
cvs.texi(,13080) The first matching regular expression is used.
cvs.texi(,13081) 
cvs.texi(,13082) @xref{commit files}, for a description of the syntax of
cvs.texi(,13083) the @file{loginfo} file.
cvs.texi(,13084) 
cvs.texi(,13085) The user may specify a format string as
cvs.texi(,13086) part of the filter.  The string is composed of a
cvs.texi(,13087) @samp{%} followed by a space, or followed by a single
cvs.texi(,13088) format character, or followed by a set of format
cvs.texi(,13089) characters surrounded by @samp{@{} and @samp{@}} as
cvs.texi(,13090) separators.  The format characters are:
cvs.texi(,13091) 
cvs.texi(,13092) @table @t
cvs.texi(,13093) @item s
cvs.texi(,13094) file name
cvs.texi(,13095) @item V
cvs.texi(,13096) old version number (pre-checkin)
cvs.texi(,13097) @item v
cvs.texi(,13098) new version number (post-checkin)
cvs.texi(,13099) @end table
cvs.texi(,13100) 
cvs.texi(,13101) All other characters that appear in a format string
cvs.texi(,13102) expand to an empty field (commas separating fields are
cvs.texi(,13103) still provided).
cvs.texi(,13104) 
cvs.texi(,13105) For example, some valid format strings are @samp{%},
cvs.texi(,13106) @samp{%s}, @samp{%@{s@}}, and @samp{%@{sVv@}}.
cvs.texi(,13107) 
cvs.texi(,13108) The output will be a space separated string of tokens enclosed in
cvs.texi(,13109) quotation marks (@t{"}).
cvs.texi(,13110) Any embedded dollar signs (@t{$}), backticks (@t{`}),
cvs.texi(,13111) backslashes (@t{\}), or quotation marks will be preceded
cvs.texi(,13112) by a backslash (this allows the shell to correctly parse it
cvs.texi(,13113) as a single string, regardless of the characters it contains).
cvs.texi(,13114) For backwards compatibility, the first
cvs.texi(,13115) token will be the repository subdirectory.  The rest of the
cvs.texi(,13116) tokens will be comma-delimited lists of the information
cvs.texi(,13117) requested in the format string.  For example, if
cvs.texi(,13118) @samp{/u/src/master/yoyodyne/tc} is the repository, @samp{%@{sVv@}}
cvs.texi(,13119) is the format string, and three files (@t{ChangeLog},
cvs.texi(,13120) @t{Makefile}, @t{foo.c}) were modified, the output
cvs.texi(,13121) might be:
cvs.texi(,13122) 
cvs.texi(,13123) @example
cvs.texi(,13124) "yoyodyne/tc ChangeLog,1.1,1.2 Makefile,1.3,1.4 foo.c,1.12,1.13"
cvs.texi(,13125) @end example
cvs.texi(,13126) 
cvs.texi(,13127) As another example, @samp{%@{@}} means that only the
cvs.texi(,13128) name of the repository will be generated.
cvs.texi(,13129) 
cvs.texi(,13130) Note: when @sc{cvs} is accessing a remote repository,
cvs.texi(,13131) @file{loginfo} will be run on the @emph{remote}
cvs.texi(,13132) (i.e., server) side, not the client side (@pxref{Remote
cvs.texi(,13133) repositories}).
cvs.texi(,13134) 
cvs.texi(,13135) @menu
cvs.texi(,13136) * loginfo example::             Loginfo example
cvs.texi(,13137) * Keeping a checked out copy::  Updating a tree on every checkin
cvs.texi(,13138) @end menu
cvs.texi(,13139) 
cvs.texi(,13140) @c . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
cvs.texi(,13141) @node loginfo example
cvs.texi(,13142) @appendixsubsubsec Loginfo example
cvs.texi(,13143) 
cvs.texi(,13144) The following @file{loginfo} file, together with the
cvs.texi(,13145) tiny shell-script below, appends all log messages
cvs.texi(,13146) to the file @file{$CVSROOT/CVSROOT/commitlog},
cvs.texi(,13147) and any commits to the administrative files (inside
cvs.texi(,13148) the @file{CVSROOT} directory) are also logged in
cvs.texi(,13149) @file{/usr/adm/cvsroot-log}.
cvs.texi(,13150) Commits to the @file{prog1} directory are mailed to @t{ceder}.
cvs.texi(,13151) 
cvs.texi(,13152) @c FIXME: is it a CVS feature or bug that only the
cvs.texi(,13153) @c first matching line is used?  It is documented
cvs.texi(,13154) @c above, but is it useful?  For example, if we wanted
cvs.texi(,13155) @c to run both "cvs-log" and "Mail" for the CVSROOT
cvs.texi(,13156) @c directory, it is kind of awkward if
cvs.texi(,13157) @c only the first matching line is used.
cvs.texi(,13158) @example
cvs.texi(,13159) ALL             /usr/local/bin/cvs-log $CVSROOT/CVSROOT/commitlog $USER
cvs.texi(,13160) ^CVSROOT        /usr/local/bin/cvs-log /usr/adm/cvsroot-log
cvs.texi(,13161) ^prog1          Mail -s %s ceder
cvs.texi(,13162) @end example
cvs.texi(,13163) 
cvs.texi(,13164) The shell-script @file{/usr/local/bin/cvs-log} looks
cvs.texi(,13165) like this:
cvs.texi(,13166) 
cvs.texi(,13167) @example
cvs.texi(,13168) #!/bin/sh
cvs.texi(,13169) (echo "------------------------------------------------------";
cvs.texi(,13170)  echo -n $2"  ";
cvs.texi(,13171)  date;
cvs.texi(,13172)  echo;
cvs.texi(,13173)  cat) >> $1
cvs.texi(,13174) @end example
cvs.texi(,13175) 
cvs.texi(,13176) @node Keeping a checked out copy
cvs.texi(,13177) @appendixsubsubsec Keeping a checked out copy
cvs.texi(,13178) 
cvs.texi(,13179) @c What other index entries?  It seems like
cvs.texi(,13180) @c people might want to use a lot of different
cvs.texi(,13181) @c words for this functionality.
cvs.texi(,13182) @cindex Keeping a checked out copy
cvs.texi(,13183) @cindex Checked out copy, keeping
cvs.texi(,13184) @cindex Web pages, maintaining with CVS
cvs.texi(,13185) 
cvs.texi(,13186) It is often useful to maintain a directory tree which
cvs.texi(,13187) contains files which correspond to the latest version
cvs.texi(,13188) in the repository.  For example, other developers might
cvs.texi(,13189) want to refer to the latest sources without having to
cvs.texi(,13190) check them out, or you might be maintaining a web site
cvs.texi(,13191) with @sc{cvs} and want every checkin to cause the files
cvs.texi(,13192) used by the web server to be updated.
cvs.texi(,13193) @c Can we offer more details on the web example?  Or
cvs.texi(,13194) @c point the user at how to figure it out?  This text
cvs.texi(,13195) @c strikes me as sufficient for someone who already has
cvs.texi(,13196) @c some idea of what we mean but not enough for the naive
cvs.texi(,13197) @c user/sysadmin to understand it and set it up.
cvs.texi(,13198) 
cvs.texi(,13199) The way to do this is by having loginfo invoke
cvs.texi(,13200) @code{cvs update}.  Doing so in the naive way will
cvs.texi(,13201) cause a problem with locks, so the @code{cvs update}
cvs.texi(,13202) must be run in the background.
cvs.texi(,13203) @c Should we try to describe the problem with locks?
cvs.texi(,13204) @c It seems like a digression for someone who just
cvs.texi(,13205) @c wants to know how to make it work.
cvs.texi(,13206) @c Another choice which might work for a single file
cvs.texi(,13207) @c is to use "cvs -n update -p" which doesn't take
cvs.texi(,13208) @c out locks (I think) but I don't see many advantages
cvs.texi(,13209) @c of that and we might as well document something which
cvs.texi(,13210) @c works for multiple files.
cvs.texi(,13211) Here is an example for unix (this should all be on one line):
cvs.texi(,13212) 
cvs.texi(,13213) @example
cvs.texi(,13214) ^cyclic-pages		(date; cat; (sleep 2; cd /u/www/local-docs;
cvs.texi(,13215)  cvs -q update -d) &) >> $CVSROOT/CVSROOT/updatelog 2>&1
cvs.texi(,13216) @end example
cvs.texi(,13217) 
cvs.texi(,13218) This will cause checkins to repository directories
cvs.texi(,13219) starting with @code{cyclic-pages} to update the checked
cvs.texi(,13220) out tree in @file{/u/www/local-docs}.
cvs.texi(,13221) @c More info on some of the details?  The "sleep 2" is
cvs.texi(,13222) @c so if we are lucky the lock will be gone by the time
cvs.texi(,13223) @c we start and we can wait 2 seconds instead of 30.
cvs.texi(,13224) 
cvs.texi(,13225) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,13226) @node rcsinfo
cvs.texi(,13227) @appendixsec Rcsinfo
cvs.texi(,13228) @cindex rcsinfo (admin file)
cvs.texi(,13229) @cindex Form for log message
cvs.texi(,13230) @cindex Log message template
cvs.texi(,13231) @cindex Template for log message
cvs.texi(,13232) 
cvs.texi(,13233) The @file{rcsinfo} file can be used to specify a form to
cvs.texi(,13234) edit when filling out the commit log.  The
cvs.texi(,13235) @file{rcsinfo} file has a syntax similar to the
cvs.texi(,13236) @file{verifymsg}, @file{commitinfo} and @file{loginfo}
cvs.texi(,13237) files.  @xref{syntax}.  Unlike the other files the second
cvs.texi(,13238) part is @emph{not} a command-line template.  Instead,
cvs.texi(,13239) the part after the regular expression should be a full pathname to
cvs.texi(,13240) a file containing the log message template.
cvs.texi(,13241) 
cvs.texi(,13242) If the repository name does not match any of the
cvs.texi(,13243) regular expressions in this file, the @samp{DEFAULT}
cvs.texi(,13244) line is used, if it is specified.
cvs.texi(,13245) 
cvs.texi(,13246) All occurrences of the name @samp{ALL} appearing as a
cvs.texi(,13247) regular expression are used in addition to the first
cvs.texi(,13248) matching regular expression or @samp{DEFAULT}.
cvs.texi(,13249) 
cvs.texi(,13250) @c FIXME: should be offering advice, somewhere around
cvs.texi(,13251) @c here, about where to put the template file.  The
cvs.texi(,13252) @c verifymsg example uses /usr/cvssupport but doesn't
cvs.texi(,13253) @c say anything about what that directory is for or
cvs.texi(,13254) @c whether it is hardwired into CVS or who creates
cvs.texi(,13255) @c it or anything.  In particular we should say
cvs.texi(,13256) @c how to version control the template file.  A
cvs.texi(,13257) @c probably better answer than the /usr/cvssupport
cvs.texi(,13258) @c stuff is to use checkoutlist (with xref to the
cvs.texi(,13259) @c checkoutlist doc).
cvs.texi(,13260) @c Also I am starting to see a connection between
cvs.texi(,13261) @c this and the Keeping a checked out copy node.
cvs.texi(,13262) @c Probably want to say something about that.
cvs.texi(,13263) The log message template will be used as a default log
cvs.texi(,13264) message.  If you specify a log message with @samp{cvs
cvs.texi(,13265) commit -m @var{message}} or @samp{cvs commit -f
cvs.texi(,13266) @var{file}} that log message will override the
cvs.texi(,13267) template.
cvs.texi(,13268) 
cvs.texi(,13269) @xref{verifymsg}, for an example @file{rcsinfo}
cvs.texi(,13270) file.
cvs.texi(,13271) 
cvs.texi(,13272) When @sc{cvs} is accessing a remote repository,
cvs.texi(,13273) the contents of @file{rcsinfo} at the time a directory
cvs.texi(,13274) is first checked out will specify a template. This
cvs.texi(,13275) template will be updated on all @samp{cvs update}
cvs.texi(,13276) commands. It will also be added to new directories
cvs.texi(,13277) added with a @samp{cvs add new-directry} command.
cvs.texi(,13278) In versions of @sc{cvs} prior to version 1.12, the
cvs.texi(,13279) @file{CVS/Template} file was not updated. If the
cvs.texi(,13280) @sc{cvs} server is at version 1.12 or higher an older
cvs.texi(,13281) client may be used and the @file{CVS/Template} will
cvs.texi(,13282) be updated from the server.
cvs.texi(,13283) 
cvs.texi(,13284) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,13285) @node cvsignore
cvs.texi(,13286) @appendixsec Ignoring files via cvsignore
cvs.texi(,13287) @cindex cvsignore (admin file), global
cvs.texi(,13288) @cindex Global cvsignore
cvs.texi(,13289) @cindex Ignoring files
cvs.texi(,13290) @c -- This chapter should maybe be moved to the
cvs.texi(,13291) @c tutorial part of the manual?
cvs.texi(,13292) 
cvs.texi(,13293) There are certain file names that frequently occur
cvs.texi(,13294) inside your working copy, but that you don't want to
cvs.texi(,13295) put under @sc{cvs} control.  Examples are all the object
cvs.texi(,13296) files that you get while you compile your sources.
cvs.texi(,13297) Normally, when you run @samp{cvs update}, it prints a
cvs.texi(,13298) line for each file it encounters that it doesn't know
cvs.texi(,13299) about (@pxref{update output}).
cvs.texi(,13300) 
cvs.texi(,13301) @sc{cvs} has a list of files (or sh(1) file name patterns)
cvs.texi(,13302) that it should ignore while running @code{update},
cvs.texi(,13303) @code{import} and @code{release}.
cvs.texi(,13304) @c -- Are those the only three commands affected?
cvs.texi(,13305) This list is constructed in the following way.
cvs.texi(,13306) 
cvs.texi(,13307) @itemize @bullet
cvs.texi(,13308) @item
cvs.texi(,13309) The list is initialized to include certain file name
cvs.texi(,13310) patterns: names associated with @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,13311) administration, or with other common source control
cvs.texi(,13312) systems; common names for patch files, object files,
cvs.texi(,13313) archive files, and editor backup files; and other names
cvs.texi(,13314) that are usually artifacts of assorted utilities.
cvs.texi(,13315) Currently, the default list of ignored file name
cvs.texi(,13316) patterns is:
cvs.texi(,13317) 
cvs.texi(,13318) @cindex Ignored files
cvs.texi(,13319) @cindex Automatically ignored files
cvs.texi(,13320) @example
cvs.texi(,13321)     RCS     SCCS    CVS     CVS.adm
cvs.texi(,13322)     RCSLOG  cvslog.*
cvs.texi(,13323)     tags    TAGS
cvs.texi(,13324)     .make.state     .nse_depinfo
cvs.texi(,13325)     *~      #*      .#*     ,*      _$*     *$
cvs.texi(,13326)     *.old   *.bak   *.BAK   *.orig  *.rej   .del-*
cvs.texi(,13327)     *.a     *.olb   *.o     *.obj   *.so    *.exe
cvs.texi(,13328)     *.Z     *.elc   *.ln
cvs.texi(,13329)     core
cvs.texi(,13330) @end example
cvs.texi(,13331) 
cvs.texi(,13332) @item
cvs.texi(,13333) The per-repository list in
cvs.texi(,13334) @file{$CVSROOT/CVSROOT/cvsignore} is appended to
cvs.texi(,13335) the list, if that file exists.
cvs.texi(,13336) 
cvs.texi(,13337) @item
cvs.texi(,13338) The per-user list in @file{.cvsignore} in your home
cvs.texi(,13339) directory is appended to the list, if it exists.
cvs.texi(,13340) 
cvs.texi(,13341) @item
cvs.texi(,13342) Any entries in the environment variable
cvs.texi(,13343) @code{$CVSIGNORE} is appended to the list.
cvs.texi(,13344) 
cvs.texi(,13345) @item
cvs.texi(,13346) Any @samp{-I} options given to @sc{cvs} is appended.
cvs.texi(,13347) 
cvs.texi(,13348) @item
cvs.texi(,13349) As @sc{cvs} traverses through your directories, the contents
cvs.texi(,13350) of any @file{.cvsignore} will be appended to the list.
cvs.texi(,13351) The patterns found in @file{.cvsignore} are only valid
cvs.texi(,13352) for the directory that contains them, not for
cvs.texi(,13353) any sub-directories.
cvs.texi(,13354) @end itemize
cvs.texi(,13355) 
cvs.texi(,13356) In any of the 5 places listed above, a single
cvs.texi(,13357) exclamation mark (@samp{!}) clears the ignore list.
cvs.texi(,13358) This can be used if you want to store any file which
cvs.texi(,13359) normally is ignored by @sc{cvs}.
cvs.texi(,13360) 
cvs.texi(,13361) Specifying @samp{-I !} to @code{cvs import} will import
cvs.texi(,13362) everything, which is generally what you want to do if
cvs.texi(,13363) you are importing files from a pristine distribution or
cvs.texi(,13364) any other source which is known to not contain any
cvs.texi(,13365) extraneous files.  However, looking at the rules above
cvs.texi(,13366) you will see there is a fly in the ointment; if the
cvs.texi(,13367) distribution contains any @file{.cvsignore} files, then
cvs.texi(,13368) the patterns from those files will be processed even if
cvs.texi(,13369) @samp{-I !} is specified.  The only workaround is to
cvs.texi(,13370) remove the @file{.cvsignore} files in order to do the
cvs.texi(,13371) import.  Because this is awkward, in the future
cvs.texi(,13372) @samp{-I !} might be modified to override
cvs.texi(,13373) @file{.cvsignore} files in each directory.
cvs.texi(,13374) 
cvs.texi(,13375) Note that the syntax of the ignore files consists of a
cvs.texi(,13376) series of lines, each of which contains a space
cvs.texi(,13377) separated list of filenames.  This offers no clean way
cvs.texi(,13378) to specify filenames which contain spaces, but you can
cvs.texi(,13379) use a workaround like @file{foo?bar} to match a file
cvs.texi(,13380) named @file{foo bar} (it also matches @file{fooxbar}
cvs.texi(,13381) and the like).  Also note that there is currently no
cvs.texi(,13382) way to specify comments.
cvs.texi(,13383) @c FIXCVS?  I don't _like_ this syntax at all, but
cvs.texi(,13384) @c changing it raises all the usual compatibility
cvs.texi(,13385) @c issues and I'm also not sure what to change it to.
cvs.texi(,13386) 
cvs.texi(,13387) @node checkoutlist
cvs.texi(,13388) @appendixsec The checkoutlist file
cvs.texi(,13389) @cindex checkoutlist
cvs.texi(,13390) 
cvs.texi(,13391) It may be helpful to use @sc{cvs} to maintain your own
cvs.texi(,13392) files in the @file{CVSROOT} directory.  For example,
cvs.texi(,13393) suppose that you have a script @file{logcommit.pl}
cvs.texi(,13394) which you run by including the following line in the
cvs.texi(,13395) @file{commitinfo} administrative file:
cvs.texi(,13396) 
cvs.texi(,13397) @example
cvs.texi(,13398) ALL   $CVSROOT/CVSROOT/logcommit.pl
cvs.texi(,13399) @end example
cvs.texi(,13400) 
cvs.texi(,13401) To maintain @file{logcommit.pl} with @sc{cvs} you would
cvs.texi(,13402) add the following line to the @file{checkoutlist}
cvs.texi(,13403) administrative file:
cvs.texi(,13404) 
cvs.texi(,13405) @example
cvs.texi(,13406) logcommit.pl
cvs.texi(,13407) @end example
cvs.texi(,13408) 
cvs.texi(,13409) The format of @file{checkoutlist} is one line for each
cvs.texi(,13410) file that you want to maintain using @sc{cvs}, giving
cvs.texi(,13411) the name of the file.
cvs.texi(,13412) 
cvs.texi(,13413) After setting up @file{checkoutlist} in this fashion,
cvs.texi(,13414) the files listed there will function just like
cvs.texi(,13415) @sc{cvs}'s built-in administrative files.  For example,
cvs.texi(,13416) when checking in one of the files you should get a
cvs.texi(,13417) message such as:
cvs.texi(,13418) 
cvs.texi(,13419) @example
cvs.texi(,13420) cvs commit: Rebuilding administrative file database
cvs.texi(,13421) @end example
cvs.texi(,13422) 
cvs.texi(,13423) @noindent
cvs.texi(,13424) and the checked out copy in the @file{CVSROOT}
cvs.texi(,13425) directory should be updated.
cvs.texi(,13426) 
cvs.texi(,13427) Note that listing @file{passwd} (@pxref{Password
cvs.texi(,13428) authentication server}) in @file{checkoutlist} is not
cvs.texi(,13429) recommended for security reasons.
cvs.texi(,13430) 
cvs.texi(,13431) For information about keeping a checkout out copy in a
cvs.texi(,13432) more general context than the one provided by
cvs.texi(,13433) @file{checkoutlist}, see @ref{Keeping a checked out
cvs.texi(,13434) copy}.
cvs.texi(,13435) 
cvs.texi(,13436) @c - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
cvs.texi(,13437) @node history file
cvs.texi(,13438) @appendixsec The history file
cvs.texi(,13439) @cindex History file
cvs.texi(,13440) @cindex Log information, saving
cvs.texi(,13441) 
cvs.texi(,13442) The file @file{$CVSROOT/CVSROOT/history} is used
cvs.texi(,13443) to log information for the @code{history} command
cvs.texi(,13444) (@pxref{history}).  This file must be created to turn
cvs.texi(,13445) on logging.  This is done automatically if the
cvs.texi(,13446) @code{cvs init} command is used to set up the
cvs.texi(,13447) repository (@pxref{Creating a repository}).
cvs.texi(,13448) 
cvs.texi(,13449) The file format of the @file{history} file is
cvs.texi(,13450) documented only in comments in the @sc{cvs} source
cvs.texi(,13451) code, but generally programs should use the @code{cvs
cvs.texi(,13452) history} command to access it anyway, in case the
cvs.texi(,13453) format changes with future releases of @sc{cvs}.
cvs.texi(,13454) 
cvs.texi(,13455) @node Variables
cvs.texi(,13456) @appendixsec Expansions in administrative files
cvs.texi(,13457) @cindex Internal variables
cvs.texi(,13458) @cindex Variables
cvs.texi(,13459) 
cvs.texi(,13460) Sometimes in writing an administrative file, you might
cvs.texi(,13461) want the file to be able to know various things based
cvs.texi(,13462) on environment @sc{cvs} is running in.  There are
cvs.texi(,13463) several mechanisms to do that.
cvs.texi(,13464) 
cvs.texi(,13465) To find the home directory of the user running @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,13466) (from the @code{HOME} environment variable), use
cvs.texi(,13467) @samp{~} followed by @samp{/} or the end of the line.
cvs.texi(,13468) Likewise for the home directory of @var{user}, use
cvs.texi(,13469) @samp{~@var{user}}.  These variables are expanded on
cvs.texi(,13470) the server machine, and don't get any reasonable
cvs.texi(,13471) expansion if pserver (@pxref{Password authenticated})
cvs.texi(,13472) is in use; therefore user variables (see below) may be
cvs.texi(,13473) a better choice to customize behavior based on the user
cvs.texi(,13474) running @sc{cvs}.
cvs.texi(,13475) @c Based on these limitations, should we deprecate ~?
cvs.texi(,13476) @c What is it good for?  Are people using it?
cvs.texi(,13477) 
cvs.texi(,13478) One may want to know about various pieces of
cvs.texi(,13479) information internal to @sc{cvs}.  A @sc{cvs} internal
cvs.texi(,13480) variable has the syntax @code{$@{@var{variable}@}},
cvs.texi(,13481) where @var{variable} starts with a letter and consists
cvs.texi(,13482) of alphanumeric characters and @samp{_}.  If the
cvs.texi(,13483) character following @var{variable} is a
cvs.texi(,13484) non-alphanumeric character other than @samp{_}, the
cvs.texi(,13485) @samp{@{} and @samp{@}} can be omitted.  The @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,13486) internal variables are:
cvs.texi(,13487) 
cvs.texi(,13488) @table @code
cvs.texi(,13489) @item CVSROOT
cvs.texi(,13490) @cindex CVSROOT, internal variable
cvs.texi(,13491) This is the absolute path to the current @sc{cvs} root directory.
cvs.texi(,13492) @xref{Repository}, for a description of the various
cvs.texi(,13493) ways to specify this, but note that the internal
cvs.texi(,13494) variable contains just the directory and not any
cvs.texi(,13495) of the access method information.
cvs.texi(,13496) 
cvs.texi(,13497) @item RCSBIN
cvs.texi(,13498) @cindex RCSBIN, internal variable
cvs.texi(,13499) In @sc{cvs} 1.9.18 and older, this specified the
cvs.texi(,13500) directory where @sc{cvs} was looking for @sc{rcs}
cvs.texi(,13501) programs.  Because @sc{cvs} no longer runs @sc{rcs}
cvs.texi(,13502) programs, specifying this internal variable is now an
cvs.texi(,13503) error.
cvs.texi(,13504) 
cvs.texi(,13505) @item CVSEDITOR
cvs.texi(,13506) @cindex CVSEDITOR, internal variable
cvs.texi(,13507) @itemx EDITOR
cvs.texi(,13508) @cindex EDITOR, internal variable
cvs.texi(,13509) @itemx VISUAL
cvs.texi(,13510) @cindex VISUAL, internal variable
cvs.texi(,13511) These all expand to the same value, which is the editor
cvs.texi(,13512) that @sc{cvs} is using.  @xref{Global options}, for how
cvs.texi(,13513) to specify this.
cvs.texi(,13514) 
cvs.texi(,13515) @item USER
cvs.texi(,13516) @cindex USER, internal variable
cvs.texi(,13517) Username of the user running @sc{cvs} (on the @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,13518) server machine).
cvs.texi(,13519) When using pserver, this is the user specified in the repository
cvs.texi(,13520) specification which need not be the same as the username the
cvs.texi(,13521) server is running as (@pxref{Password authentication server}).
cvs.texi(,13522) Do not confuse this with the environment variable of the same name.
cvs.texi(,13523) @end table
cvs.texi(,13524) 
cvs.texi(,13525) If you want to pass a value to the administrative files
cvs.texi(,13526) which the user who is running @sc{cvs} can specify,
cvs.texi(,13527) use a user variable.
cvs.texi(,13528) @cindex User variables
cvs.texi(,13529) To expand a user variable, the
cvs.texi(,13530) administrative file contains
cvs.texi(,13531) @code{$@{=@var{variable}@}}.  To set a user variable,
cvs.texi(,13532) specify the global option @samp{-s} to @sc{cvs}, with
cvs.texi(,13533) argument @code{@var{variable}=@var{value}}.  It may be
cvs.texi(,13534) particularly useful to specify this option via
cvs.texi(,13535) @file{.cvsrc} (@pxref{~/.cvsrc}).
cvs.texi(,13536) 
cvs.texi(,13537) For example, if you want the administrative file to
cvs.texi(,13538) refer to a test directory you might create a user
cvs.texi(,13539) variable @code{TESTDIR}.  Then if @sc{cvs} is invoked
cvs.texi(,13540) as
cvs.texi(,13541) 
cvs.texi(,13542) @example
cvs.texi(,13543) cvs -s TESTDIR=/work/local/tests
cvs.texi(,13544) @end example
cvs.texi(,13545) 
cvs.texi(,13546) @noindent
cvs.texi(,13547) and the
cvs.texi(,13548) administrative file contains @code{sh
cvs.texi(,13549) $@{=TESTDIR@}/runtests}, then that string is expanded
cvs.texi(,13550) to @code{sh /work/local/tests/runtests}.
cvs.texi(,13551) 
cvs.texi(,13552) All other strings containing @samp{$} are reserved;
cvs.texi(,13553) there is no way to quote a @samp{$} character so that
cvs.texi(,13554) @samp{$} represents itself.
cvs.texi(,13555) 
cvs.texi(,13556) Environment variables passed to administrative files are:
cvs.texi(,13557) 
cvs.texi(,13558) @table @code
cvs.texi(,13559) @cindex environment variables, passed to administrative files
cvs.texi(,13560) 
cvs.texi(,13561) @item CVS_USER
cvs.texi(,13562) @cindex CVS_USER, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13563) The @sc{cvs}-specific username provided by the user, if it
cvs.texi(,13564) can be provided (currently just for the pserver access
cvs.texi(,13565) method), and to the empty string otherwise.  (@code{CVS_USER}
cvs.texi(,13566) and @code{USER} may differ when @file{$CVSROOT/CVSROOT/passwd}
cvs.texi(,13567) is used to map @sc{cvs} usernames to system usernames.)
cvs.texi(,13568) 
cvs.texi(,13569) @item LOGNAME
cvs.texi(,13570) @cindex LOGNAME, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13571) The username of the system user.
cvs.texi(,13572) 
cvs.texi(,13573) @item USER
cvs.texi(,13574) @cindex USER, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13575) Same as @code{LOGNAME}.
cvs.texi(,13576) Do not confuse this with the internal variable of the same name.
cvs.texi(,13577) @end table
cvs.texi(,13578) 
cvs.texi(,13579) @node config
cvs.texi(,13580) @appendixsec The CVSROOT/config configuration file
cvs.texi(,13581) 
cvs.texi(,13582) @cindex config, in CVSROOT
cvs.texi(,13583) @cindex CVSROOT/config
cvs.texi(,13584) 
cvs.texi(,13585) The administrative file @file{config} contains various
cvs.texi(,13586) miscellaneous settings which affect the behavior of
cvs.texi(,13587) @sc{cvs}.  The syntax is slightly different from the
cvs.texi(,13588) other administrative files.  Variables are not
cvs.texi(,13589) expanded.  Lines which start with @samp{#} are
cvs.texi(,13590) considered comments.
cvs.texi(,13591) @c FIXME: where do we define comments for the other
cvs.texi(,13592) @c administrative files.
cvs.texi(,13593) Other lines consist of a keyword, @samp{=}, and a
cvs.texi(,13594) value.  Note that this syntax is very strict.
cvs.texi(,13595) Extraneous spaces or tabs are not permitted.
cvs.texi(,13596) @c See comments in parseinfo.c:parse_config for more
cvs.texi(,13597) @c discussion of this strictness.
cvs.texi(,13598) 
cvs.texi(,13599) Currently defined keywords are:
cvs.texi(,13600) 
cvs.texi(,13601) @table @code
cvs.texi(,13602) @cindex RCSBIN, in CVSROOT/config
cvs.texi(,13603) @item RCSBIN=@var{bindir}
cvs.texi(,13604) For @sc{cvs} 1.9.12 through 1.9.18, this setting told
cvs.texi(,13605) @sc{cvs} to look for @sc{rcs} programs in the
cvs.texi(,13606) @var{bindir} directory.  Current versions of @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,13607) do not run @sc{rcs} programs; for compatibility this
cvs.texi(,13608) setting is accepted, but it does nothing.
cvs.texi(,13609) 
cvs.texi(,13610) @cindex SystemAuth, in CVSROOT/config
cvs.texi(,13611) @item SystemAuth=@var{value}
cvs.texi(,13612) If @var{value} is @samp{yes}, then pserver should check
cvs.texi(,13613) for users in the system's user database if not found in
cvs.texi(,13614) @file{CVSROOT/passwd}.  If it is @samp{no}, then all
cvs.texi(,13615) pserver users must exist in @file{CVSROOT/passwd}.
cvs.texi(,13616) The default is @samp{yes}.  For more on pserver, see
cvs.texi(,13617) @ref{Password authenticated}.
cvs.texi(,13618) 
cvs.texi(,13628) 
cvs.texi(,13629) @cindex TopLevelAdmin, in CVSROOT/config
cvs.texi(,13630) @item TopLevelAdmin=@var{value}
cvs.texi(,13631) Modify the @samp{checkout} command to create a
cvs.texi(,13632) @samp{CVS} directory at the top level of the new
cvs.texi(,13633) working directory, in addition to @samp{CVS}
cvs.texi(,13634) directories created within checked-out directories.
cvs.texi(,13635) The default value is @samp{no}.
cvs.texi(,13636) 
cvs.texi(,13637) This option is useful if you find yourself performing
cvs.texi(,13638) many commands at the top level of your working
cvs.texi(,13639) directory, rather than in one of the checked out
cvs.texi(,13640) subdirectories.  The @file{CVS} directory created there
cvs.texi(,13641) will mean you don't have to specify @code{CVSROOT} for
cvs.texi(,13642) each command.  It also provides a place for the
cvs.texi(,13643) @file{CVS/Template} file (@pxref{Working directory
cvs.texi(,13644) storage}).
cvs.texi(,13645) 
cvs.texi(,13646) @cindex LockDir, in CVSROOT/config
cvs.texi(,13647) @item LockDir=@var{directory}
cvs.texi(,13648) Put @sc{cvs} lock files in @var{directory} rather than
cvs.texi(,13649) directly in the repository.  This is useful if you want
cvs.texi(,13650) to let users read from the repository while giving them
cvs.texi(,13651) write access only to @var{directory}, not to the
cvs.texi(,13652) repository.
cvs.texi(,13653) It can also be used to put the locks on a very fast
cvs.texi(,13654) in-memory file system to speed up locking and unlocking
cvs.texi(,13655) the repository.
cvs.texi(,13656) You need to create @var{directory}, but
cvs.texi(,13657) @sc{cvs} will create subdirectories of @var{directory} as it
cvs.texi(,13658) needs them.  For information on @sc{cvs} locks, see
cvs.texi(,13659) @ref{Concurrency}.
cvs.texi(,13660) 
cvs.texi(,13661) @c Mention this in Compatibility section?
cvs.texi(,13662) Before enabling the LockDir option, make sure that you
cvs.texi(,13663) have tracked down and removed any copies of @sc{cvs} 1.9 or
cvs.texi(,13664) older.  Such versions neither support LockDir, nor will
cvs.texi(,13665) give an error indicating that they don't support it.
cvs.texi(,13666) The result, if this is allowed to happen, is that some
cvs.texi(,13667) @sc{cvs} users will put the locks one place, and others will
cvs.texi(,13668) put them another place, and therefore the repository
cvs.texi(,13669) could become corrupted.  @sc{cvs} 1.10 does not support
cvs.texi(,13670) LockDir but it will print a warning if run on a
cvs.texi(,13671) repository with LockDir enabled.
cvs.texi(,13672) 
cvs.texi(,13673) @cindex LogHistory, in CVSROOT/config
cvs.texi(,13674) @item LogHistory=@var{value}
cvs.texi(,13675) Control what is logged to the @file{CVSROOT/history} file (@pxref{history}).
cvs.texi(,13676) Default of @samp{TOEFWUCGMAR} (or simply @samp{all}) will log
cvs.texi(,13677) all transactions.  Any subset of the default is
cvs.texi(,13678) legal.  (For example, to only log transactions that modify the
cvs.texi(,13679) @file{*,v} files, use @samp{LogHistory=TMAR}.)
cvs.texi(,13680) 
cvs.texi(,13681) @cindex RereadLogAfterVerify, in CVSROOT/config
cvs.texi(,13682) @cindex @file{verifymsg}, changing the log message
cvs.texi(,13683) @item RereadLogAfterVerify=@var{value}
cvs.texi(,13684) Modify the @samp{commit} command such that CVS will reread the
cvs.texi(,13685) log message after running the program specified by @file{verifymsg}.
cvs.texi(,13686) @var{value} may be one of @samp{yes} or @samp{always}, indicating that
cvs.texi(,13687) the log message should always be reread; @samp{no}
cvs.texi(,13688) or @samp{never}, indicating that it should never be
cvs.texi(,13689) reread; or @var{value} may be @samp{stat}, indicating
cvs.texi(,13690) that the file should be checked with the filesystem
cvs.texi(,13691) @samp{stat()} function to see if it has changed (see warning below)
cvs.texi(,13692) before rereading.  The default value is @samp{always}.
cvs.texi(,13693) 
cvs.texi(,13694) @strong{Note: the `stat' mode can cause CVS to pause for up to
cvs.texi(,13695) one extra second per directory committed.  This can be less IO and
cvs.texi(,13696) CPU intensive but is not recommended for use with large repositories}
cvs.texi(,13697) 
cvs.texi(,13698) @xref{verifymsg}, for more information on how verifymsg
cvs.texi(,13699) may be used.
cvs.texi(,13700) 
cvs.texi(,13701) @cindex UserAdminOptions, in CVSROOT/config
cvs.texi(,13702) @item UserAdminOptions=@var{value}
cvs.texi(,13703) Control what options will be allowed with the @code{cvs admin}
cvs.texi(,13704) command (@pxref{admin}) for users not in the @code{cvsadmin} group.
cvs.texi(,13705) The @var{value} string is a list of single character options
cvs.texi(,13706) which should be allowed.  If a user who is not a member of the
cvs.texi(,13707) @code{cvsadmin} group tries to execute any @code{cvs admin}
cvs.texi(,13708) option which is not listed they will will receive an error message
cvs.texi(,13709) reporting that the option is restricted.
cvs.texi(,13710) 
cvs.texi(,13711) If no @code{cvsadmin} group exists on the server, @sc{cvs} will
cvs.texi(,13712) ignore the @code{UserAdminOptions} keyword (@pxref{admin}).
cvs.texi(,13713) 
cvs.texi(,13714) When not specified, @code{UserAdminOptions} defaults to
cvs.texi(,13715) @samp{k}.  In other words, it defaults to allowing
cvs.texi(,13716) users outside of the @code{cvsadmin} group to use the
cvs.texi(,13717) @code{cvs admin} command only to change the default keyword
cvs.texi(,13718) expansion mode for files.
cvs.texi(,13719) 
cvs.texi(,13720) As an example, to restrict users not in the @code{cvsadmin}
cvs.texi(,13721) group to using @code{cvs admin} to change the default keyword
cvs.texi(,13722) substitution mode, lock revisions, unlock revisions, and
cvs.texi(,13723) replace the log message, use @samp{UserAdminOptions=klum}.
cvs.texi(,13724) @end table
cvs.texi(,13725) 
cvs.texi(,13726) @c ---------------------------------------------------------------------
cvs.texi(,13727) @node Environment variables
cvs.texi(,13728) @appendix All environment variables which affect CVS
cvs.texi(,13729) @cindex Environment variables
cvs.texi(,13730) @cindex Reference manual for variables
cvs.texi(,13731) 
cvs.texi(,13732) This is a complete list of all environment variables
cvs.texi(,13733) that affect @sc{cvs}.
cvs.texi(,13734) 
cvs.texi(,13735) @table @code
cvs.texi(,13736) @cindex CVSIGNORE, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13737) @item $CVSIGNORE
cvs.texi(,13738) A whitespace-separated list of file name patterns that
cvs.texi(,13739) @sc{cvs} should ignore. @xref{cvsignore}.
cvs.texi(,13740) 
cvs.texi(,13741) @cindex CVSWRAPPERS, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13742) @item $CVSWRAPPERS
cvs.texi(,13743) A whitespace-separated list of file name patterns that
cvs.texi(,13744) @sc{cvs} should treat as wrappers. @xref{Wrappers}.
cvs.texi(,13745) 
cvs.texi(,13746) @cindex CVSREAD, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13747) @cindex Read-only files, and CVSREAD
cvs.texi(,13748) @item $CVSREAD
cvs.texi(,13749) If this is set, @code{checkout} and @code{update} will
cvs.texi(,13750) try hard to make the files in your working directory
cvs.texi(,13751) read-only.  When this is not set, the default behavior
cvs.texi(,13752) is to permit modification of your working files.
cvs.texi(,13753) 
cvs.texi(,13754) @cindex CVSREADONLYFS, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13755) @item $CVSREADONLYFS
cvs.texi(,13756) Turns on read-only repository mode. This allows one to
cvs.texi(,13757) check out from a read-only repository, such as within
cvs.texi(,13758) an anoncvs server, or from a CDROM repository.
cvs.texi(,13759) 
cvs.texi(,13760) It has the same effect as if the @samp{-R} command-line
cvs.texi(,13761) option is used. This can also allow the use of
cvs.texi(,13762) read-only NFS repositories.
cvs.texi(,13763) 
cvs.texi(,13764) @item $CVSUMASK
cvs.texi(,13765) Controls permissions of files in the repository.  See
cvs.texi(,13766) @ref{File permissions}.
cvs.texi(,13767) 
cvs.texi(,13768) @item $CVSROOT
cvs.texi(,13769) Should contain the full pathname to the root of the @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,13770) source repository (where the @sc{rcs} files are
cvs.texi(,13771) kept).  This information must be available to @sc{cvs} for
cvs.texi(,13772) most commands to execute; if @code{$CVSROOT} is not set,
cvs.texi(,13773) or if you wish to override it for one invocation, you
cvs.texi(,13774) can supply it on the command line: @samp{cvs -d cvsroot
cvs.texi(,13775) cvs_command@dots{}} Once you have checked out a working
cvs.texi(,13776) directory, @sc{cvs} stores the appropriate root (in
cvs.texi(,13777) the file @file{CVS/Root}), so normally you only need to
cvs.texi(,13778) worry about this when initially checking out a working
cvs.texi(,13779) directory.
cvs.texi(,13780) 
cvs.texi(,13781) @item $CVSEDITOR
cvs.texi(,13782) @cindex CVSEDITOR, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13783) @itemx $EDITOR
cvs.texi(,13784) @cindex EDITOR, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13785) @itemx $VISUAL
cvs.texi(,13786) @cindex VISUAL, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13787) Specifies the program to use for recording log messages
cvs.texi(,13788) during commit.  @code{$CVSEDITOR} overrides
cvs.texi(,13789) @code{$EDITOR}, which overrides @code{$VISUAL}.
cvs.texi(,13790) See @ref{Committing your changes} for more or
cvs.texi(,13791) @ref{Global options} for alternative ways of specifying a
cvs.texi(,13792) log editor.
cvs.texi(,13793) 
cvs.texi(,13794) @cindex PATH, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13795) @item $PATH
cvs.texi(,13796) If @code{$RCSBIN} is not set, and no path is compiled
cvs.texi(,13797) into @sc{cvs}, it will use @code{$PATH} to try to find all
cvs.texi(,13798) programs it uses.
cvs.texi(,13799) 
cvs.texi(,13800) @cindex HOME, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13801) @item $HOME
cvs.texi(,13802) @cindex HOMEPATH, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13803) @item $HOMEPATH
cvs.texi(,13804) @cindex HOMEDRIVE, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13805) @item $HOMEDRIVE
cvs.texi(,13806) Used to locate the directory where the @file{.cvsrc}
cvs.texi(,13807) file, and other such files, are searched.  On Unix, @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,13808) just checks for @code{HOME}.  On Windows NT, the system will
cvs.texi(,13809) set @code{HOMEDRIVE}, for example to @samp{d:} and @code{HOMEPATH},
cvs.texi(,13810) for example to @file{\joe}.  On Windows 95, you'll
cvs.texi(,13811) probably need to set @code{HOMEDRIVE} and @code{HOMEPATH} yourself.
cvs.texi(,13812) @c We are being vague about whether HOME works on
cvs.texi(,13813) @c Windows; see long comment in windows-NT/filesubr.c.
cvs.texi(,13814) 
cvs.texi(,13815) @cindex CVS_RSH, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13816) @item $CVS_RSH
cvs.texi(,13817) Specifies the external program which @sc{cvs} connects with,
cvs.texi(,13818) when @code{:ext:} access method is specified.
cvs.texi(,13819) @pxref{Connecting via rsh}.
cvs.texi(,13820) 
cvs.texi(,13821) @item $CVS_SERVER
cvs.texi(,13822) Used in client-server mode when accessing a remote
cvs.texi(,13823) repository using @sc{rsh}.  It specifies the name of
cvs.texi(,13824) the program to start on the server side (and any
cvs.texi(,13825) necessary arguments) when accessing a remote repository
cvs.texi(,13826) using the @code{:ext:}, @code{:fork:}, or @code{:server:} access methods.
cvs.texi(,13827) The default value for @code{:ext:} and @code{:server:} is @code{cvs};
cvs.texi(,13828) the default value for @code{:fork:} is the name used to run the client.
cvs.texi(,13829) @pxref{Connecting via rsh}
cvs.texi(,13830) 
cvs.texi(,13831) @item $CVS_PASSFILE
cvs.texi(,13832) Used in client-server mode when accessing the @code{cvs
cvs.texi(,13833) login server}.  Default value is @file{$HOME/.cvspass}.
cvs.texi(,13834) @pxref{Password authentication client}
cvs.texi(,13835) 
cvs.texi(,13836) @item $CVS_CLIENT_PORT
cvs.texi(,13837) Used in client-server mode to set the port to use when accessing the server
cvs.texi(,13838) via Kerberos, GSSAPI, or @sc{cvs}'s password authentication protocol
cvs.texi(,13839) if the port is not specified in the CVSROOT.
cvs.texi(,13840) @pxref{Remote repositories}
cvs.texi(,13841) 
cvs.texi(,13842) @cindex CVS_RCMD_PORT, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13843) @item $CVS_RCMD_PORT
cvs.texi(,13844) Used in client-server mode.  If set, specifies the port
cvs.texi(,13845) number to be used when accessing the @sc{rcmd} demon on
cvs.texi(,13846) the server side. (Currently not used for Unix clients).
cvs.texi(,13847) 
cvs.texi(,13848) @cindex CVS_CLIENT_LOG, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13849) @item $CVS_CLIENT_LOG
cvs.texi(,13850) Used for debugging only in client-server
cvs.texi(,13851) mode.  If set, everything sent to the server is logged
cvs.texi(,13852) into @file{@code{$CVS_CLIENT_LOG}.in} and everything
cvs.texi(,13853) sent from the server is logged into
cvs.texi(,13854) @file{@code{$CVS_CLIENT_LOG}.out}.
cvs.texi(,13855) 
cvs.texi(,13856) @cindex CVS_SERVER_SLEEP, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13857) @item $CVS_SERVER_SLEEP
cvs.texi(,13858) Used only for debugging the server side in
cvs.texi(,13859) client-server mode.  If set, delays the start of the
cvs.texi(,13860) server child process the specified amount of
cvs.texi(,13861) seconds so that you can attach to it with a debugger.
cvs.texi(,13862) 
cvs.texi(,13863) @cindex CVS_IGNORE_REMOTE_ROOT, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13864) @item $CVS_IGNORE_REMOTE_ROOT
cvs.texi(,13865) For @sc{cvs} 1.10 and older, setting this variable
cvs.texi(,13866) prevents @sc{cvs} from overwriting the @file{CVS/Root}
cvs.texi(,13867) file when the @samp{-d} global option is specified.
cvs.texi(,13868) Later versions of @sc{cvs} do not rewrite
cvs.texi(,13869) @file{CVS/Root}, so @code{CVS_IGNORE_REMOTE_ROOT} has no
cvs.texi(,13870) effect.
cvs.texi(,13871) 
cvs.texi(,13872) @cindex CVS_LOCAL_BRANCH_NUM, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13873) @item $CVS_LOCAL_BRANCH_NUM
cvs.texi(,13874) Setting this variable allows some control over the
cvs.texi(,13875) branch number that is assigned. This is specifically to
cvs.texi(,13876) support the local commit feature of CVSup. If one sets
cvs.texi(,13877) @code{CVS_LOCAL_BRANCH_NUM} to (say) 1000 then branches
cvs.texi(,13878) the local repository, the revision numbers will look
cvs.texi(,13879) like 1.66.1000.xx. There is almost a dead-set certainty
cvs.texi(,13880) that there will be no conflicts with version numbers.
cvs.texi(,13881) 
cvs.texi(,13882) @cindex COMSPEC, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13883) @item $COMSPEC
cvs.texi(,13884) Used under OS/2 only.  It specifies the name of the
cvs.texi(,13885) command interpreter and defaults to @sc{cmd.exe}.
cvs.texi(,13886) 
cvs.texi(,13887) @cindex TMPDIR, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13888) @item $TMPDIR
cvs.texi(,13889) @cindex TMP, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13890) @itemx $TMP
cvs.texi(,13891) @cindex TEMP, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13892) @itemx $TEMP
cvs.texi(,13893) @cindex Temporary files, location of
cvs.texi(,13894) @c This is quite nuts.  We don't talk about tempnam
cvs.texi(,13895) @c or mkstemp which we sometimes use.  The discussion
cvs.texi(,13896) @c of "Global options" is semi-incoherent.
cvs.texi(,13897) @c I'm not even sure those are the only inaccuracies.
cvs.texi(,13898) @c Furthermore, the conventions are
cvs.texi(,13899) @c pretty crazy and they should be simplified.
cvs.texi(,13900) Directory in which temporary files are located.
cvs.texi(,13901) The @sc{cvs} server uses
cvs.texi(,13902) @code{TMPDIR}.  @xref{Global options}, for a
cvs.texi(,13903) description of how to specify this.
cvs.texi(,13904) Some parts of @sc{cvs} will always use @file{/tmp} (via
cvs.texi(,13905) the @code{tmpnam} function provided by the system).
cvs.texi(,13906) 
cvs.texi(,13907) On Windows NT, @code{TMP} is used (via the @code{_tempnam}
cvs.texi(,13908) function provided by the system).
cvs.texi(,13909) 
cvs.texi(,13910) The @code{patch} program which is used by the @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,13911) client uses @code{TMPDIR}, and if it is not set, uses
cvs.texi(,13912) @file{/tmp} (at least with GNU patch 2.1).  Note that
cvs.texi(,13913) if your server and client are both running @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,13914) 1.9.10 or later, @sc{cvs} will not invoke an external
cvs.texi(,13915) @code{patch} program.
cvs.texi(,13916) 
cvs.texi(,13917) @cindex CVS_PID, environment variable
cvs.texi(,13918) @item $CVS_PID
cvs.texi(,13919) This is the process identification (aka pid) number of
cvs.texi(,13920) the @sc{cvs} process. It is often useful in the
cvs.texi(,13921) programs and/or scripts specified by the
cvs.texi(,13922) @file{commitinfo}, @file{verifymsg}, @file{loginfo}
cvs.texi(,13923) files.
cvs.texi(,13924) @end table
cvs.texi(,13925) 
cvs.texi(,13926) @node Compatibility
cvs.texi(,13927) @appendix Compatibility between CVS Versions
cvs.texi(,13928) 
cvs.texi(,13929) @cindex CVS, versions of
cvs.texi(,13930) @cindex Versions, of CVS
cvs.texi(,13931) @cindex Compatibility, between CVS versions
cvs.texi(,13932) @c We don't mention versions older than CVS 1.3
cvs.texi(,13933) @c on the theory that it would clutter it up for the vast
cvs.texi(,13934) @c majority of people, who don't have anything that old.
cvs.texi(,13935) @c
cvs.texi(,13936) The repository format is compatible going back to
cvs.texi(,13937) @sc{cvs} 1.3.  But see @ref{Watches Compatibility}, if
cvs.texi(,13938) you have copies of @sc{cvs} 1.6 or older and you want
cvs.texi(,13939) to use the optional developer communication features.
cvs.texi(,13940) @c If you "cvs rm" and commit using 1.3, then you'll
cvs.texi(,13941) @c want to run "rcs -sdead <file,v>" on each of the
cvs.texi(,13942) @c files in the Attic if you then want 1.5 and
cvs.texi(,13943) @c later to recognize those files as dead (I think the
cvs.texi(,13944) @c symptom if this is not done is that files reappear
cvs.texi(,13945) @c in joins).  (Wait: the above will work but really to
cvs.texi(,13946) @c be strictly correct we should suggest checking
cvs.texi(,13947) @c in a new revision rather than just changing the
cvs.texi(,13948) @c state of the head revision, shouldn't we?).
cvs.texi(,13949) @c The old convert.sh script was for this, but it never
cvs.texi(,13950) @c did get updated to reflect use of the RCS "dead"
cvs.texi(,13951) @c state.
cvs.texi(,13952) @c Note: this is tricky to document without confusing
cvs.texi(,13953) @c people--need to carefully say what CVS version we
cvs.texi(,13954) @c are talking about and keep in mind the distinction
cvs.texi(,13955) @c between a
cvs.texi(,13956) @c repository created with 1.3 and on which one now
cvs.texi(,13957) @c uses 1.5+, and a repository on which one wants to
cvs.texi(,13958) @c use both versions side by side (e.g. during a
cvs.texi(,13959) @c transition period).
cvs.texi(,13960) @c Wait, can't CVS just detect the case in which a file
cvs.texi(,13961) @c is in the Attic but the head revision is not dead?
cvs.texi(,13962) @c Not sure whether this should produce a warning or
cvs.texi(,13963) @c something, and probably needs further thought, but
cvs.texi(,13964) @c it would appear that the situation can be detected.
cvs.texi(,13965) @c
cvs.texi(,13966) @c We might want to separate out the 1.3 compatibility
cvs.texi(,13967) @c section (for repository & working directory) from the
cvs.texi(,13968) @c rest--that might help avoid confusing people who
cvs.texi(,13969) @c are upgrading (for example) from 1.6 to 1.8.
cvs.texi(,13970) @c
cvs.texi(,13971) @c A minor incompatibility is if a current version of CVS
cvs.texi(,13972) @c puts "Nfoo" into CVS/Tag, then CVS 1.9 or older will
cvs.texi(,13973) @c see this as if there is no tag.  Seems to me this is
cvs.texi(,13974) @c too obscure to mention.
cvs.texi(,13975) 
cvs.texi(,13976) The working directory format is compatible going back
cvs.texi(,13977) to @sc{cvs} 1.5.  It did change between @sc{cvs} 1.3
cvs.texi(,13978) and @sc{cvs} 1.5.  If you run @sc{cvs} 1.5 or newer on
cvs.texi(,13979) a working directory checked out with @sc{cvs} 1.3,
cvs.texi(,13980) @sc{cvs} will convert it, but to go back to @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,13981) 1.3 you need to check out a new working directory with
cvs.texi(,13982) @sc{cvs} 1.3.
cvs.texi(,13983) 
cvs.texi(,13984) The remote protocol is interoperable going back to @sc{cvs} 1.5, but no
cvs.texi(,13985) further (1.5 was the first official release with the remote protocol,
cvs.texi(,13986) but some older versions might still be floating around).  In many
cvs.texi(,13987) cases you need to upgrade both the client and the server to take
cvs.texi(,13988) advantage of new features and bugfixes, however.
cvs.texi(,13989) 
cvs.texi(,13990) @c Perhaps should be saying something here about the
cvs.texi(,13991) @c "D" lines in Entries (written by CVS 1.9; 1.8 and
cvs.texi(,13992) @c older don't use them).  These are supposed to be
cvs.texi(,13993) @c compatible in both directions, but I'm not sure
cvs.texi(,13994) @c they quite are 100%.  One common gripe is if you
cvs.texi(,13995) @c "rm -r" a directory and 1.9 gets confused, as it
cvs.texi(,13996) @c still sees it in Entries.  That one is fixed in
cvs.texi(,13997) @c (say) 1.9.6.  Someone else reported problems with
cvs.texi(,13998) @c starting with a directory which was checked out with
cvs.texi(,13999) @c an old version, and then using a new version, and
cvs.texi(,14000) @c some "D" lines appeared, but not for every
cvs.texi(,14001) @c directory, causing some directories to be skipped.
cvs.texi(,14002) @c They weren't sure how to reproduce this, though.
cvs.texi(,14003) 
cvs.texi(,14004) @c ---------------------------------------------------------------------
cvs.texi(,14005) @node Troubleshooting
cvs.texi(,14006) @appendix Troubleshooting
cvs.texi(,14007) 
cvs.texi(,14008) If you are having trouble with @sc{cvs}, this appendix
cvs.texi(,14009) may help.  If there is a particular error message which
cvs.texi(,14010) you are seeing, then you can look up the message
cvs.texi(,14011) alphabetically.  If not, you can look through the
cvs.texi(,14012) section on other problems to see if your problem is
cvs.texi(,14013) mentioned there.
cvs.texi(,14014) 
cvs.texi(,14015) @menu
cvs.texi(,14016) * Error messages::              Partial list of CVS errors
cvs.texi(,14017) * Connection::                  Trouble making a connection to a CVS server
cvs.texi(,14018) * Other problems::              Problems not readily listed by error message
cvs.texi(,14019) @end menu
cvs.texi(,14020) 
cvs.texi(,14028) 
cvs.texi(,14029) @node Error messages
cvs.texi(,14030) @appendixsec Partial list of error messages
cvs.texi(,14031) 
cvs.texi(,14032) Here is a partial list of error messages that you may
cvs.texi(,14033) see from @sc{cvs}.  It is not a complete list---@sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,14034) is capable of printing many, many error messages, often
cvs.texi(,14035) with parts of them supplied by the operating system,
cvs.texi(,14036) but the intention is to list the common and/or
cvs.texi(,14037) potentially confusing error messages.
cvs.texi(,14038) 
cvs.texi(,14039) The messages are alphabetical, but introductory text
cvs.texi(,14040) such as @samp{cvs update: } is not considered in
cvs.texi(,14041) ordering them.
cvs.texi(,14042) 
cvs.texi(,14043) In some cases the list includes messages printed by old
cvs.texi(,14044) versions of @sc{cvs} (partly because users may not be
cvs.texi(,14045) sure which version of @sc{cvs} they are using at any
cvs.texi(,14046) particular moment).
cvs.texi(,14047) @c If we want to start retiring messages, perhaps we
cvs.texi(,14048) @c should pick a cutoff version (for example, no more
cvs.texi(,14049) @c messages which are specific to versions before 1.9)
cvs.texi(,14050) @c and then move the old messages to an "old messages"
cvs.texi(,14051) @c node rather than deleting them completely.
cvs.texi(,14052) 
cvs.texi(,14053) @table @code
cvs.texi(,14054) @c FIXME: What is the correct way to format a multiline
cvs.texi(,14055) @c error message here?  Maybe @table is the wrong
cvs.texi(,14056) @c choice?  Texinfo gurus?
cvs.texi(,14057) @item @var{file}:@var{line}: Assertion '@var{text}' failed
cvs.texi(,14058) The exact format of this message may vary depending on
cvs.texi(,14059) your system.  It indicates a bug in @sc{cvs}, which can
cvs.texi(,14060) be handled as described in @ref{BUGS}.
cvs.texi(,14061) 
cvs.texi(,14062) @item cvs @var{command}: authorization failed: server @var{host} rejected access
cvs.texi(,14063) This is a generic response when trying to connect to a
cvs.texi(,14064) pserver server which chooses not to provide a
cvs.texi(,14065) specific reason for denying authorization.  Check that
cvs.texi(,14066) the username and password specified are correct and
cvs.texi(,14067) that the @code{CVSROOT} specified is allowed by @samp{--allow-root}
cvs.texi(,14068) in @file{inetd.conf}.  See @ref{Password authenticated}.
cvs.texi(,14069) 
cvs.texi(,14070) @item cvs @var{command}: conflict: removed @var{file} was modified by second party
cvs.texi(,14071) This message indicates that you removed a file, and
cvs.texi(,14072) someone else modified it.  To resolve the conflict,
cvs.texi(,14073) first run @samp{cvs add @var{file}}.  If desired, look
cvs.texi(,14074) at the other party's modification to decide whether you
cvs.texi(,14075) still want to remove it.  If you don't want to remove
cvs.texi(,14076) it, stop here.  If you do want to remove it, proceed
cvs.texi(,14077) with @samp{cvs remove @var{file}} and commit your
cvs.texi(,14078) removal.
cvs.texi(,14079) @c Tests conflicts2-142b* in sanity.sh test for this.
cvs.texi(,14080) 
cvs.texi(,14081) @item cannot change permissions on temporary directory
cvs.texi(,14082) @example
cvs.texi(,14083) Operation not permitted
cvs.texi(,14084) @end example
cvs.texi(,14085) This message has been happening in a non-reproducible,
cvs.texi(,14086) occasional way when we run the client/server testsuite,
cvs.texi(,14087) both on Red Hat Linux 3.0.3 and 4.1.  We haven't been
cvs.texi(,14088) able to figure out what causes it, nor is it known
cvs.texi(,14089) whether it is specific to linux (or even to this
cvs.texi(,14090) particular machine!).  If the problem does occur on
cvs.texi(,14091) other unices, @samp{Operation not permitted} would be
cvs.texi(,14092) likely to read @samp{Not owner} or whatever the system
cvs.texi(,14093) in question uses for the unix @code{EPERM} error.  If
cvs.texi(,14094) you have any information to add, please let us know as
cvs.texi(,14095) described in @ref{BUGS}.  If you experience this error
cvs.texi(,14096) while using @sc{cvs}, retrying the operation which
cvs.texi(,14097) produced it should work fine.
cvs.texi(,14098) @c This has been seen in a variety of tests, including
cvs.texi(,14099) @c multibranch-2, multibranch-5, and basic1-24-rm-rm,
cvs.texi(,14100) @c so it doesn't seem particularly specific to any one
cvs.texi(,14101) @c test.
cvs.texi(,14102) 
cvs.texi(,14103) @item cvs [server aborted]: Cannot check out files into the repository itself
cvs.texi(,14104) The obvious cause for this message (especially for
cvs.texi(,14105) non-client/server @sc{cvs}) is that the @sc{cvs} root
cvs.texi(,14106) is, for example, @file{/usr/local/cvsroot} and you try
cvs.texi(,14107) to check out files when you are in a subdirectory, such
cvs.texi(,14108) as @file{/usr/local/cvsroot/test}.  However, there is a
cvs.texi(,14109) more subtle cause, which is that the temporary
cvs.texi(,14110) directory on the server is set to a subdirectory of the
cvs.texi(,14111) root (which is also not allowed).  If this is the
cvs.texi(,14112) problem, set the temporary directory to somewhere else,
cvs.texi(,14113) for example @file{/var/tmp}; see @code{TMPDIR} in
cvs.texi(,14114) @ref{Environment variables}, for how to set the
cvs.texi(,14115) temporary directory.
cvs.texi(,14116) 
cvs.texi(,14117) @item cannot commit files as 'root'
cvs.texi(,14118) See @samp{'root' is not allowed to commit files}.
cvs.texi(,14119) 
cvs.texi(,14120) @c For one example see basica-1a10 in the testsuite
cvs.texi(,14121) @c For another example, "cvs co ." on NT; see comment
cvs.texi(,14122) @c at windows-NT/filesubr.c (expand_wild).
cvs.texi(,14123) @c For another example, "cvs co foo/bar" where foo exists.
cvs.texi(,14124) @item cannot open CVS/Entries for reading: No such file or directory
cvs.texi(,14125) This generally indicates a @sc{cvs} internal error, and
cvs.texi(,14126) can be handled as with other @sc{cvs} bugs
cvs.texi(,14127) (@pxref{BUGS}).  Usually there is a workaround---the
cvs.texi(,14128) exact nature of which would depend on the situation but
cvs.texi(,14129) which hopefully could be figured out.
cvs.texi(,14130) 
cvs.texi(,14131) @c This is more obscure than it might sound; it only
cvs.texi(,14132) @c happens if you run "cvs init" from a directory which
cvs.texi(,14133) @c contains a CVS/Root file at the start.
cvs.texi(,14134) @item cvs [init aborted]: cannot open CVS/Root: No such file or directory
cvs.texi(,14135) This message is harmless.  Provided it is not
cvs.texi(,14136) accompanied by other errors, the operation has
cvs.texi(,14137) completed successfully.  This message should not occur
cvs.texi(,14138) with current versions of @sc{cvs}, but it is documented
cvs.texi(,14139) here for the benefit of @sc{cvs} 1.9 and older.
cvs.texi(,14140) 
cvs.texi(,14141) @item cvs server: cannot open /root/.cvsignore: Permission denied
cvs.texi(,14142) @itemx cvs [server aborted]: can't chdir(/root): Permission denied
cvs.texi(,14143) See @ref{Connection}.
cvs.texi(,14144) 
cvs.texi(,14145) @item cvs [checkout aborted]: cannot rename file @var{file} to CVS/,,@var{file}: Invalid argument
cvs.texi(,14146) This message has been reported as intermittently
cvs.texi(,14147) happening with @sc{cvs} 1.9 on Solaris 2.5.  The cause is
cvs.texi(,14148) unknown; if you know more about what causes it, let us
cvs.texi(,14149) know as described in @ref{BUGS}.
cvs.texi(,14150) 
cvs.texi(,14151) @item cvs [@var{command} aborted]: cannot start server via rcmd
cvs.texi(,14152) This, unfortunately, is a rather nonspecific error
cvs.texi(,14153) message which @sc{cvs} 1.9 will print if you are
cvs.texi(,14154) running the @sc{cvs} client and it is having trouble
cvs.texi(,14155) connecting to the server.  Current versions of @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,14156) should print a much more specific error message.  If
cvs.texi(,14157) you get this message when you didn't mean to run the
cvs.texi(,14158) client at all, you probably forgot to specify
cvs.texi(,14159) @code{:local:}, as described in @ref{Repository}.
cvs.texi(,14160) 
cvs.texi(,14161) @item ci: @var{file},v: bad diff output line: Binary files - and /tmp/T2a22651 differ
cvs.texi(,14162) @sc{cvs} 1.9 and older will print this message
cvs.texi(,14163) when trying to check in a binary file if
cvs.texi(,14164) @sc{rcs} is not correctly installed.  Re-read the
cvs.texi(,14165) instructions that came with your @sc{rcs} distribution
cvs.texi(,14166) and the @sc{install} file in the @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,14167) distribution.  Alternately, upgrade to a current
cvs.texi(,14168) version of @sc{cvs}, which checks in files itself
cvs.texi(,14169) rather than via @sc{rcs}.
cvs.texi(,14170) 
cvs.texi(,14171) @item cvs checkout: could not check out @var{file}
cvs.texi(,14172) With @sc{cvs} 1.9, this can mean that the @code{co} program
cvs.texi(,14173) (part of @sc{rcs}) returned a failure.  It should be
cvs.texi(,14174) preceded by another error message, however it has been
cvs.texi(,14175) observed without another error message and the cause is
cvs.texi(,14176) not well-understood.  With the current version of @sc{cvs},
cvs.texi(,14177) which does not run @code{co}, if this message occurs
cvs.texi(,14178) without another error message, it is definitely a @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,14179) bug (@pxref{BUGS}).
cvs.texi(,14180) @c My current suspicion is that the RCS in the rcs (not
cvs.texi(,14181) @c cvs/winnt/rcs57nt.zip) directory on the _Practical_
cvs.texi(,14182) @c CD is bad (remains to be confirmed).
cvs.texi(,14183) @c There is also a report of something which looks
cvs.texi(,14184) @c very similar on SGI, Irix 5.2, so I dunno.
cvs.texi(,14185) 
cvs.texi(,14186) @item cvs [login aborted]: could not find out home directory
cvs.texi(,14187) This means that you need to set the environment
cvs.texi(,14188) variables that @sc{cvs} uses to locate your home directory.
cvs.texi(,14189) See the discussion of @code{HOME}, @code{HOMEDRIVE}, and @code{HOMEPATH} in
cvs.texi(,14190) @ref{Environment variables}.
cvs.texi(,14191) 
cvs.texi(,14192) @item cvs update: could not merge revision @var{rev} of @var{file}: No such file or directory
cvs.texi(,14193) @sc{cvs} 1.9 and older will print this message if there was
cvs.texi(,14194) a problem finding the @code{rcsmerge} program.  Make
cvs.texi(,14195) sure that it is in your @code{PATH}, or upgrade to a
cvs.texi(,14196) current version of @sc{cvs}, which does not require
cvs.texi(,14197) an external @code{rcsmerge} program.
cvs.texi(,14198) 
cvs.texi(,14199) @item cvs [update aborted]: could not patch @var{file}: No such file or directory
cvs.texi(,14200) This means that there was a problem finding the
cvs.texi(,14201) @code{patch} program.  Make sure that it is in your
cvs.texi(,14202) @code{PATH}.  Note that despite appearances the message
cvs.texi(,14203) is @emph{not} referring to whether it can find @var{file}.
cvs.texi(,14204) If both the client and the server are running a current
cvs.texi(,14205) version of @sc{cvs}, then there is no need for an
cvs.texi(,14206) external patch program and you should not see this
cvs.texi(,14207) message.  But if either client or server is running
cvs.texi(,14208) @sc{cvs} 1.9, then you need @code{patch}.
cvs.texi(,14209) 
cvs.texi(,14210) @item cvs update: could not patch @var{file}; will refetch
cvs.texi(,14211) This means that for whatever reason the client was
cvs.texi(,14212) unable to apply a patch that the server sent.  The
cvs.texi(,14213) message is nothing to be concerned about, because
cvs.texi(,14214) inability to apply the patch only slows things down and
cvs.texi(,14215) has no effect on what @sc{cvs} does.
cvs.texi(,14216) @c xref to update output.  Or File status?
cvs.texi(,14217) @c Or some place else that
cvs.texi(,14218) @c explains this whole "patch"/P/Needs Patch thing?
cvs.texi(,14219) 
cvs.texi(,14220) @item dying gasps from @var{server} unexpected
cvs.texi(,14221) There is a known bug in the server for @sc{cvs} 1.9.18
cvs.texi(,14222) and older which can cause this.  For me, this was
cvs.texi(,14223) reproducible if I used the @samp{-t} global option.  It
cvs.texi(,14224) was fixed by Andy Piper's 14 Nov 1997 change to
cvs.texi(,14225) src/filesubr.c, if anyone is curious.
cvs.texi(,14226) If you see the message,
cvs.texi(,14227) you probably can just retry the operation which failed,
cvs.texi(,14228) or if you have discovered information concerning its
cvs.texi(,14229) cause, please let us know as described in @ref{BUGS}.
cvs.texi(,14230) 
cvs.texi(,14231) @item end of file from server (consult above messages if any)
cvs.texi(,14232) The most common cause for this message is if you are
cvs.texi(,14233) using an external @code{rsh} program and it exited with
cvs.texi(,14234) an error.  In this case the @code{rsh} program should
cvs.texi(,14235) have printed a message, which will appear before the
cvs.texi(,14236) above message.  For more information on setting up a
cvs.texi(,14237) @sc{cvs} client and server, see @ref{Remote repositories}.
cvs.texi(,14238) 
cvs.texi(,14239) @item cvs [update aborted]: EOF in key in RCS file @var{file},v
cvs.texi(,14240) @itemx cvs [checkout aborted]: EOF while looking for end of string in RCS file @var{file},v
cvs.texi(,14241) This means that there is a syntax error in the given
cvs.texi(,14242) @sc{rcs} file.  Note that this might be true even if @sc{rcs} can
cvs.texi(,14243) read the file OK; @sc{cvs} does more error checking of
cvs.texi(,14244) errors in the RCS file.  That is why you may see this
cvs.texi(,14245) message when upgrading from @sc{cvs} 1.9 to @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,14246) 1.10.  The likely cause for the original corruption is
cvs.texi(,14247) hardware, the operating system, or the like.  Of
cvs.texi(,14248) course, if you find a case in which @sc{cvs} seems to
cvs.texi(,14249) corrupting the file, by all means report it,
cvs.texi(,14250) (@pxref{BUGS}).
cvs.texi(,14251) There are quite a few variations of this error message,
cvs.texi(,14252) depending on exactly where in the @sc{rcs} file @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,14253) finds the syntax error.
cvs.texi(,14254) 
cvs.texi(,14255) @cindex mkmodules
cvs.texi(,14256) @item cvs commit: Executing 'mkmodules'
cvs.texi(,14257) This means that your repository is set up for a version
cvs.texi(,14258) of @sc{cvs} prior to @sc{cvs} 1.8.  When using @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,14259) 1.8 or later, the above message will be preceded by
cvs.texi(,14260) 
cvs.texi(,14261) @example
cvs.texi(,14262) cvs commit: Rebuilding administrative file database
cvs.texi(,14263) @end example
cvs.texi(,14264) 
cvs.texi(,14265) If you see both messages, the database is being rebuilt
cvs.texi(,14266) twice, which is unnecessary but harmless.  If you wish
cvs.texi(,14267) to avoid the duplication, and you have no versions of
cvs.texi(,14268) @sc{cvs} 1.7 or earlier in use, remove @code{-i mkmodules}
cvs.texi(,14269) every place it appears in your @code{modules}
cvs.texi(,14270) file.  For more information on the @code{modules} file,
cvs.texi(,14271) see @ref{modules}.
cvs.texi(,14272) 
cvs.texi(,14273) @c This message comes from "co", and I believe is
cvs.texi(,14274) @c possible only with older versions of CVS which call
cvs.texi(,14275) @c co.  The problem with being able to create the bogus
cvs.texi(,14276) @c RCS file still exists, though (and I think maybe
cvs.texi(,14277) @c there is a different symptom(s) now).
cvs.texi(,14278) @c FIXME: Would be nice to have a more exact wording
cvs.texi(,14279) @c for this message.
cvs.texi(,14280) @item missing author
cvs.texi(,14281) Typically this can happen if you created an RCS file
cvs.texi(,14282) with your username set to empty.  @sc{cvs} will, bogusly,
cvs.texi(,14283) create an illegal RCS file with no value for the author
cvs.texi(,14284) field.  The solution is to make sure your username is
cvs.texi(,14285) set to a non-empty value and re-create the RCS file.
cvs.texi(,14286) @c "make sure your username is set" is complicated in
cvs.texi(,14287) @c and of itself, as there are the environment
cvs.texi(,14288) @c variables the system login name, &c, and it depends
cvs.texi(,14289) @c on the version of CVS.
cvs.texi(,14290) 
cvs.texi(,14291) @item cvs [checkout aborted]: no such tag @var{tag}
cvs.texi(,14292) This message means that @sc{cvs} isn't familiar with
cvs.texi(,14293) the tag @var{tag}.  Usually this means that you have
cvs.texi(,14294) mistyped a tag name; however there are (relatively
cvs.texi(,14295) obscure) cases in which @sc{cvs} will require you to
cvs.texi(,14296) @c Search sanity.sh for "no such tag" to see some of
cvs.texi(,14297) @c the relatively obscure cases.
cvs.texi(,14298) try a few other @sc{cvs} commands involving that tag,
cvs.texi(,14299) before you find one which will cause @sc{cvs} to update
cvs.texi(,14300) the @file{val-tags} file; see discussion of val-tags in
cvs.texi(,14301) @ref{File permissions}.  You only need to worry about
cvs.texi(,14302) this once for a given tag; when a tag is listed in
cvs.texi(,14303) @file{val-tags}, it stays there.  Note that using
cvs.texi(,14304) @samp{-f} to not require tag matches does not override
cvs.texi(,14305) this check; see @ref{Common options}.
cvs.texi(,14306) 
cvs.texi(,14307) @item *PANIC* administration files missing
cvs.texi(,14308) This typically means that there is a directory named
cvs.texi(,14309) @sc{cvs} but it does not contain the administrative files
cvs.texi(,14310) which @sc{cvs} puts in a CVS directory.  If the problem is
cvs.texi(,14311) that you created a CVS directory via some mechanism
cvs.texi(,14312) other than @sc{cvs}, then the answer is simple, use a name
cvs.texi(,14313) other than @sc{cvs}.  If not, it indicates a @sc{cvs} bug
cvs.texi(,14314) (@pxref{BUGS}).
cvs.texi(,14315) 
cvs.texi(,14316) @item rcs error: Unknown option: -x,v/
cvs.texi(,14317) This message will be followed by a usage message for
cvs.texi(,14318) @sc{rcs}.  It means that you have an old version of
cvs.texi(,14319) @sc{rcs} (probably supplied with your operating
cvs.texi(,14320) system), as well as an old version of @sc{cvs}.
cvs.texi(,14321) @sc{cvs} 1.9.18 and earlier only work with @sc{rcs} version 5 and
cvs.texi(,14322) later; current versions of @sc{cvs} do not run @sc{rcs} programs.
cvs.texi(,14323) @c For more information on installing @sc{cvs}, see
cvs.texi(,14324) @c (FIXME: where?  it depends on whether you are
cvs.texi(,14325) @c getting binaries or sources or what).
cvs.texi(,14326) @c The message can also say "ci error" or something
cvs.texi(,14327) @c instead of "rcs error", I suspect.
cvs.texi(,14328) 
cvs.texi(,14329) @item cvs [server aborted]: received broken pipe signal
cvs.texi(,14330) This message seems to be caused by a hard-to-track-down
cvs.texi(,14331) bug in @sc{cvs} or the systems it runs on (we don't
cvs.texi(,14332) know---we haven't tracked it down yet!).  It seems to
cvs.texi(,14333) happen only after a @sc{cvs} command has completed, and
cvs.texi(,14334) you should be able to just ignore the message.
cvs.texi(,14335) However, if you have discovered information concerning its
cvs.texi(,14336) cause, please let us know as described in @ref{BUGS}.
cvs.texi(,14337) 
cvs.texi(,14338) @item 'root' is not allowed to commit files
cvs.texi(,14339) When committing a permanent change, @sc{cvs} makes a log entry of
cvs.texi(,14340) who committed the change.  If you are committing the change logged
cvs.texi(,14341) in as "root" (not under "su" or other root-priv giving program),
cvs.texi(,14342) @sc{cvs} cannot determine who is actually making the change.
cvs.texi(,14343) As such, by default, @sc{cvs} disallows changes to be committed by users
cvs.texi(,14344) logged in as "root".  (You can disable this option by passing the
cvs.texi(,14345) @code{--enable-rootcommit} option to @file{configure} and recompiling @sc{cvs}.
cvs.texi(,14346) On some systems this means editing the appropriate @file{config.h} file
cvs.texi(,14347) before building @sc{cvs}.)
cvs.texi(,14348) 
cvs.texi(,14349) @item Too many arguments!
cvs.texi(,14350) This message is typically printed by the @file{log.pl}
cvs.texi(,14351) script which is in the @file{contrib} directory in the
cvs.texi(,14352) @sc{cvs} source distribution.  In some versions of
cvs.texi(,14353) @sc{cvs}, @file{log.pl} has been part of the default
cvs.texi(,14354) @sc{cvs} installation.  The @file{log.pl} script gets
cvs.texi(,14355) called from the @file{loginfo} administrative file.
cvs.texi(,14356) Check that the arguments passed in @file{loginfo} match
cvs.texi(,14357) what your version of @file{log.pl} expects.  In
cvs.texi(,14358) particular, the @file{log.pl} from @sc{cvs} 1.3 and
cvs.texi(,14359) older expects the logfile as an argument whereas the
cvs.texi(,14360) @file{log.pl} from @sc{cvs} 1.5 and newer expects the
cvs.texi(,14361) logfile to be specified with a @samp{-f} option.  Of
cvs.texi(,14362) course, if you don't need @file{log.pl} you can just
cvs.texi(,14363) comment it out of @file{loginfo}.
cvs.texi(,14364) 
cvs.texi(,14365) @item cvs [update aborted]: unexpected EOF reading @var{file},v
cvs.texi(,14366) See @samp{EOF in key in RCS file}.
cvs.texi(,14367) 
cvs.texi(,14368) @item cvs [login aborted]: unrecognized auth response from @var{server}
cvs.texi(,14369) This message typically means that the server is not set
cvs.texi(,14370) up properly.  For example, if @file{inetd.conf} points
cvs.texi(,14371) to a nonexistent cvs executable.  To debug it further,
cvs.texi(,14372) find the log file which inetd writes
cvs.texi(,14373) (@file{/var/log/messages} or whatever inetd uses on
cvs.texi(,14374) your system).  For details, see @ref{Connection}, and
cvs.texi(,14375) @ref{Password authentication server}.
cvs.texi(,14376) 
cvs.texi(,14377) @item cvs commit: Up-to-date check failed for `@var{file}'
cvs.texi(,14378) This means that someone else has committed a change to
cvs.texi(,14379) that file since the last time that you did a @code{cvs
cvs.texi(,14380) update}.  So before proceeding with your @code{cvs
cvs.texi(,14381) commit} you need to @code{cvs update}.  @sc{cvs} will merge
cvs.texi(,14382) the changes that you made and the changes that the
cvs.texi(,14383) other person made.  If it does not detect any conflicts
cvs.texi(,14384) it will report @samp{M @var{file}} and you are ready
cvs.texi(,14385) to @code{cvs commit}.  If it detects conflicts it will
cvs.texi(,14386) print a message saying so, will report @samp{C @var{file}},
cvs.texi(,14387) and you need to manually resolve the
cvs.texi(,14388) conflict.  For more details on this process see
cvs.texi(,14389) @ref{Conflicts example}.
cvs.texi(,14390) 
cvs.texi(,14391) @item Usage:	diff3 [-exEX3 [-i | -m] [-L label1 -L label3]] file1 file2 file3
cvs.texi(,14392) @example
cvs.texi(,14393) Only one of [exEX3] allowed
cvs.texi(,14394) @end example
cvs.texi(,14395) This indicates a problem with the installation of
cvs.texi(,14396) @code{diff3} and @code{rcsmerge}.  Specifically
cvs.texi(,14397) @code{rcsmerge} was compiled to look for GNU diff3, but
cvs.texi(,14398) it is finding unix diff3 instead.  The exact text of
cvs.texi(,14399) the message will vary depending on the system.  The
cvs.texi(,14400) simplest solution is to upgrade to a current version of
cvs.texi(,14401) @sc{cvs}, which does not rely on external
cvs.texi(,14402) @code{rcsmerge} or @code{diff3} programs.
cvs.texi(,14403) 
cvs.texi(,14404) @item warning: unrecognized response `@var{text}' from cvs server
cvs.texi(,14405) If @var{text} contains a valid response (such as
cvs.texi(,14406) @samp{ok}) followed by an extra carriage return
cvs.texi(,14407) character (on many systems this will cause the second
cvs.texi(,14408) part of the message to overwrite the first part), then
cvs.texi(,14409) it probably means that you are using the @samp{:ext:}
cvs.texi(,14410) access method with a version of rsh, such as most
cvs.texi(,14411) non-unix rsh versions, which does not by default
cvs.texi(,14412) provide a transparent data stream.  In such cases you
cvs.texi(,14413) probably want to try @samp{:server:} instead of
cvs.texi(,14414) @samp{:ext:}.  If @var{text} is something else, this
cvs.texi(,14415) may signify a problem with your @sc{cvs} server.
cvs.texi(,14416) Double-check your installation against the instructions
cvs.texi(,14417) for setting up the @sc{cvs} server.
cvs.texi(,14418) @c FIXCVS: should be printing CR as \r or \015 or some
cvs.texi(,14419) @c such, probably.
cvs.texi(,14420) 
cvs.texi(,14421) @item cvs commit: [@var{time}] waiting for @var{user}'s lock in @var{directory}
cvs.texi(,14422) This is a normal message, not an error.  See
cvs.texi(,14423) @ref{Concurrency}, for more details.
cvs.texi(,14424) 
cvs.texi(,14425) @item cvs commit: warning: editor session failed
cvs.texi(,14426) @cindex Exit status, of editor
cvs.texi(,14427) This means that the editor which @sc{cvs} is using exits with a nonzero
cvs.texi(,14428) exit status.  Some versions of vi will do this even when there was not
cvs.texi(,14429) a problem editing the file.  If so, point the
cvs.texi(,14430) @code{CVSEDITOR} environment variable to a small script
cvs.texi(,14431) such as:
cvs.texi(,14432) 
cvs.texi(,14433) @example
cvs.texi(,14434) #!/bin/sh
cvs.texi(,14435) vi $*
cvs.texi(,14436) exit 0
cvs.texi(,14437) @end example
cvs.texi(,14438) 
cvs.texi(,14439) @c "warning: foo was lost" and "no longer pertinent" (both normal).
cvs.texi(,14440) @c Would be nice to write these up--they are
cvs.texi(,14441) @c potentially confusing for the new user.
cvs.texi(,14442) @end table
cvs.texi(,14443) 
cvs.texi(,14444) @node Connection
cvs.texi(,14445) @appendixsec Trouble making a connection to a CVS server
cvs.texi(,14446) 
cvs.texi(,14447) This section concerns what to do if you are having
cvs.texi(,14448) trouble making a connection to a @sc{cvs} server.  If
cvs.texi(,14449) you are running the @sc{cvs} command line client
cvs.texi(,14450) running on Windows, first upgrade the client to
cvs.texi(,14451) @sc{cvs} 1.9.12 or later.  The error reporting in
cvs.texi(,14452) earlier versions provided much less information about
cvs.texi(,14453) what the problem was.  If the client is non-Windows,
cvs.texi(,14454) @sc{cvs} 1.9 should be fine.
cvs.texi(,14455) 
cvs.texi(,14456) If the error messages are not sufficient to track down
cvs.texi(,14457) the problem, the next steps depend largely on which
cvs.texi(,14458) access method you are using.
cvs.texi(,14459) 
cvs.texi(,14460) @table @code
cvs.texi(,14461) @cindex :ext:, troubleshooting
cvs.texi(,14462) @item :ext:
cvs.texi(,14463) Try running the rsh program from the command line.  For
cvs.texi(,14464) example: "rsh servername cvs -v" should print @sc{cvs}
cvs.texi(,14465) version information.  If this doesn't work, you need to
cvs.texi(,14466) fix it before you can worry about @sc{cvs} problems.
cvs.texi(,14467) 
cvs.texi(,14468) @cindex :server:, troubleshooting
cvs.texi(,14469) @item :server:
cvs.texi(,14470) You don't need a command line rsh program to use this
cvs.texi(,14471) access method, but if you have an rsh program around,
cvs.texi(,14472) it may be useful as a debugging tool.  Follow the
cvs.texi(,14473) directions given for :ext:.
cvs.texi(,14474) 
cvs.texi(,14475) @cindex :pserver:, troubleshooting
cvs.texi(,14476) @item :pserver:
cvs.texi(,14477) Errors along the lines of "connection refused" typically indicate
cvs.texi(,14478) that inetd isn't even listening for connections on port 2401
cvs.texi(,14479) whereas errors like "connection reset by peer",
cvs.texi(,14480) "received broken pipe signal", "recv() from server: EOF",
cvs.texi(,14481) or "end of file from server"
cvs.texi(,14482) typically indicate that inetd is listening for
cvs.texi(,14483) connections but is unable to start @sc{cvs} (this is frequently
cvs.texi(,14484) caused by having an incorrect path in @file{inetd.conf}
cvs.texi(,14485) or by firewall software rejecting the connection).
cvs.texi(,14486) "unrecognized auth response" errors are caused by a bad command
cvs.texi(,14487) line in @file{inetd.conf}, typically an invalid option or forgetting
cvs.texi(,14488) to put the @samp{pserver} command at the end of the line.
cvs.texi(,14489) Another less common problem is invisible control characters that
cvs.texi(,14490) your editor "helpfully" added without you noticing.
cvs.texi(,14491) 
cvs.texi(,14492) One good debugging tool is to "telnet servername
cvs.texi(,14493) 2401".  After connecting, send any text (for example
cvs.texi(,14494) "foo" followed by return).  If @sc{cvs} is working
cvs.texi(,14495) correctly, it will respond with
cvs.texi(,14496) 
cvs.texi(,14497) @example
cvs.texi(,14498) cvs [pserver aborted]: bad auth protocol start: foo
cvs.texi(,14499) @end example
cvs.texi(,14500) 
cvs.texi(,14501) If instead you get:
cvs.texi(,14502) 
cvs.texi(,14503) @example
cvs.texi(,14504) Usage: cvs [cvs-options] command [command-options-and-arguments]
cvs.texi(,14505) ...
cvs.texi(,14506) @end example
cvs.texi(,14507) 
cvs.texi(,14508) @noindent
cvs.texi(,14509) then you're missing the @samp{pserver} command at the end of the
cvs.texi(,14510) line in @file{inetd.conf}; check to make sure that the entire command
cvs.texi(,14511) is on one line and that it's complete.
cvs.texi(,14512) 
cvs.texi(,14513) Likewise, if you get something like:
cvs.texi(,14514) 
cvs.texi(,14515) @example
cvs.texi(,14516) Unknown command: `pserved'
cvs.texi(,14517) 
cvs.texi(,14518) CVS commands are:
cvs.texi(,14519)         add          Add a new file/directory to the repository
cvs.texi(,14520) ...
cvs.texi(,14521) @end example
cvs.texi(,14522) 
cvs.texi(,14523) @noindent
cvs.texi(,14524) then you've misspelled @samp{pserver} in some way.  If it isn't
cvs.texi(,14525) obvious, check for invisible control characters (particularly
cvs.texi(,14526) carriage returns) in @file{inetd.conf}.
cvs.texi(,14527) 
cvs.texi(,14528) If it fails to work at all, then make sure inetd is working
cvs.texi(,14529) right.  Change the invocation in @file{inetd.conf} to run the
cvs.texi(,14530) echo program instead of cvs.  For example:
cvs.texi(,14531) 
cvs.texi(,14532) @example
cvs.texi(,14533) 2401  stream  tcp  nowait  root /bin/echo echo hello
cvs.texi(,14534) @end example
cvs.texi(,14535) 
cvs.texi(,14536) After making that change and instructing inetd to
cvs.texi(,14537) re-read its configuration file, "telnet servername
cvs.texi(,14538) 2401" should show you the text hello and then the
cvs.texi(,14539) server should close the connection.  If this doesn't
cvs.texi(,14540) work, you need to fix it before you can worry about
cvs.texi(,14541) @sc{cvs} problems.
cvs.texi(,14542) 
cvs.texi(,14543) On AIX systems, the system will often have its own
cvs.texi(,14544) program trying to use port 2401.  This is AIX's problem
cvs.texi(,14545) in the sense that port 2401 is registered for use with
cvs.texi(,14546) @sc{cvs}.  I hear that there is an AIX patch available
cvs.texi(,14547) to address this problem.
cvs.texi(,14548) 
cvs.texi(,14549) Another good debugging tool is the @samp{-d}
cvs.texi(,14550) (debugging) option to inetd.  Consult your system
cvs.texi(,14551) documentation for more information.
cvs.texi(,14552) 
cvs.texi(,14553) If you seem to be connecting but get errors like:
cvs.texi(,14554) 
cvs.texi(,14555) @example
cvs.texi(,14556) cvs server: cannot open /root/.cvsignore: Permission denied
cvs.texi(,14557) cvs [server aborted]: can't chdir(/root): Permission denied
cvs.texi(,14558) @end example
cvs.texi(,14559) 
cvs.texi(,14560) @noindent
cvs.texi(,14561) then you probably haven't specified @samp{-f} in @file{inetd.conf}.
cvs.texi(,14562) (In releases prior to @sc{cvs} 1.11.1, this problem can be caused by
cvs.texi(,14563) your system setting the @code{$HOME} environment variable
cvs.texi(,14564) for programs being run by inetd.  In this case, you can either
cvs.texi(,14565) have inetd run a shell script that unsets @code{$HOME} and then runs
cvs.texi(,14566) @sc{cvs}, or you can use @code{env} to run @sc{cvs} with a pristine
cvs.texi(,14567) environment.)
cvs.texi(,14568) 
cvs.texi(,14569) If you can connect successfully for a while but then can't,
cvs.texi(,14570) you've probably hit inetd's rate limit.
cvs.texi(,14571) (If inetd receives too many requests for the same service
cvs.texi(,14572) in a short period of time, it assumes that something is wrong
cvs.texi(,14573) and temporarily disables the service.)
cvs.texi(,14574) Check your inetd documentation to find out how to adjust the
cvs.texi(,14575) rate limit (some versions of inetd have a single rate limit,
cvs.texi(,14576) others allow you to set the limit for each service separately.)
cvs.texi(,14577) @end table
cvs.texi(,14578) 
cvs.texi(,14579) @node Other problems
cvs.texi(,14580) @appendixsec Other common problems
cvs.texi(,14581) 
cvs.texi(,14582) Here is a list of problems which do not fit into the
cvs.texi(,14583) above categories.  They are in no particular order.
cvs.texi(,14584) 
cvs.texi(,14585) @itemize @bullet
cvs.texi(,14586) @item
cvs.texi(,14587) On Windows, if there is a 30 second or so delay when
cvs.texi(,14588) you run a @sc{cvs} command, it may mean that you have
cvs.texi(,14589) your home directory set to @file{C:/}, for example (see
cvs.texi(,14590) @code{HOMEDRIVE} and @code{HOMEPATH} in
cvs.texi(,14591) @ref{Environment variables}).  @sc{cvs} expects the home
cvs.texi(,14592) directory to not end in a slash, for example @file{C:}
cvs.texi(,14593) or @file{C:\cvs}.
cvs.texi(,14594) @c FIXCVS: CVS should at least detect this and print an
cvs.texi(,14595) @c error, presumably.
cvs.texi(,14596) 
cvs.texi(,14597) @item
cvs.texi(,14598) If you are running @sc{cvs} 1.9.18 or older, and
cvs.texi(,14599) @code{cvs update} finds a conflict and tries to
cvs.texi(,14600) merge, as described in @ref{Conflicts example}, but
cvs.texi(,14601) doesn't tell you there were conflicts, then you may
cvs.texi(,14602) have an old version of @sc{rcs}.  The easiest solution
cvs.texi(,14603) probably is to upgrade to a current version of
cvs.texi(,14604) @sc{cvs}, which does not rely on external @sc{rcs}
cvs.texi(,14605) programs.
cvs.texi(,14606) @end itemize
