cvs.texi(,14654) @node BUGS
cvs.texi(,14655) @appendix Dealing with bugs in CVS or this manual
cvs.texi(,14656) 
cvs.texi(,14657) @cindex Bugs in this manual or CVS
cvs.texi(,14658) Neither @sc{cvs} nor this manual is perfect, and they
cvs.texi(,14659) probably never will be.  If you are having trouble
cvs.texi(,14660) using @sc{cvs}, or think you have found a bug, there
cvs.texi(,14661) are a number of things you can do about it.  Note that
cvs.texi(,14662) if the manual is unclear, that can be considered a bug
cvs.texi(,14663) in the manual, so these problems are often worth doing
cvs.texi(,14664) something about as well as problems with @sc{cvs} itself.
cvs.texi(,14665) 
cvs.texi(,14666) @cindex Reporting bugs
cvs.texi(,14667) @cindex Bugs, reporting
cvs.texi(,14668) @cindex Errors, reporting
cvs.texi(,14669) @itemize @bullet
cvs.texi(,14670) @item
cvs.texi(,14671) If you want someone to help you and fix bugs that you
cvs.texi(,14672) report, there are companies which will do that for a
cvs.texi(,14673) fee.  One such company is:
cvs.texi(,14674) 
cvs.texi(,14675) @cindex Ximbiot
cvs.texi(,14676) @cindex Support, getting CVS support
cvs.texi(,14677) @example
cvs.texi(,14678) Ximbiot
cvs.texi(,14679) 319 S. River St.
cvs.texi(,14680) Harrisburg, PA  17104-1657
cvs.texi(,14681) USA
cvs.texi(,14682) Email: info@@ximbiot.com
cvs.texi(,14683) Phone: (717) 579-6168
cvs.texi(,14684) Fax:   (717) 234-3125
cvs.texi(,14685) http://ximbiot.com/
cvs.texi(,14686) 
cvs.texi(,14687) @end example
cvs.texi(,14688) 
cvs.texi(,14689) @item
cvs.texi(,14690) If you got @sc{cvs} through a distributor, such as an
cvs.texi(,14691) operating system vendor or a vendor of freeware
cvs.texi(,14692) @sc{cd-rom}s, you may wish to see whether the
cvs.texi(,14693) distributor provides support.  Often, they will provide
cvs.texi(,14694) no support or minimal support, but this may vary from
cvs.texi(,14695) distributor to distributor.
cvs.texi(,14696) 
cvs.texi(,14697) @item
cvs.texi(,14698) If you have the skills and time to do so, you may wish
cvs.texi(,14699) to fix the bug yourself.  If you wish to submit your
cvs.texi(,14700) fix for inclusion in future releases of @sc{cvs}, see
cvs.texi(,14701) the file @sc{hacking} in the @sc{cvs} source
cvs.texi(,14702) distribution.  It contains much more information on the
cvs.texi(,14703) process of submitting fixes.
cvs.texi(,14704) 
cvs.texi(,14705) @item
cvs.texi(,14706) There may be resources on the net which can help.  Two
cvs.texi(,14707) good places to start are:
cvs.texi(,14708) 
cvs.texi(,14709) @example
cvs.texi(,14710) http://www.cvshome.org
cvs.texi(,14711) http://www.loria.fr/~molli/cvs-index.html
cvs.texi(,14712) @end example
cvs.texi(,14713) 
cvs.texi(,14714) If you are so inspired, increasing the information
cvs.texi(,14715) available on the net is likely to be appreciated.  For
cvs.texi(,14716) example, before the standard @sc{cvs} distribution
cvs.texi(,14717) worked on Windows 95, there was a web page with some
cvs.texi(,14718) explanation and patches for running @sc{cvs} on Windows
cvs.texi(,14719) 95, and various people helped out by mentioning this
cvs.texi(,14720) page on mailing lists or newsgroups when the subject
cvs.texi(,14721) came up.
cvs.texi(,14722) 
cvs.texi(,14723) @item
cvs.texi(,14724) It is also possible to report bugs to @code{bug-cvs}.
cvs.texi(,14725) Note that someone may or may not want to do anything
cvs.texi(,14726) with your bug report---if you need a solution consider
cvs.texi(,14727) one of the options mentioned above.  People probably do
cvs.texi(,14728) want to hear about bugs which are particularly severe
cvs.texi(,14729) in consequences and/or easy to fix, however.  You can
cvs.texi(,14730) also increase your odds by being as clear as possible
cvs.texi(,14731) about the exact nature of the bug and any other
cvs.texi(,14732) relevant information.  The way to report bugs is to
cvs.texi(,14733) send email to @code{bug-cvs@@gnu.org}.  Note
cvs.texi(,14734) that submissions to @code{bug-cvs} may be distributed
cvs.texi(,14735) under the terms of the @sc{gnu} Public License, so if
cvs.texi(,14736) you don't like this, don't submit them.  There is
cvs.texi(,14737) usually no justification for sending mail directly to
cvs.texi(,14738) one of the @sc{cvs} maintainers rather than to
cvs.texi(,14739) @code{bug-cvs}; those maintainers who want to hear
cvs.texi(,14740) about such bug reports read @code{bug-cvs}.  Also note
cvs.texi(,14741) that sending a bug report to other mailing lists or
cvs.texi(,14742) newsgroups is @emph{not} a substitute for sending it to
cvs.texi(,14743) @code{bug-cvs}.  It is fine to discuss @sc{cvs} bugs on
cvs.texi(,14744) whatever forum you prefer, but there are not
cvs.texi(,14745) necessarily any maintainers reading bug reports sent
cvs.texi(,14746) anywhere except @code{bug-cvs}.
cvs.texi(,14747) @end itemize
cvs.texi(,14748) 
cvs.texi(,14749) @cindex Known bugs in this manual or CVS
cvs.texi(,14750) People often ask if there is a list of known bugs or
cvs.texi(,14751) whether a particular bug is a known one.  The file
cvs.texi(,14752) @sc{bugs} in the @sc{cvs} source distribution is one
cvs.texi(,14753) list of known bugs, but it doesn't necessarily try to
cvs.texi(,14754) be comprehensive.  Perhaps there will never be a
cvs.texi(,14755) comprehensive, detailed list of known bugs.
cvs.texi(,14756) 
